<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Jamaica-Election     02-13 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamaica-Election,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Image for Jamaica and Michael Manley</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In returning Michael Manley to power,
Jamaicans opted for a new style of leadership, decisively rejecting
the tough economic solutions and autocratic demeanor of conservative
incumbent Edward Seaga.
   The island also emerged from its short but tense election
campaign with an improved record on controlling political violence.
   Preliminary indications were that the charismatic Manley, a
radical-turned-moderate leader with a new pro-business image, won 44
of 60 seats in Parliament in Thursday's voting.
   Jamaica's leading political analyst and pollster, Carl Stone of
the University of the West Indies, said he thought there would be no
fundamental policy shifts under Manley, who was prime minister from
1972 to 1980.
   ``There will be the same policies, but a different style of
leadership,'' Stone said. ``He really feels obsessed with correcting
his mismanagement during the 1970s.''
   Seaga, a technocrat and hard-nosed manager, was regarded as a
friend of big business, which is wary of Manley.
   ``There definitely are going to be memories of what happened in
the past,'' said Peter Thwaites, president of the Private Sector
Organization of Jamaica, the country's main business group. But he
said if Manley carries out his current proposals, ``there will be
very little change in the economic policies of the country.''
   Manley appropriated private farms and heavily taxed business
during his previous government. Now, he says he has ``abandoned all
thoughts of nationalization'' and wants to give private enterprise a
free hand in developing the economy.
   Seaga improved the island's economy, especially tourism, but he
did it by doubling the foreign debt to about $4 billion, raising
taxes, laying off thousands of workers and cutting back spending on
health and education.
   Prices rose sharply, leading to food riots in 1985.
   ``The program he (Seaga) has carried out has been very rigid,''
said Stone. ``And he's paying the price for it.''
   Seaga, a staunch ally of the United States and close political
friend of Ronald Reagan, said he was afraid the results of his
economic measures had not reached enough people.
   ``You see the results, yes, but the results have not reached
enough people, (so) that enough people will say `Yes, well, we took
the medicine and we've benefited,''' he said recently.
   He said he was forced to take unpopular measures because of the
near-bankrupt state of the economy when he took office in 1980 after
eight years of Manley rule and the collapse of the bauxite industry
in 1983.
   He said younger voters had no memories of how bad things were
under Manley.
   Manley, known by his most ardent supporters as ``Joshua'' after
the Old Testament prophet, pledged to revitalize schools and
hospitals he said were neglected for eight years under Seaga's
cost-cutting administration.
   As prime minister, Manley gained an international reputation as a
firebrand socialist. He forged close ties with Cuba's Fidel Castro
and brought in scores of Cuban doctors and technicians.
   In recent years, he has turned sharply to the political center as
a social democrat. The 64-year-old leader has been saying he is an
older and wiser man, and on election night Thursday he thanked the
Jamaican people for giving him a ``second chance.''
   Manley said he would restore relations with Cuba but was more
interested in working with the Bush administration and Western
lending institutions such as the International Monetary Fund and the
World Bank.
   He said his first foreign trip as prime minister will be to
Washington to establish ``the widest and most constructive''
relationship possible with the new administration.
   The Bush administration won't be pleased that Manley is reopening
the Cuban Embassy, which was closed by Seaga, but U.S. officials say
they are encouraged by Manley's pledge to limit the Cuban presence
and influence to formal diplomatic ties.
   Policy issues were overshadowed during the campaign by fears that
bloodshed among rival political supporters would further split the
nation of 2.4 million and wreck tourism, which brings in $600
million a year and is Jamaica's top earner of foreign exchange.
   The tourism industry still is recovering from a sharp drop in
visitors in the aftermath of Hurricane Gilbert, which slammed into
the island Sept. 12, killing 45 people and causing $1 billion in
damage.
   In 1980, when Jamaica's last nationally contested election was
held, an estimated 700 people were murdered over a nine-month
campaign. This time, 13 died in campaign-related shootings and
stabbings.
   But in comparison with the mayhem of 1980, the election appeared
to mark a turning point in Jamaican politics.
</TEXT>
