<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay-Adjusting     02-13 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay-Adjusting,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraguayans Adjust To Political Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gunfire has stopped, the dictator
is gone and the celebrating is over. Paraguayans now must get down
to the business of adjusting to life without the only president most
of them have ever known.
   On the surface, the future looks brighter for this South American
nation of nearly 4 million _ holding promises of new leadership and
perhaps a more representative government.
   The likelihood that another general will replace ousted leader
Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, now in exile in neighboring Brazil, bothers
few Paraguayans.
   Neither does the certainty that political power will remain in
the hands of the ruling Colorado Party, a pillar of Stroessner's
support throughout his nearly 35 years in power.
   ``It doesn't make any difference what kind of government we get,
it has to be better than the one we had,'' said 20-year-old Celso
Gonzalez, one of the thousands of citizens who went into the street
to celebrate the fall of the 76-year-old dictator.
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, whose tanks and troops ousted Stroessner
in a violent coup Feb. 3, seems to be many things his predecessor
was not.
   Rodriguez quickly dissolved Congress and called for elections May
1 in which all parties _ except the Communists _ can participate. He
promised to respect human rights, freedom of expression and the
Roman Catholic Church.
   He named an 11-man Cabinet that even opposition members
grudgingly admit includes Paraguay's most successful and talented
administrators and technocrats.
   The new government will have to deal with urgent problems,
including poverty, economic stagnation, 30 percent annual inflation
and a foreign debt of nearly $2 billion.
   The church, which had become a leading opposition body in this
predominantly Roman Catholic nation, promised the new president its
support.
   Rodriguez, 65, has denied rumors he may be linked to drug
traffickers who move cocaine through Paraguay, and he pledged to
cooperate with the United States and international agencies seeking
to end the drug trade.
   In Paraguay's first presidential press conference, the affable,
self-assured cavalry general left open the possibility he may run
for president.
   ``I am simply a soldier, not a politician,'' Rodriguez told
reporters. ``However, if I can be useful to my country, I will do
what I am asked.''
   Luis Maria Argana, the new foreign minister who was seen as the
party's most likely presidential choice, quickly denied reports he
would run and endorsed Rodriguez.
   The Colorado Party, which claims membership of 1.4 million and
has ruled since 1947, has said it will call a convention soon to
select candidates and new party leaders.
   The 101-year-old party was badly split in August 1987 when a
small but fanatical pro-Stroessner group usurped party leadership in
a battle over how to prepare for post-Stroessner rule.
   The Stroessner backers, an inner circle of militant government
and party officials, favored continuation of hard-line authoritarian
rule, possibly under Stroessner's eldest son, Gustavo, an air force
colonel.
   The majority, calling themselves ``traditionalists,'' favored
some relaxation of iron rule and the eventual replacement of
Stroessner with a civilian president.
   Recently, the situation was complicated by Stroessner's failing
health. The nation, accustomed to seeing his picture every day in
the newspapers, was astounded in September when he vanished for two
weeks for an unannounced prostate operation.
   In a nation where virtually every decision was made by the
president, the wheels of government ground to a halt.
   ``The president used to personally sign most government
documents,'' said a foreign diplomat. ``Some of our transferring
personnel even received shipment orders for their household goods
signed by him.''
   Rodriguez's decision to act, diplomats and politicians say, came
when Stroessner ordered him to give up command of the powerful First
Army Corps and retire, or accept a political post, possibly defense
minister, without command of troops.
   Stroessner's downfall sent citizens _ 70 percent of whom had
known only Stroessner as president _ into the streets to celebrate.
Rival politicians, bitter enemies for years, embraced, danced and
sang.
   The nation's opposition political parties face new problems. Most
were unrecognized because they had not been allowed to participate
in the political process.
   ``The hinges of our political limbs are rusty from lack of use,''
said Euclides Acevedo, president of the left-leaning Revolutionary
Febrerista Party.
   Domingo Laino, popular head of the National Accord, a loose
grouping of four opposition parties, suggested the opposition needs
``as much as a year'' to organize to effectively compete with the
Colorados in elections.
   Political leaders largely discount the possibility that
Stroessner or his son Gustavo could effectively organiize any effort
to return to power.
   Stroessner supporters were hard to find after the coup and they
spoke with reluctance.
   ``I have to admit that I don't think that Stroessner was all
bad,'' said a taxi driver as he drove through streets of happy
demonstrators following the coup. ``He gave us peace and he built
schools for our children and roads where there were only mudholes
before.''
   ``Look at those people,'' he said, nodding toward the
demonstrators. ``If Stroessner were still in power, most of them
would be cheering for him instead of Rodriguez.''
</TEXT>
