<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Transvestites     02-13 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Transvestites,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Transvestites To Be Convicted Under New Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who dressed and behaved
like women in public were both fined by the Moslem Religious Court
under a law that took effect this year, a newspaper reported today.
   The Star said Ismail Awang, 31, and Amdan Osman, 42, were the
first to be convicted under the law, which applies to Moslems in
Kedah state.
   Under the law, a transvestite caught in a public place can be
fined up to 1,000 ringgits ($366) or jailed for six months. The two
men each paid $183 fines in lieu of spending four months in jail.
   The two were caught in a raid by Religious Affairs Department
officers on a street in Alor Star on Feb. 4, Prosecutor Ustaz Mansor
Osman told the court Sunday in Alor Star, 210 miles north of the
capital, the newspaper reported.
   The two were wearing skirts and T-shirts and were soliciting when
arrested, the paper said.
</TEXT>
