<DOCNO> AP890213-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-13 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When your name is Herbert Hoover, you have
to have a sense of humor. Just ask him.
   ``I remember once I needed a reservation at a Washington, D.C.,
hotel and I called and made it in my name,'' Herbert Hoover said
recently.
   ``But when I showed up, they had no reservation. They thought it
had been a prank call. ...
   ``You can't take it seriously or your life would be miserable,''
said Hoover, who works for the Nebraska Technical Assistance Center.
   Hoover was born in Mississippi in 1931 during his namesake's
presidential administration. Given his name, it's only natural he
once bought a pickup truck from a man named Warren Harding (not the
29th president), and that his office mate when he worked for the
U.S. Department of Agriculture at the University of Missouri was
Oliver Wendell Holmes (not the former U.S. Supreme Court Justice).
   He said most people have forgotten former president Hoover, but
many kid him about the Hoover vacuum cleaner.
   ``You have to get used to people laughing at you,'' he said.
   ``My name shocks people,'' Hoover said, ``so I started saying
Herb over the phone. But a few years ago, Burger King had an
advertising campaign featuring a guy named Herb and I started
finding `Where's Herb?' posters all over my office.''
   Although he hasn't changed his name, Hoover has given his son a
different start.
   ``My son's name is Michael,'' Hoover said. ``I would never do
that (name him Herbert). Children have enough to worry about.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Carolina sweet potato growers have
an identity crisis on their hands.
   Just last month, they finally got rid of the name ``yam'' from
the name of their trade group to make a distinction between their
product and the related African tuber. The state grows no yams, but
its $60 million crop represents 40 percent of the nation's sweet
potatoes.
   Now the federal government has decided sweet potato is really one
word: sweetpotato. The U.S. Department of Agriculture is apparently
worried that consumers might think a sweet potato is an Irish potato
that's sweet.
   ``That's the government bureaucracy for you,'' grumbled Milton
Horne, a salesman for Corbett Farms in Wilmington.
   The USDA wants the state's growers, and their trade group, to go
along. The N.C. Sweetpotato Commission has agreed, says Billy
Yeargin, executive director of the group.
   But the Sweet Potato Council of the United States, a
Washington-based grower group, stands by its spelling.
   ``Just because the USDA does it that way means North Carolina
does also,'' said director Howard Hoecker, noting with pride: ``But
we at the council do not.''
   North Carolina Commissioner of Agriculture Jim Graham doesn't see
what all the fuss is about.
   ``To heck with how you spell it,'' Graham said in an interview
with The Charlotte Observer. ``We'll spell it any way they want as
long as people are buying them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
