<DOCNO> AP890213-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-CentralAmerica     02-13 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Central America,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prospective Latin Aide Calls For Downgrading Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democrat who is set to become Bush
administration's top aide for Latin America was once a strong
supporter of the Nicaraguan Contras but now believes other
strategies should be pursued for achieving a settlement in Central
America.
   Bernard Aronson, who once advised President Carter and Vice
President Walter Mondale, believes the new administration should
make an all-out effort to build on the peace agreement the five
Central American presidents signed in August 1987.
   Aronson's views were outlined in a little-noticed paper he
co-authored last October which was intended to influence the debate
over Central America as the Reagan administration was bowing out.
   The report was published by Freedom House, a human rights group
based in New York.
   Eight others participated in writing the paper, titled ``Peace
Through Democracy, A Bipartisan Initiative for the Central American
Crisis.''
   Although there have been some objections to Aronson's prospective
appointment, administration aides say Secretary of State James A.
Baker has indicated that his decision is final.
   Baker has placed high priority on filling the post, vacated last
month by Elliott Abrams, with someone who will have more success
than Abrams did in forging a bipartisan policy on Central America.
   While the policies of the new administration are still in the
planning stage, the Central Americans themselves are engaged in a
flurry of diplomatic activity.
   Central American foreign ministers met in New York last week and
the five regional presidents were opening a two-day meeting today in
San Salvador to discuss the future of the Nicaraguan Contras and
other issues.
   Aronson, 42, helped write a pro-Contra aid speech for President
Reagan several years ago but the report he helped write last fall
suggests his views on rebel aid have shifted in light of new
developments.
   Baker has discussed the Central America issue only in general
terms but what he has said appears to be consistent with the
substance of the report co-authored by Aronson.
   While hinting that Contra aid may be a last resort at some point,
the report suggests that continued pursuit of that approach is
tactically unwise because of hostile public opinion in the United
States.
   ``Those who favor the immediate resumption of military aid to the
Nicaraguan resistance are in danger of once again launching a
military policy from a weak political base,'' the report said.
   It said few believe there is a broad enough consensus in support
of Contra aid to sustain that approach for a substantial period.
   Instead, the report recommends giving a ``rigorous test'' to the
Esquipulas agreement, signed by the five Central America presidents
18 months ago.
   Among other provisions, the agreement commits Nicaragua's leftist
government to establish democracy and also bars continued U.S. aid
to the Contras.
   Six months after the agreement was signed, Congress suspended
military aid to the rebels, most of whom have since fled to camps
along the Honduran border where they receive U.S. humanitarian
assistance.
   The Reagan administration was deeply mistrustful of the
agreement, seeing it as a mechanism that would relieve Contra
military pressure on the Sandinista government without ensuring a
democratic outcome in Nicaragua.
   American officials have repeatedly accused the Sandinista
government of dragging its feet in adopting democratic reforms.
   Abrams maintained that Contra military pressure was the only way
to ensure a democratic evolution in Nicaragua. Aronson suggests that
the Reagan administration should have pursued more vigorously the
opening created at Esquipulas, the site in Guatemala where the
agreement was signed.
   The Freedom House report said the accord has ``greater moral and
political validity than other approaches being considered.''
   On the other hand, it said the agreement has a number of
weaknesses, including a lack of ``compelling verification and
enforcement mechanisms'' and a reluctance ``to confront Soviet and
Cuban involvement in the region's turmoil.''
   Among other recommendations, the report calls for the
establishment of a bipartisan task force to determine whether the
agreement is an appropriate instrument for bringing about peace and
democracy in the region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ReformCaucus     02-13 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reform Caucus,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caucus Looks for Action After Bush's Reform Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The image and words heartened members of the
Congressional Military Reform Caucus.
   There was President Bush, standing on the deck of the
1,048-foot-long carrier America last month at the huge Norfolk Naval
Base and telling Navy personnel and contractor employees that he
wants ``tighter controls and higher standards in weapons
procurement.''
   ``I'm very hopeful. I know the president intends to make
changes,'' says Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del.
   ``We have a tremendous opportunity in the next few years,'' said
Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.
   Roth and Boxer _ representatives of different sides of the aisle
and different sides of the Capitol _ last week were named co-chairs
of the caucus, an informal, bipartisan organization of House and
Senate members.
   The Republican-Democratic, House-Senate mix is standard. During
the 100th Congress, the caucus membership totaled 136 with 27
members of the Senate and 109 members of the House. Seventy-eight
were Democrats and 58 were Republicans.
   Members are ``of a like mind concerned about reform in the
military,'' said Boxer.
   At times during the eight-year tenure of Bush's predecessor,
Ronald Reagan, the caucus was frustrated.
   For example, in 1983, it led the fight for the creation of an
independent Pentagon operational test and evaluation office, but the
Reagan administration delayed the installation of a test director
until two years later.
   During the Reagan presidency and the accompanying record
peacetime military buildup, scandals surfaced about Pentagon payment
of exorbitant prices for hammers, wrenches and toilet seats.
   Of a more serious nature, the Justice Department has been
pursuing a two-year probe of alleged purchasing fraud. The case
involves charges that private consultants, hired by military
contractors, bribed Pentagon officials to obtain inside information
that gave companies an edge in bidding for Defense Department work.
   ``Ronald Reagan is the true father of the caucus,'' said Rep.
Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., a member of the House Armed Services
Committee and a frequent critic of the past Republican
administration.
   The caucus says its purpose is not to advocate ``overall
increases or decreases in defense spending, only more effective
expenditure of those dollars allocated for national defense.''
   ``The notion is not to argue what weapons are needed. We're
trying to find a way to make the most of the military for less
money,'' said Boxer.
   The caucus began in 1981 after former Rep. G. William Whitehurst,
R-Va., noticed an article in The Wall Street Journal on military
reform. The story's author was former Colorado senator and onetime
presidential candidate Gary Hart.
   In reading the article, Whitehurst found that he shared some of
the same views as Hart. The senator and the congressman huddled on
military reform, joined forces with a handful of others and formed
the caucus.
   Initially, the organization concentrated on such military reforms
as maneuver tactics and leadership training. Later, as the caucus
increased in numbers, it turned its attention to purchasing reform
and conventional weapons.
   The organization says its activities ``are intended to support
the regular committee work for a more effective national defense.''
   ``We've held hearings we couldn't get the Armed Services
Committee to hold. The caucus has pushed Armed Services,'' Boxer
said.
   The caucus has no budget, no dues, not even an official phone
number. Its staff is the staff of the co-chairs who handle mailings
and pay for events.
   The caucus holds frequent briefings and seminars for members on
such issues as the Bradley Fighting Vehicle, the military budget and
conventional defense.
   This congressional session, the focus will be on promoting
legislation to strengthen the procurement system and whistleblower
protection, and tighten the revolving door between the Pentagon and
the defense industry, said Boxer and Roth.
   Affecting the reform effort will be the budget crunch facing the
Pentagon. In his speech Thursday, Bush proposed a $308.8 billion
defense budget for fiscal 1990, eliminating the 2 percent increase
proposed by Reagan in January.
   ``With less funds available, it will be critically important that
we get the biggest bang for the buck,'' said Roth. ``Centralized
procurement within the department _ this kind of approach is the
highest priority on the agenda.''
   Roth, who has been called a ``cheap hawk,'' jokes that he has to
``live up to his reputation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
