<DOCNO> AP890213-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FortuneTellers     02-13 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fortune Tellers,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gambling Resort's Fortune Tellers May Be Subject To Criminal Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who predict the future will
have to reveal their past if officials in this gambling resort get
their way.
   City council last week unanimously passed a measure to require
palm readers to undergo a criminal check, fingerprinting and
positive identification when they go for their annual license. The
city currently charges a $400 license fee for readers to practice
their trade.
   ``The city can't deal in morality, but it can regulate things
better,'' said Councilwoman Louise Palmentieri, who proposed the
measure. The council will take a final vote Wednesday.
   Many established readers support the effort.
   ``People come in here to work for a couple of months, and we
don't know who they really are,'' said Sam Mitchell, part of a
palm-reading family that has operated here for more than 50 years.
``We want the tighter restrictions. It gives us the best
protection.''
   Sharon Annette, a Boardwalk phrenologist _ someone who claims to
detect character traits in the shape of a person's skull _ said the
legalization of gambling 10 years ago has increased demand for
fortune tellers' services and the need for tougher licensing
regulations.
   ``We get a lot of bus people who want a reading to see how their
luck is running,'' she said. ``Most of Atlantic City's readers have
been here for a long time. But since the casinos came, a lot of new
(readers) came in.''
   Altantic City required non-resident workers to register with the
city from 1953 to 1972, but it was dropped after civil rights groups
complained it violated individuals' rights, Police Chief Joseph
Pasquale said.
   ``It was a good system, though, because we found people who were
wanted for murder in other states,'' Pasquale said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     02-13 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheep Production Once Exceeded US Cattle Herd</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to livestock, it may be hard to
realize today that the United States was once a nation of sheep, not
cows.
   Not anymore, of course. The Agriculture Department reported last
week that the nation's cattle inventory, although down slightly,
totaled nearly 99.5 million head on Jan. 1. The number of sheep and
lambs increased a bit for the third straight year to 10.8 million.
   Even milk cows, at 10.2 million head, nearly matched the U.S.
sheep flock. And dairy cow numbers were the smallest since 1872.
   ``Sheep and lamb production has long been an important segment of
our economy,'' the department's Agricultural Statistics Board said
in a supplemental report. ``Since colonial times, production of
sheep and lamb for meat and wool has substantially contributed to
our food and fiber industry.''
   Before the 1900s, wool production was most important, while sheep
and lamb output for meat was incidental. But the report said ``there
was a marked change'' from 1870 to 1920 as the production of lambs
for slaughter became increasingly important.
   The USDA began officially estimating sheep and lamb numbers right
after the Civil War. On Jan. 1, 1867, those totaled 46.3 million
head having a value of about $108 million, or about $2.40 per head.
   ``There were about one-third more sheep than cattle in this
earliest count,'' the report said. ``By 1884, sheep and lamb numbers
increased to 53.3 million head but exceeded cattle numbers for the
last time.''
   According to USDA records, the cattle inventory in 1867 was 28.6
million head worth an estimated $547.9 million, an average of $19.13
per head.
   By 1884, when sheep totaled 53.3 million head, cattle were at
49.8 million. The following year, in 1885, sheep were estimated at
49.6 million.
   ``Sheep and lamb numbers passed through many cyclical phases,''
the report said. ``Inventory declined after 1884 until 1897 and then
increased again until 1909, when almost 50.8 million head were on
U.S. farms and ranches.''
   The next peak for sheep and lambs was in 1932 when nearly 54
million head were reported. The all-time high was in 1942 when 56.2
million head were being raised to help with the U.S. effort in World
War II, both for wool and meat.
   Inventories dropped after the war, declining to fewer than 30
million head by 1950 and then mostly leveled off. After 1960 through
most of the 1970s, sheep and lambs continued to decline and than
hovered just under 13 million head from 1977 to 1982.
   The U.S. flock dropped to below 10 million head, an all-time low,
on Jan. 1, 1986, before the modest recovery of recent years.
   A number of causes are blamed for the demise of the U.S. sheep
industry, the report said. Mostly it has stemmed from a reduced
demand for wool, reflecting the intrusion of synthetic fibers and
cheaper substitute materials, plus a declining demand for lamb in
consumer diets.
   One big problem has been the difficulty in obtaining and keeping
reliable herders to manage and care for range flocks, which are
located mostly in the West. The increased competition for public
range land also was cited.
   ``Another important factor which has contributed to the decline
is the increasing problem of predators (such as coyotes) in many
range and farm-flock producing states,'' the report said. ``Also,
relatively large imports of lamb and mutton have contributed to the
decline of the domestic sheep industry.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last month's trade figures released by the
Commerce Department showed an impressive gain in the value of
agricultural exports from levels the year before, says an
Agriculture Department analysis.
   Agricultural exports in November, the most recent figures
reported, topped $3.3 billion, up $500 million from a year earlier
and the highest for a single month since December 1984, the report
said. The gains reflect higher export prices due to tighter U.S.
supplies stemming from last summer's drought.
   But from a volume perspective, the gains were more modest, the
report said. November shipments rose 2 percent from a year earlier
to 11.4 million metric tons.
   ``So far this year, U.S. agricultural exports ... are commanding
a $50 per ton premium on the world market over year-ago levels,''
the report said. ``The largest price increases have been in those
commodities most severely affected by last summer's drought _ wheat,
feed grains and soybeans and products.''
</TEXT>
