<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   02-13 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0807,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Highers, Stocks Fall in Tokyo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS 3 grafs to UPDATE with close. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``A
hike ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was stronger against the Japanese yen
Monday, while stock prices declined moderately in reaction to a hike
in the U.S. prime lending rate.
   The dollar ended the day's trading at 128.30 yen, up 0.65 yen
from Friday's close of 127.65 yen. It traded in a range of
128.20-128.63 yen and was quoted at 128.50 yen at midday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 53.56-point winner Friday, closed 146.67 points
or 0.4 percent lower at 31,985.32. It finished last week at a record
high 32,131.99 points.
   A hike in the prime lending rate from 10.5 percent to 11 percent
by many American commercial banks and the news of a
higher-than-expected U.S. producer price index for January, both
announced Friday, combined to spur the dollar's rally, said a dealer
at the Bank of Tokyo.
   The dollar dipped slightly in midmorning selling, but rebounded
somewhat later. Trading was slow, the dealer said.
   The dollar's direction hinges on what happens to overseas
interest rates, so players here are inclined, in the absence of any
compelling incentives to trade during Tokyo business hours, to let
the European and U.S. markets take the lead, the dealer added,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The prime lending rate is closely watched because bankers use it
as a basis for calculating interest on corporate loans and for
determining various types of fixed and adjustable-rate consumer
loans, including home equity loans.
   Higher U.S. interest rates make the dollar more attractive to
foreign investors, but tend to have a negative impact on stock
prices.
   Kazuhiro Nakamura of Wako Securities said Tokyo share prices
declined in reaction to the interest rate hike and also to the
defeat of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party Sunday in a closely
watched parliamentary by-election.
   The election was seen as an indication of public sentiment toward
the LDP following the passage of a long-sought tax reform package
last December that included introduction of an unpopular 3 percent
sales tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
