<HEAD>Sample of Items in Questionnaire About Alcohol Beliefs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Teen Drinking, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These items from a questionnaire that measures
beliefs about alcohol are among the most predictive of risk for
problem drinking, says researcher Mark Goldman.
   But he cautions that risk is indicated by the overall pattern of
responses to all 90 items, rather than to individual ones.
   Subjects are asked to mark ``true'' or ``false'' such items as:
   _ People understand things better when they are drinking alcohol.
   _ It's easier to play sports after a few drinks of alcohol.
   _ Drinking alcohol makes people feel more alert.
   _ Alcohol makes parties more fun.
   _ Drinking alcohol is OK because it allows people to join in with
others who are having fun.
   _ Drinking alcohol makes people more friendly.
