<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-13 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rebounds, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rebounded against the Japanese yen today,
while stock prices declined on profit-taking selling following six
consecutive days of record-high closings.
   Both markets reacted early in the day to a rise Friday in the
U.S. prime lending rate, which pushed the dollar higher but
depressed stock prices. The stock market also reacted negatively to
local political developments.
   The dollar, which fell 1.74 yen last Friday to a closing of
127.65 yen, gained back 0.65 yen on Monday, closing at 128.30 yen.
   After opening at 128.50 yen, the dollar weakened on mid-morning
selling, recovered and later sagged as several banks sold the
currency to protect their bond holdings, said Kaneo Ogino, a trader
at Goldman Sachs. It traded in a range of 128.20-128.63 yen.
   An increase in the prime lending rate from 10.5 percent to 11
percent by many American commercial banks and news of an
unexpectedly high U.S. producer price index for January, both
announced Friday, combined to spur the dollar's early rally, said a
dealer at the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``Now everyone's paying attention to interest-rate differentials
and inflation, which should be good for the dollar,'' Ogino said.
   Higher U.S. interest rates tend to make the dollar more
attractive to foreign investors.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 53.56-point gainer Friday, closed 146.67 points,
or 0.4 percent, lower at 31,985.32. It finished last week at a
record high 32,131.99 points.
   Share prices declined in reaction to the interest rate hike and
to the governing Liberal Democratic Party's loss Sunday in a closely
watched parliamentary by-election, said Kazuhiro Nakamura of Wako
Securities.
   ``After the LDP's severe defeat and six straight days of (stock
index) increase, investors felt it was time to ease off,'' Nakamura
said.
   The election to fill the seat of a Liberal Democrat who died in
December was the first race for a national office since the
so-called Recruit stock scandal over financial links between Recruit
Co. and prominent politicians and bureaucrats came to light.
   The election also was seen as an indication of public opinion
toward the governing party following the passage of a long-sought
tax reform package in December that included introduction of an
unpopular 3 percent sales tax.
</TEXT>
