<FIRST>r a PM-SouthBostonBlacks     02-13 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Boston Blacks,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Black Families In South Boston Housing Projects Happy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Separate Cities, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the first two black families moved into the
virtually all-white housing projects of south Boston last summer,
they were accompanied by police.
   After weeks of protests by neighbors and extensive news coverage,
city officials feared a replay of the 1970s riots over the busing of
blacks to schools in the working class section. Instead, more than
six months later, the two families report little enmity and much
hospitality.
   ``I'm just a neighbor like anyone else,'' said Elizabeth
Clinkscales, 37, who lives in a three-bedroom apartment with her
20-year-old daughter, Anjanette, and grandson, Jahman, 4.
   ``I haven't experienced much animosity since I've been here. I
think south Boston's in a healing process now.''
   The move for Clinkscales and the family of Bessie Payne, 36, was
made easier because the two have been friends since high school.
   Coincidentally, they were both given eviction notices about the
same time and applied for emergency housing with the Boston Housing
Authority.
   ``My main focus at that time was not to become homeless, not to
go into a shelter,'' said Clinkscales, who works as an assistant at
a day-care center and pays $225 a month for her apartment. ``To me
that was just as frightening as moving to south Boston.''
   Payne tells a similar story.
   ``I couldn't see myself in a shelter with the children and I saw
no reason to be when BHA had a three-bedroom apartment available,''
Payne said.
   Until recently, the projects in the predominantly Irish Catholic
neighborhood known as Southie were 98 percent white and 2 percent
non-black minorities. But since the Clinkscales and Paynes moved
into Southie, several other black families have been placed in the
projects.
   It was in the same neighborhood, separated from downtown by a
harbor channel, where years of protests erupted after court-ordered
busing in 1974. Whites stoned buses of black children shuttled from
the Roxbury section.
   After federal authorities told Boston officials to desegregate
the projects last year, Mayor Raymond L. Flynn held meetings in
south Boston to urge acceptance of the plan. Instead, they booed
Flynn, a south Boston native, and called him a traitor.
   When Clinkscales and Payne moved in last July, the city had
developed a long-term ``safety plan'' for them in case of trouble.
For the first week, the two families were told to check in with
police when they left their apartments and when they returned.
   ``My image was that there was some prejudice here but I'm the
type of person who realizes there's prejudice everywhere,'' said
Clinkscales.
   Clinkscales and Payne said in recent interviews that little has
happened to make them feel like the targets of bigotry.
   ``When I moved in, I expected a lot of turbulence,'' said Payne,
37, who is an administrator at a church, and shares her apartment
with her son, Kimani Poles, 14, and daughter, Dadizi Poles, 9.
``When it didn't happen, I was really grateful. I think the people
here are willing to accept change now.''
   The two said they give each other moral support with daily phone
calls. Yet the only disturbing incident for both came when
teen-agers once yelled racial slurs outside their apartments. They
said it occurred just once.
   Clinkscales' daughter, Anjanette, said she and her mother
exchanged Christmas gifts with the Mahoney family next door and
counts 18-year-old Kerry Mahoney as a friend.
   ``I was surprised at how nice they were,'' said Kerry Mahoney,
who said she had never known a black family until the Clinkscales
moved in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
