<FIRST>r a PM-Rudolph-Exile     02-13 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rudolph-Exile,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Pioneer Says He Was `Dumb' To Accept U.S. Exile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NASA pioneer who helped develop the
rocket that took men to the moon says he was ``very dumb'' to
renounce his U.S. citizenship rather than fight charges that he
committed war crimes in Nazi Germany.
   Arthur Rudolph, 82, is seeking a temporary visa so he can attend
an Apollo space program reunion at the Alabama Space and Rocket
Center in Huntsville. He was project manager of the Apollo Saturn 5
rocket.
   The Justice Department accused Rudolph of playing a role in the
deaths of thousands of concentration camp prisoners during World War
II, charges he denies.
   ``I did not have the financial resources to go through a lengthy
court trial and I did not know if after 40 years I could still find
any witnesses to rebut the charges against me,'' he said in an
interview last week with The Birmingham News at his home outside
Hamburg, West Germany.
   Rudolph renounced his United States citizenship at Hamburg's
American consulate in May 1984 after agreeing to return to West
Germany following a series of interviews with the Justice
Department's Office of Special Investigations.
   He called that decision ``dumb, very dumb,'' the newspaper
reported Sunday.
   Rudolph regained his West German citizenship last year after a
lengthy West German investigation concluded he had committed no war
crimes.
   As a member of Nazi Germany's von Braun rocket team during World
War II and a member of the Nazi Party, Rudolph was in charge of
production of the V-2 missile in the underground Mittelwerk factory
about 140 miles south of Hamburg. The area is now part of East
Germany.
   The Justice Department said thousands of concentration camp
prisoners were worked to death or executed at Mittelwerk. It charged
that Rudolph influenced what happened there.
   Rudolph, who was living in retirement in California when the
charges were made, said he ``never pleaded guilty but they talk
anyway about alleged things that I did, not proven, and I'm not
guilty.''
   Walter Haeussermann, who worked with Rudolph in Nazi Germany and
again in development of NASA rockets at Huntsville, said the
campaign for restoration of Rudolph's U.S. citizenship would
continue, but that efforts would focus now on his request for a
temporary visa.
   ``We think the fight for (Rudolph's) exoneration may take longer
and we would like to get permission for him to visit here even
temporarily to be part of the reunion _ the United States owes him
that,'' Haeussermann said.
   In exchange for Rudolph's agreement to leave rather than fight
the accusations, the Justice Department agreed not to challenge the
American citizenship of his wife, Martha, who lives with him in
Hamburg, or his daughter, Marianne, who works for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration in Southern California.
   Rudolph also was allowed to keep his NASA pension and medical
insurance coverage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PedophilePrivacy     02-13 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pedophile Privacy,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland Legislature Rethinking Confidentiality Privileges For Pedophiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators are having second thoughts
about a unique law that grants confidentiality to pedophiles who
confess to psychiatrists.
   Although the legislature removed some privileges last year,
Maryland remains the only state that grants patient-doctor privilege
if the pedophile discloses sexual abuse of children, or even simple
child abuse, that occurred before seeking treatment from a
psychiatrist who specializes in treating pedophilia.
   Dr. Fred Berlin, head of the Johns Hopkins Sexual Disorders
Clinic, said in a recent interview that if he were required by law
to report a pedophile's past, that person probably wouldn't come
forward for treatment.
   He and others in his specialty won special confidentiality
privileges from the General Assembly in 1987 to encourage pedophiles
to get help.
   Now, the lawmakers want to force psychiatrists to report
instances of past abuse that a pedophile reveals at any time _ even
at his initial psychiatric evaluation.
   Child advocates and social services officials backing the bill
maintain it's more important to protect a child's rights than to
guarantee any privacy to the offender.
   Stuart Comstock-Gay, the Maryland American Civil Liberties
Union's executive director, said the bill presents ``an interesting
privacy issue.''
   The state ACLU has yet to take a final position on the proposed
change, which passed the Senate last month. The House has yet to
schedule debate on the bill.
   ``There's always a balance between individual rights and another
interest in the public safety and public health,'' Comstock-Gay said.
   ``I'm sure on the surface, it must seem it's good for children to
report (the abuse), and bad not to,'' said Berlin, who believes more
abuse may be uncovered by encouraging pedophiles to enter treatment.
   Noting that clergymen who counsel pedophiles and lawyers who
refer them to psychiatrists for treatment are not compelled by law
to report them, he added: ``My concern is that people who otherwise
might have come forward would be deterred from doing so.''
   For example, without the assurance of confidentiality, one of his
patients, an attorney involved sexually with his daughter, never
would have sought help, nor would therapists necessarily have gotten
his daughter into counseling, Berlin said.
   ``There's no way he wanted to risk being disbarred. He very much
wanted treatment,'' Berlin said.
   Howard Davidson, director of the American Bar Association's
National Legal Resource Center for Child Advocacy and Protection in
Washington, believes some abuse could remain hidden by such
privileged communications.
   ``It concerns me that the balance with that sort of law tips
toward protection of the offender,'' said Davidson. ``What about the
rights of all of his victims?''
   State Sen. Walter Baker, who introduced the bill to strip the
reporting exemption, subscribes to the once-a-pedophile,
always-a-pedophile school of thought.
   ``Everybody admits they (pedophiles) can't be cured,'' Baker
said. ``I am of the opinion that they can't even be treated. I'd
rather see them in jail, that's where they belong.''
   However, Berlin believes his program of intensive psychotherapy,
in tandem sometimes with hormone treatments, can curb pedophilia.
   He also said that when a patient appears to be a danger to
others, he won't hesitate to commit him to a hospital ward for sex
offenders.
   ``It's so easy to be in the corner where you seem to be against
kids, or victims. When things get pigeon-holed, it puts pressure on
legislators, and it certainly makes it uncomfortable for me,''
Berlin said. ``I don't think there's a cure, but I do believe
people, with help, can control themselves appropriately. It's like
alcoholism; today we have the Betty Ford Clinic.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0047 </DOCNO>
