<FIRST>r a PM-IranianRally     02-13 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iranian Rally,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranians Rally Against Khomeini On 10th Anniversary Of Shah's Overthrow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Iranian emigres marking the 10th
anniversary of the Islamic revolution shouted ``Death to Khomeini''
and cheered as the shah's son's called for restoration of the
Peacock Throne.
   ``This is the day to honor the memory of all our compatriots who
lost their lives in war, in prisons and in the torture chambers of
this bloodthirsty regime,'' Prince Reza Pahlavi told the crowd of
about 12,000.
   The rally inside the Los Angeles Sports Arena came a day after a
massive demonstration in Tehran, Iran, where up to 4 million people
celebrated Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's leadership, who overthrew
the U.S.-backed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, and chanted ``Death to
America.''
   The pro-shah rally was staged in Los Angeles because the city has
the largest Iranian population outside Iran, with an estimated
500,000 expatriates living here. Several thousand Iranians marched
through central London on Saturday to support the prince's
restoration.
   Iranian businessmen handed out free tickets to the Los Angeles
rally. Those entering were frisked by police after passing through
metal detectors.
   Thousands waved green, white and red flags flags bearing the
symbol of the shah's regime, stomped their feet, clapped and chanted
anti-Khomeini slogans.
   Pahlavi, 28, took the stage to thunderous applause, holding his
hands over his head in fists, blowing kisses and tossing roses into
the crowd.
   He said Khomeini's regime has ``spilled the blood of hundreds of
thousands of Iranians,'' and ``caused the wholesale destruction of
the country.''
   He said all Iranians should come together and work to return the
royal family to power.
   ``It is time for our intellectuals, our youth, our talented and
experienced compatriots who have been forced into exile ... to enter
the stage of history, to lead and organize, to encourage cooperation
while respecting diversity of tastes and ideology,'' he said.
   Pahlavi said the end of Iran's war with Iraq presents an ideal
opportunity for Iranians to unite.
   ``The war with Iraq had kept our collective attention focused on
an external enemy. With the end of war, the bankruptcy of the regime
is ever more evident,'' Pahlavi said.
   Pahlavi conducted his entire 40-minute speech in Farsi. English
translations were provided.
</TEXT>
