<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-13 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in quiet European trading this
morning and gold prices fell.
   One currency trader at a major U.S. commercial bank in Milan,
Italy, said the dollar received considerable support from Friday's
release of statistics showing a large-than-expected 1 percent
increase in U.S. producer prices in January.
   The figures boosted expectations that the U.S. Federal Reserve
will soon raise interest rates, a move which would reinforce the
dollar, the trader said.
   He said Friday's figures neutralized much of the negative
reaction to President Bush's budget speech, which contained few new
ideas on how to trim the U.S. budget deficit.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.65 yen to a closing 128.30. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 128.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8700 West German marks, up from 1.8595
   _1.5899 Swiss francs, up from 1.5778
   _6.3620 French francs, up from 6.3200
   _2.1091 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0960
   _1,362.90 Italian lire, up from 1,353.75
   _1.1845 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1857
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7510, cheaper for buyers
than late Friday's $1.7547.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $386.65 a troy ounce,
down from $391.00 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $387.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $386.50, down from $389.50 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 11 cents to close at a bid
$388.68.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.80 a troy ounce,
down from Friday's $5.85.
</TEXT>
