<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-Reagans     02-13 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Reagans,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Eats Lunch at His Desk, Works on Speeches, Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan says there is
``no such thing as an average day'' since he left the White House
and began work on memoirs, speeches and post-presidential
politicking.
   ``We're glad to be home with our family and friends and are
enjoying getting back to a more normal life _ for example, going to
church on Sundays,'' Reagan said in answering written questions for
the Los Angeles Herald Examiner. A story about his responses was
published in today's editions of the newspaper.
   ``In Washington, it had been decided our going to church
represented a threat to too many people in these times of
terrorism,'' he said.
   The Reagans were applauded when they showed up at Bel-Air
Presbyterian Church the weekend after returning to California and
their new Bel-Air home after he left office last month.
   Reagan, 78, keeps an office atop a Century City skyscraper, where
he works on speeches, for which he'll be paid $50,000 each, believed
to be the highest fee in the country. He also is compiling a book of
speeches to be published by Simon and Schuster and is to write his
memoirs for the same publisher.
   Contrary to earlier reports that suggested a ghost writer would
be employed, the former president insisted he will do the work
himself.
   ``I always intended to write my memoirs,'' Reagan said, ``because
I believe the story of any presidency is best told by the
president.''
   Former first lady Nancy Reagan is nearing completion of her
memoirs, due to be published in the fall.
   ``There is really no such thing as an average day for either of
us,'' Reagan said. ``Lunch is soup or a sandwich at my desk, and
then back to work.''
   The former president said most days at the new office begin with
a meeting with his staff of 12, most of them former White House
aides. He spends six to seven hours a day with meetings and writing.
   Mrs. Reagan's schedule is also busy, including appearances for
the anti-drug campaign she began in the White House. A drug
treatment center bearing her name is planned for the San Fernando
Valley.
   Like his wife, Reagan has named some issues, including abolishing
the two-term limit on the presidency, he will address in his
post-White House years.
   ``My change of address has not diminished my interest in these
issues,'' he said.
</TEXT>
