<SECOND>PM-Subway Shooting,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snubbed Partygoer Shoots Six at Subway Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager, apparently angry at being turned
away from a ``Sweet 16'' party, opened fire on 40 people standing on
a Bronx subway platform, wounding six people, police said.
   Four men and two teen-age girls were wounded, said Al O'Leary, a
Transit Police spokesman. One of the men, who was shot in the
stomach, was in critical condition, while the others were in
satisfactory condition, he said.
   The gunman, described by witnesses as about 17 years old, fired a
9mm automatic pistol on a crowded Bronx subway platform at about 1
a.m. Sunday, O'Leary said. The attacker fled and no arrests were
made.
   The shooting may have been in retaliation for not being allowed
to attend the party nearby, said Transit Police Chief of Detectives
Charles Mills. At least one of the victims had attended the party.
   Derrick Jackson, a resident of Tracey Towers, the large housing
development where the party took place, said he saw about 25 people
get off a subway car at about 12:30 a.m. and walk toward the party.
   ``Apparently, they couldn't get into the party so they came back
downstairs,'' Jackson said. ``That's when they started going up the
block. About 10 minutes after they went up the block, I heard
gunshots.''
