<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     02-13 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Jews,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Cultural Center Opens in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Jews celebrated a measure of religious
freedom with the opening of the first Jewish community center in the
Soviet Union in 50 years.
   Soviet Jews and Jewish leaders from 70 nations filled the
building in downtown Moscow on Sunday for the opening.
   Elie Wiesel, an author and winner of the 1986 Nobel Peace Prize,
said the reforms of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev made the center
possible.
   ``Today is a time to say `thank you,''' Wiesel said. ``I think he
deserves our trust.''
   The opening of the Solomon Mikhoels Cultural Center, named after
a Soviet Jewish actor who died in the Stalinist oppression in 1948,
represents a significant change in relations between the government
and the country's 1.8 million Jews.
   It came just a few days after a Soviet newspaper made a major
admission: that Soviet Jews have suffered discrimination for decades
and that dictator Josef Stalin destroyed Jewish culture in the
country.
   The center is in the Moscow Jewish Musical Theater on Taganka
Square in the southeastern section of the capital.
   For Jews, greater tolerance by the Kremlin has meant a rise in
emigration _ including an eight-year high of 20,000 in 1988 _ less
harassment at Jewish holiday celebrations and the opening of a
private Jewish museum and library in Moscow.
   World Jewish Congress President Edgar Bronfman also praised
Gorbachev, saying his reforms made it possible to ``hope for a great
revival of Jewish culture and religion in the U.S.S.R.''
   But he added it will be some years before Soviet Jews overcome
their fear of religious repression in the Soviet Union, where the
teaching of Hebrew was once outlawed. He also expressed worry that
the cultural center could become the target of anti-Semitism.
   Wiesel said he still hopes ``to see in history books a
recognition that the main victims of Hitler were Jewish _ because
they were Jewish, not because they were Communists and Russian
citizens.''
   Sunday's ceremony drew Jewish leaders from around the world,
including former Soviet refusenik Yuli Edelstein, now an executive
of the Soviet Jewry Zionist Forum in Israel; World Jewish Congress
vice president Isi Leibler of Australia; and Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean
of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles.
   The cultural center is particularly important because decades of
repression have left most of the Soviet Union's Jews with virtually
no knowledge of their religion, history and culture.
   ``Soviet Jews are not really Jews,'' said Edelstein, who served
three years in prison for teaching Hebrew.
   The cultural center opened with a photo exhibit on the Holocaust.
Organizers hope to offer classes in Yiddish and Hebrew, films,
exhibits, music and a cafe featuring Jewish food, said director
Mikhail Gluz.
   The ambassadors of the United States, Australia, Canada, Great
Britain and France also spoke at the ceremony. Israel, which does
not have diplomatic relations with the Soviet Union but which has
had warmer contacts with Moscow in recent months, sent Arie Levin,
head of its consular mission in Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
