<DOCNO> AP890213-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Welfare-Eviction     02-13 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Welfare-Eviction,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Trying To Evict Welfare Tenant When Mounds Of Cash Found In
Apartment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city Housing Authority has begun proceedings
to evict a welfare recipient from an apartment where two drug raids
turned up cocaine and more than $200,000 in cash, according to a
report today.
   On Jan. 26, federal Drug Enforcement Administration agents and
Housing Authority police raided Ansille Watts' aartment and found
more than $55,000 in cash, the New York Post reported. Officials
said the city was paying Watts' entire $137-a-month rent.
   The raid also netted close to 1,000 vials of crack cocaine that
were thrown out a window when the officers burst in, the Post said.
   Watts, 36, was charged with possession of drugs and guns and
remains in jail awaiting trial.
   Authorities said the apartment continued in use as a crack den
and on Feb. 1 they returned and found close to $150,000 in cash and
a receipt for a $44,000 Mercedes Benz.
   The Housing Authority has classified Watts an ``undesirable
tenant'' and begun eviction proceedings, said Housing Authority
spokeswoman Val Coleman.
</TEXT>
