<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0446 02-13 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast Kills Arab; Troops Critically Wound Two Teen-agers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with explosion killing Arab; teen-agers
critically wounded. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``We are ...'' EDITS thereafter
to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion killed a Palestinian in the
occupied territories today, and Israeli troops critically wounded
two Arab teen-agers during a stone-throwing riot, the army said.
   In Jerusalem, two left-wing members of Parliament said recent
attacks by Israelis on Palestinians in the occupied West Bank are
the work of a ``very efficient and well armed'' Jewish settler
militia.
   The army imposed a curfew on Kabatiya village in the West Bank
after an unidentified man accidentally blew himself up in an blast
that hurt two other villagers, a military spokesman said.
   ``A preliminary report indicates they found a suspicious object,
played with it and it exploded,'' said a military statement.
   An Arab reporter in the West Bank said a 4-year-old girl and her
10-year-old brother were seriously hurt while herding sheep near
their Tayasir village home. The children's parents said they heard
an explosion, but do not know its cause.
   It was not immediately clear whether the army and the Arab
reporter described the same incident. Tayasir and Kabatiya are 10
miles apart.
   A military spokesman denied the man was killed inside Kabatiya,
but refused to elaborate.
   At least six other children have been reported wounded in similar
mysterious blasts, which the government is investigating.
   Ehud Barak, deputy chief of staff of the armed forces, has said
some injuries were caused by flares emitted by fighter jets to
deflect heat-seeking missiles. A few flares fall to earth instead of
exploding, he said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip's Rafah refugee camp today, two
14-year-olds were shot in the head by troops. They were in critical
condition in Israeli hospitals, a military spokeswoman said.
   Two Jerusalem legislators from the left-wing Citizens Rights
Movement sent a letter to Attorney General Yosef Harish charging
there is a well-organized militia of several hundred settlers armed
with automatic weapons, vehicles and advanced communications sytems.
   Settler leaders denied an organized militia exists.
   The lawmakers' letter was sent Sunday after 40 settlers stormed
into a West Bank Palestinian mayor's office to protest stonings and
firebombings of settlers' cars. The army spirited Mayor Mohammed Abu
Sneineh out of his Qalqilya office and forced the settlers to leave.
   ``We are calling on the attorney general to break up this
militia,'' said Yossi Sarid, who authored the letter with Dedi
Zucker.
   Sarid said bands of settler vigilante groups started forming a
few months ago in response to Palestinian attacks on some of the
70,000 Jewish settlers who uneasily share the occupied lands with
1.7 million Arabs.
   Settlers formed the militia because they have lost faith in the
army's ability to protect them, Sarid said.
   Settler leader Ron Nachman, named in the letter as a key militia
chief, said the paramilitary organization was Sarid's ``fantasy.''
   ``There is a difference between a militia and people getting fed
up and doing something,'' said Nachman, mayor of the West Bank
settlement of Ariel.
   However, he added that if the government does not take harsher
measures to end the 14-month Palestinian uprising, such as deporting
Palestinian leaders, more settler violence is likely.
   The settlers were protesting the death Wednesday of a 37-year-old
Jewish taxi driver from the West Bank settlement of Alfe Menashe.
Police said Albert Jerassi apparently was attacked by Arabs, but
they have not discovered what caused his car to burst into flames as
he drove past Qalqilya.
   Jerassi's death would raise to 16 the number of Israelis who have
died in the Palestinian uprising. At least 380 Palestinians have
been killed in the revolt against Israel's occupation of lands
seized in the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
