<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru   02-13 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0491,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Endorse Gradual Change to Multiparty System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with Grosz comments published today, INSERT three
grafs after 6th graf pvs: ``Parliament is...multiparty system.'' Pickup
7th graf pvs: ``The Soviets...'' EDITS 10th graf pvs: ``His comments...''
to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's ruling Communist Party has
endorsed a multiparty system for the first time, but says the change
must be gradual and orderly.
   The party's policy-making Central Committee announced its new
position over the weekend after a two-day meeting during which it
also revised its view of the 1956 anti-Soviet uprising.
   Allowing more than one political party would provide a ``better
safeguard'' against abuse of power, the Communist Party said Sunday
in a communique released by the state news agecy MTI.
   It also said ``danger exists for the process to become
destabilized and uncontrollable. That is not in the interest of any
force with a sense of responsibility.''
   In a half-hour interview broadcast on radio and television Sunday
evening, party leader Karoly Grosz said alternative parties could
exist ``only on a socialist basis.''
   Parliament is expected to pass a bill by Aug. 1 that would allow
alternative parties, making Hungary the first East bloc country to
have a genuine multiparty system.
   The Communist Party daily Nepszabadsag today published Grosz's
speech at the Central Committee meeting, held Friday and Saturday.
   Grosz criticized the ``extremist wing'' of potential alternative
parties. He said all parties would have to accept Hungary's
membership in the Warsaw Pact military alliance and ``prevent any
deepening'' of the nation's economic problems.
   Grosz also praised what he called ``more composed'' forces and
said ``there is a realistic possibility to establish a lasting
political alliance with these.''
   The Soviets have not taken a public stand on recent Hungarian
reforms. Grosz is to visit Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in
March.
   Hungarian Politburo reformer Imre Pozsgay created conflict among
communists two weeks ago with a stunning re-evaluation of the
anti-Soviet revolt of 1956.
   Pozsgay said the revolt was a popular uprising, not a
counterrevolution as his party had called it for 32 years.
   His comments touched off intense public debate and led to the
Central Committee meeting.
   The committee statement and Grosz's remarks on television
indicated there had been a compromise on reassessing the revolt.
   Grosz said that over the years the party ``had forgotten those
popular elements'' that started the uprising against the Stalinist
regime of Matyas Rakosi on Oct. 23, 1956.
   But, he said, by the time the Soviets had crushed the uprising on
Nov. 4, 1956, counterrevolutionary forces were leading the revolt.
   Western diplomats and some Hungarians active in the dozens of
alternative political groups started recently said they believed the
outcome of the Central Committee meeting was a victory for Pozsgay,
who has pushed hard for a multiparty system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Baker 3rdLd-Writethru a0502 02-13 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0502,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Works On Missile Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for grafs 5-6 pvs ``We believe it...'' to UPDATE
with Norwegian foreign minister's comments. Picks up 7th graf pvs ``The
most ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III left a
dispute over short-range nuclear missiles behind in West Germany and
took his NATO tour to Scandinavia today hoping a solution would be
worked out before his return to Bonn.
   Baker met first today in Copenhagen with Danish Foreign Minister
Uffe Ellemann-Jensen on a stop designed to acquaint the new U.S.
secretary of state with Denmark's skittishness over nuclear weapons.
   Baker then flew to Norway, a staunch U.S. ally that considers
itself the cornerstone of NATO's northern defense. In Oslo, Norway's
leaders expressed reservations about the need to update the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization missiles.
   Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland said modernizing the Western
alliance's battlefield nuclear arms was one of many issues that
required more discussion.
   ``We believe it should be a wide agenda, including both
deterrence and disarmament negotiations,'' Mrs. Brundtland told
reporters, with Baker standing at her side.
   Norwegian Foreign Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg added later,
``Negotiations could lead to a result which does not make
modernization necessary.''
   Stoltenberg, who will visit Washington this month, said Baker did
not press for modernizing the nuclear arsenal, but only was
``thinking aloud on the policy of the new administration.''
   The most critical talks of Baker's eight-day tour of the 15 NATO
allies are being held in Bonn. West German leaders are trying to
delay the modernization of Lance battlefield nuclear missiles, while
the Bush administration wants to upgrade them.
   U.S. officials said a statement was being prepared in Bonn while
Baker was in Scandinavia that Baker, who was returning to West
Germany tonight, would discuss with Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher.
   The U.S. officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, declined
to say whether a compromise had been reached or the differences
would papered over until the issue is addressed at a NATO summit
meeting in May.
   West German leaders are concerned that upgrading the missiles
could threaten further progress in East-West disarmament talks.
There is strong public opposition to modernization in West Germany
and the country is to hold national elections next year.
   Baker began talks with West German officials on Sunday after
meeting with British officials in London.
   He has said he is not worried about Kohl's statement last week
that the Lance missiles now deployed are adequate until 1995.
   Under a NATO plan, the missiles' 70-mile range would be extended
with new rockets that could hit targets about 320 miles away.
   NATO is expected to make a decision on modernization in three
months.
   On Baker's agenda in Bonn were two other touchy issues: Western
curbs on technology sales to the Soviet Union and the help West
German companies gave to Libya in the construction of an alleged
chemical weapons plant.
   Baker said the British told him they would like to see the curbs
lifted now that Soviet troops are leaving Afghanistan.
   Concerning Libya, Baker said new West German export restrictions
were ``quite promising,'' as were recent pledges by the Bonn
government to prosecute violators.
   Commenting on his meetings Sunday with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher of Britain and Sir Geoffrey Howe, the British foreign
secretary, a U.S. source said Baker received support on many NATO
issues. The source declined to elaborate.
   Also, the source said, Howe urged Baker to plunge into the Middle
East situation ``to sustain the moderate course'' the foreign
secretary said the Palestinians had taken.
   The source said Baker made it clear U.S. dialogue with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, which began in December after a
13-year ban, would be continued.
   Baker's trip began Friday in Canada and took him to Iceland on
Saturday. His last stop is Paris before returning to Washington on
Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
