<FIRST>r a PM-WomenKilled     02-13 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Women Killed,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Women Killed In their Home, Two Weeks After Another Relative
Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT GIBSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly woman and her daughter were
found stabbed to death with a butcher knife in their home two weeks
after another member of the family was strangled in her home across
town, authorities said today.
   ``We have reason to believe all three slayings were related,''
said Claiborne County Sheriff Frank Davis.
   Davis said officers were questioning a male suspect in the
slayings and that formal charges were expected later in the day. The
man was not related to the victims, he said.
   A relative discovered the bodies of Georgia Mae Thomas, 58, and
her mother, Mary Bell Simmons, 88, about 6 p.m. Sunday in a bedroom
of the home they shared in Port Gibson.
   ``It appeared they were both sexually molested and both had stab
wounds to the chest,'' Davis said. The bodies were found within an
hour after the women were killed, he said.
   The apparent murder weapon, a butcher knife, was found at the
scene, he said. Highway Patrol investigators and officers from
neighboring counties were assisting in the investigation.
   Davis said another member of the family, Bertha Peterson, 47, of
Port Gibson, was strangled in her home two weeks ago and that the
circumstances were similar. He said he wasn't sure what her
relationship to the other two women was.
   This historic town, about 30 miles south of Vicksburg in
southwestern Mississippi, has a population of about 2,500. It has
many pre-Civil War buildings because Union officers called it ``too
pretty to burn'' when their armies swept through the state.
</TEXT>
