<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchTakeover 1stLd-Writethru a0497 02-13 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Takeover, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0497,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Calls Dissidents Liars; They Vow To Continue Church Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The 89-year-old...', with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with detail from this morning, clarify that protests not disrupting church
activities. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `The dispute...'. SUBS 13-14th grafs
pvs, bgng `Chmiel said...', with 1 graf to delete now-redundant material.
Picks up 15th graf, `In addition...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The priest of St. Michael's Roman
Catholic Church said dissident parishioners occupying his church are
liars and said he won't respond to their demands that Polish
traditions be preserved and a popular Polish priest retained.
   The dissidents, who number about 80 and say they have the support
of 800 of the church's 1,200 parishioners, vowed Sunday to continue
their occupation of the church.
   The Rev. John Bambol, the current parish priest, said the
protesters have falsely accused him of forcing a popular Polish
priest out of the parish.
   ``This is a small group of people, new immigrants,'' Bambol said.
``We are being threatened by them in the news, through telephone
calls and with lies.''
   Bambol said church officials have decided to ignore the
occupation that began Saturday afternoon and continued this morning.
   ``Nothing. We're going to do nothing,'' he said.
   The protest has not disrupted activities in the 89-year-old
church, which was packed with about 500 people during Sunday's noon
Mass. Following the service, about 80 dissidents remained behind to
continue the occupation.
   This morning, about 20 protesters sang hymns, said the rosary and
prayed in Polish in the church. They said they hope to continue the
protest indefinitely, staying at the church in shifts, instead of
ending today as originally planned. They vowed to start a hunger
strike later in the week if necessary to press their demands.
   The dispute centers on the pending transfer of associate pastor,
the Rev. Roman Palaszewski of Poland, and the replacing of the Rev.
Bruno Pysz, who was moved to a Buffalo, N.Y., church in August.
   Halina Chmiel, a spokeswoman for the dissidents, said Palaszewski
was notified nine weeks ago that he was being transferred back to
Poland by the Franciscan order. She said Palaszewski was in the
third year of a five-year assignment to St. Michael's.
   ``We want our priest back in the parish,'' Chmiel said. ``He kept
the culture, the Polish tradition, which is important in this
church. He was a people's priest.''
   She accused Bambol of getting him transferred back to Poland out
of jealousy.
   ``It's a lie,'' Bambol said. ``He got orders to go and you have
to go.''
   Officials of the Bridgeport Diocese didn't respond to messages
seeking comment, left with the diocese's answering service Sunday
and today.
   In addition to the dispute over priests, some critics have said
the protesters are upset that Bambol was attempting to open the
parish to other ethnic groups. The parish is in a largely Hispanic
neighborhood.
   Protester Genevieve Kozlowski said they didn't want to keep other
groups out of the church but did want to keep its Polish heritage.
   ``What we have is Polish church. Why can't it stay a Polish
church? We don't care if Puerto Ricans or blacks come to pray with
us. We welcome them. But we want to keep our Polish customs,
traditions and language,'' she said.
</TEXT>
