<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Doctors to Perform Surgery in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of American doctors will travel
to Vietnam to perform about 100 operations in a mission financed by
U.S. veterans of the Vietnam War, the official Vietnam News Agency
said Monday.
   The 40 plastic surgeons, nurses and other medical personnel will
fly to Vietnam from Bangkok this week, said Ross Petzing, a
spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok.
   He said the group from ``Operation Smile'' was one of various
charitable groups responding to the U.S. government's recommendation
that Vietnam be given private aid in humanitarian fields.
   ``Operation Smile'' is a non-governmental, non-profit
organization based in Norfolk, Va., Petzing said.
   The United States and Vietnam do not have diplomatic relations,
but Washington has encouraged more humanitarian aid since Vietnam
pledged in 1987 to speed up an accounting of Americans missing from
the Vietnam War.
   The Vietnamese news agency, monitored in Bangkok, said the
specialists were from 23 American states. They will stay in
Vietnam's capital of Hanoi for five days, it said.
   It quoted William Magee, the founder of ``Operation Smile,'' as
saying that his group would in the future also send specialists to
Vietnam's major southern city of Ho Chi Minh and other areas ``to
bring smiles back to those children with mouth defects.''
