<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SoldierKilled     02-13 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soldier Killed,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norwegian Soldier Killed, Comrade Injured in Car Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armored personnel carrier skidded off the
road in southeast Lebanon on Monday, killing a Norwegian soldier of
the U.N. peacekeeping force and injuring another, a U.N. spokesman
said.
   The accident occurred near the town of Rashaya in the foothills
of Mount Hermon, two miles north of Israel's self-designated
security zone in south Lebanon, said spokesman Timur Goksel.
   ``One Norwegian private was killed and another was wounded. Three
other Norwegians in the APC escaped unharmed,'' said Goksel,
declining to identify the victims.
   Goksel said both were flown to the Lebanese border town of
Naqoura, which houses the command headquarters of the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon.
   The accident brought U.N. fatalities to 159 since the
5,844-strong force was deployed in south Lebanon in 1978 to serve as
a buffer between Israel and Palestinian guerrillas. Among those
killed were 16 Norwegians.
   The force is made up of troops from France, Fiji, Finland, Ghana,
Ireland, Italy, Nepal, Norway and Sweden.
