<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Jews     02-13 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Jews,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Praises New Jewish Cultural Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze met Monday
with the head of the World Jewish Congress and welcomed the opening
of the first Jewish cultural center in the Soviet Union in 50 years,
a member of the congress said.
   Isi Leibler, a vice president of the congress who said he did not
attend the meeting but was briefed on it, said Shevardnadze
``expressed optimism about the opening of the center.''
   The Solomon Mikhoels Cultural Center was opened Sunday in
southeastern Moscow, and more than 70 foreign Jewish leaders,
ambassadors and Soviet officials attended.
   Leibler, who also is the president of the Executive Council of
Australian Jewry, said in an interview he could not divulge details
of Shevardnadze's meeting with World Jewish Congress President Edgar
Bronfman. He listed the topics discussed as Jewish culture,
religion, emigration and refuseniks _ the term for those denied
permission to leave the Soviet Union.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass said Bronfman discussed with
Shevardnadze a settlement of the rift between the Arabs and Israelis
and that the foreign minister again appealed for convening an
international conference on the Middle East.
   ``In our view, it is time to undertake immediate steps to begin
concrete preparations for the conference,'' Shevardnadze was quoted
as saying.
   In November, Bronfman's organization announced after he met with
Shevardnadze and other Soviet officials that the Kremlin had given
the green light for opening the cultural center. The World Jewish
Congress, which represents Jewish groups in 70 countries, also said
Soviet officials agreed to lift a ban on the teaching of Hebrew.
   Hebrew and Yiddish classes are planned at the Solomon Mikhoels
center. At the opening, Nobel Peace Prize winner Elie Wiesel said
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev deserved praise for freeing several
jailed Jews and opening the door to freer emigration of Jews. Last
year, 20,000 Jews left the Soviet Union, marking an eight-year high.
</TEXT>
