<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru a0451 02-13 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presidents Meet to Discuss Central American Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SAN SALVADOR</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with summit opening. Picks up 6th
pvs, ``Among the ...'' Changes byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TESORO BEACH, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
opened a much-postponed Central American summit today, saying the
five leaders are optimistic about bringing peace and progress to the
turbulent region.
   Flanked by Presidents Jose Azcona of Honduras, Daniel Ortega of
Nicaragua, Oscar Arias of Costa Rica and Vinicio Cerezo of
Guatemala, Duarte made the brief statement opening the meeting at
Tesoro Beach, a seaside resort 40 miles southeast of San Salvador.
   ``I am sure that we, with optimism, will analyze the efforts
we've made according to the Esquipulas II plan and search for
favorable solutions that will promote peace and progress in Central
America,'' Duarte said.
   Then the presidents went into closed session.
   The stalled peace plan was named for the Guatemalan city where
the five presidents decided to sign the August 1987 agreement.
   Diplomats say Nicaragua's four neighbors plan to press its
government for democratic reforms promised under the peace plan.
   ``The main roadblock in Nicaragua has been removed _ the
Contras,'' said one diplomat referring to the decline of the
Nicaraguan rebels called Contras. ``There are no more obstacles (to
reform) and no more excuses.''
   At the same time, Nicaragua probably has most to gain from the
conference, which it hopes will help destroy the Contras.
   ``Among the most important things that will be dealt with at the
summit is the matter of verification and control of borders,''
Duarte told a news conference last week.
   Ortega said upon his arrival Sunday that he believed the leaders
``are going to ratify'' a new plan to step up border controls to
prevent the Central American neighbors from supporting subversion
against one another.
   Central American foreign ministers met U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar in New York last week and called for
creation of ``an impartial mechanism'' to verify compliance along
borders.
   About 11,000 Contras remain in Honduran camps near Nicaragua's
border, but the Bush administration has made no request for renewed
military aid and senior U.S. officials acknowledge the era of an
anti-Sandinista army as an arm of U.S. policy has passed.
   Nicaragua has scheduled elections for 1990 and has met with
opposition leaders to discuss its recent economic austerity
measures, but the opposition claims Sandinista talk of democratic
reform is window dressing.
   A Costa Rican diplomat said that unless the Sandinistas make
``precise commitments and agree to deadlines for democratization
measures ... we will have to prepare for the peace plan's funeral
and the Nicaraguans will have to accept responsibility for its
demise.''
   Arias won the Nobel Peace Prize for writing the plan, which is
designed to bring peace and promote democracy in the turbulent
region.
   ``We go to the summit full of optimism, despite the obstacles,
because reality demands the search for solutions to the problems we
Central Americans have,'' Arias was quoted as saying by the Costa
Rican newspaper El Diario de la Republica on Sunday.
   A summit in August was to mark the anniversary of the plan's
signing, but the presidents, who last met 13 months ago, could not
agree on an agenda. The meeting has since been scheduled and
postponed five times.
   When the peace plan was signed, stubborn civil wars plagued El
Salvador and Guatemala and the Contras were waging a fierce campaign
against the Sandinistas.
   Duarte's U.S.-backed government and the leftist guerrillas
battling it were unable to negotiate a cease-fire. Guatemala's
leftist rebels have been reduced to isolated zones but remain
active, and Cerezo's government has not sought negotiations.
   The United States cut off military aid to the Contras a year ago,
and the rebels signed a preliminary cease-fire with the Sandinistas
in March. Although some fighting continues, it now is scattered and
sporadic.
   Nicaragua, however, has been strongly criticized for failing to
live up to the plan's requirement to strengthen democratic
institutions and practices.
   Besides that, the plan calls for amnesties for political
prisoners, a halt to outside aid to insurgents, and prohibits
signatories from allowing their territory to be used as bases for
attacks against another's territory.
</TEXT>
