<FIRST>r i AM-SovietInspectors     02-13 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Inspectors,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>12 Soviet INF Inspectors to Conduct Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors arrived at Rhine
Main Air Base south of Frankfurt on Monday to witness the
destruction of U.S.-built Pershing 2 nuclear missile launchers.
   The 12 Soviets arrived aboard a TU-154B jetliner and were greeted
by U.S. Air Force Col. John Fer, the head of the European On-Site
Inspection Agency office located at Rhine Main.
   Fer's office is responsible for accommodating and escorting the
Soviet inspectors, who are conducting checks under the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty signed by the superpowers
in December 1987.
   The Soviets were to spend the night at a military hotel on base.
   ``Under the Intermediate Nuclear Missile treaty, the Soviets gave
notice of their plans 72 hours in advance after they were notified
that 19 Pershing 2 missile lauchers were to be destroyed at
Hausen,'' said U.S. Air Force Lt. Col. Pat Maloney.
   He said plans called for the Soviets to carry out the on-site
inspections on Tuesday and Wednesday.
   Hausen, a Frankfurt suburb, is the location of the same U.S. Army
missile maintenance depot where Soviet inspectors watched the
destruction of nine other Pershing 2 missile launchers in October.
   Under the treaty, Soviet and U.S. inspectors have been conducting
reciprocal on-site verification checks on removal and destruction of
medium- and shorter-range nuclear missile systems at sites in
central Europe, the Soviet Union the United States since last summer.
   U.S. Army Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie, who has headed the U.S.
On-Site Inspection Agency since it was created in April, has said
the Soviets are trying hard to comply with the treaty.
   Lajoie said the Soviets clearly view verification under the
treaty as a foundation for cooperation for further cuts in the
superpowers' nuclear arsenals.
</TEXT>
