<HEAD>New Head of Justice Department Tax Division Recommended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is recommending that
President Bush nominate Washington lawyer Shirley D. Peterson to be
assistant attorney general in charge of its tax division, sources
said Monday.
   The recommendation was sent by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
to the White House, said sources familiar with the appointment
process who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Ms. Peterson, 47, an expert on wills and estates, is a partner at
the Washington law firm of Steptoe &amp; Johnson and served between 1982
and 1984 on the Justice Department's advisory panel on tax
litigation. She chairs the gift and estate tax committee of the
American Bar Association's tax section.
   Thornburgh's recommendation means it is likely that Bush will
nominate Ms. Peterson for the post, which is subject to confirmation
by the Senate.
