<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1505EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CaveExplorer     02-13 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cave Explorer,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famous Cave Victim's Body To Be Reinterred At Mammoth Cave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HORSE CAVE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of cave explorer William Floyd
Collins, whose 1925 entrapment and death in a cave became national
news, will be laid to rest again spring, perhaps for the last time.
   After his death in Sand Cave, Collins' body was recovered and
buried, exhumed for public display, stolen and dumped along the
banks of the Green River, and put back on display.
   ``The time has come to let him rest in peace,'' said Donnie
Collins, a Horse Cave resident and Collins' great-nephew. ``He
deserves it after all these years.''
   Collins' relatives and the National Park Service have worked out
arrangements to re-inter the body.
   ``He'll be buried in a cemetery on the (Mammoth Cave) National
Park grounds in late March,'' Donnie Collins said. ``We're not sure
exactly when it will be, but there's no rush after all this time.
He's still dead.''
   The park now includes caves that Collins discovered and died in.
   Collins was 37 when he entered Sand Cave on Jan. 30, 1925, in
hopes of finding a new entrance to Crystal Cave, the cavern he
discovered under his father's Edmonson County farm on Jan. 18, 1917.
   Caves in the area were privately operated then, and competition
for tourists' dollars was intense.
   Collins was on his way out of Sand Cave _ head-first and on his
back _ when he was trapped in a small passageway by rocks that fell
onto his foot and ankle.
   More than 30 news agencies sent reporters to the site, and
thousands of spectators watched while rescuers tried in vain to dig
a shaft parallel to the cave to reach Collins.
   Collins was pronounced dead Feb. 16 _ 18 days after entering the
cave.
   His body was removed from the cave without fanfare and was buried
near an entrance to Crystal Cave.
   Later, the body was disinterred, placed in a different casket and
displayed in a large cavern in Crystal Cave.
   It was stolen four years later. The body was found at the edge of
the Green River, but one of Collins' legs _ the one which had been
trapped by the rocks _ had been sawed off.
   Eventually, the body was redressed and returned to Crystal Cave,
where it remains today in a black casket chained securely to a
concrete base.
   That cave has been closed since 1961, when it was bought by the
Park Service. Until then, Collins' casket was the highlight of tours
and, until 1948, visitors could view the body through a window in
the casket lid.
   ``I'm tickled to death they're finally going to bury him for
good,'' said Pat Thomas, a Bowling Green police polygraph examiner.
During his college days, he worked for O.O. Burgess, the funeral
home director who embalmed Collins.
   After Burgess died, his daughter gave Thomas a set of slides
Burgess had bought that photographically detailed the events
surrounding Collins' death.
   ``That's part of the commercialism of the whole deal,'' Thomas
said. ``I wouldn't trade those slides for anything, but it shows you
the way Floyd was exploited after his death.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Roseanne     02-13 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Roseanne,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Roseanne' Tries a Little Tenderness in Girl's Coming-of-Age Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' breaks ground this week with a
girl's coming-of-age story that gives series star Roseanne Barr a
chance to show a softer side.
   In Tuesday night's episode of the hit blue-collar sitcom,
11-year-old Darlene, portrayed by Sara Gilbert, gets her period. The
episode, written by Grace McKeaney and directed by John Pasquin,
handles the subject gently, while still being funny.
   Co-executive producer Tom Werner said Monday he is unaware of any
sitcom that has dealt with a girl's puberty in such a way before.
   ``I think it's a terrific area to be doing,'' he said.
``Obviously, we're doing a family show, and we're trying to do
something that is not only entertaining but is informative.
   ``And I think it's an important story because I think it's
important for young women to know what menstruation is about before
it begins so that perhaps they won't be as frightened and confused
by it, as certainly can happen,'' he said.
   Werner and his partner, Marcy Carsey, also are executive
producers of NBC's top-rated ``The Cosby Show.'' ``Roseanne,'' the
biggest new hit of the season and ABC's top-rated show, recently
underwent a change in producers. Co-creator Matt Williams left,
citing creative differences with Barr.
   Werner said the Tuesday episode was written after Williams left,
but doesn't necessarily reflect a change in the direction of the
sitcom.
   ``I think we're always trying to make good episodes, and I think
it's a chance to do a problem from a mother's point of view that is
interesting and different,'' he said.
   The episode begins with the family gathering around the TV set to
watch scary movies. Roseanne is not particularly thrilled, since the
kids tend to be up half the night with nightmares. Sure enough,
Darlene can't sleep, but she insists it isn't because of a dream.
   By the next morning, the irrepressible tomboy is moping around.
``Are you worried about your basketball game?'' her parents ask.
   ``No, I'm not worried about the basketball game.''
   ``Did you screw up in history again?''
   ``No, I didn't screw up in history again. I got my period, OK?''
   Darlene stomps out, leaving Roseanne and her husband, Dan (John
Goodman), to gape at each other.
   Later that day, Roseanne and her sister, Jackie (Laurie Metcalf),
recall their mother's less-than-helpful advice to ``feel free to ask
the school nurse'' if they had any questions about the change of
life.
   In what Werner describes aptly as ``a lovely scene,'' Darlene
runs into Dan in the garage. He feels compelled to say something on
this momentous occasion, but all he can come up with is a punch in
the arm and an awkward, ``Good goin'!''
   When Darlene starts throwing out her beloved sports
paraphernalia, Roseanne gets the chance to dispense some motherly
wisdom.
   ``I thought there was a lovely scene from Dan's point of view in
the show,'' Werner said. ``I thought that the way Roseanne
Conner-slash-Roseanne Barr handled it was terrific because I think
she tried to discuss the problem with her, which I think is
important, and she actually made her daughter feel like this was the
beginning of a new and exciting phase in her life and welcome to
being a woman.''
   Werner said the episode was probably originally the idea of
writer McKeaney, though it would have been developed by the writers
with Barr and was a subject almost everyone on the show could relate
to in some way.
   ``I'm going through it as a father,'' Werner said. ``Roseanne
obviously has gone through it as a mother. Jeff Harris, who is the
head writer, has gone through it as a father. I think we're excited
about it because I think it was handled in a well-crafted way, and I
think it made its point without being too heavy-handed.''
</TEXT>
