<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     02-13 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grosz Speech Tough on Media, `Extremists' Outside Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz
attacked the state media in a speech published Monday, and he ruled
out cooperation with ``extremists'' outside the party.
   The speech was delivered at a secretive two-day session of the
party's Central Committee that for the first time endorsed the
introduction of a multiparty system in Hungary.
   The body agreed to open talks with representatives of the many
alternative movements that have sprung up recently, but set no firm
timetable for the first multiparty elections or other aspects of the
new system, saying a transition must be gradual.
   Grosz's speech, which opened the session Friday, wasn't published
until Monday, when it appeared in the party daily Nepszabadsag.
   He attacked the unidentified ``extremist wing'' of the
alternative organizations that were legalized last month. A bill due
to be passed by Aug. 1 in parliament is to legalize alternative
political parties.
   Grosz made clear these parties would be expected not to reject
socialism outright, to accept Hungary's membership of the Warsaw
Pact military alliance, and to ``prevent any deepening'' of
Hungary's current crisis.
   There is increasing dissatisfaction over a range of austerity
measures and price increases Grosz and other leaders insist are
essential to boost the economy and help repay the $17 billion
foreign debt.
   Grosz said the party's support is narrowing and the alleged
extremists outside the party try to undermine it further by talking
of divisions between reform communists and Stalinists, preventing
the creation of a viable center.
   He also accused the more outspoken programs on state radio and TV
and particularly the daily Magyar Nemzet, which has published
astonishing articles in recent months, of undermining the system and
spreading lies.
   Grosz seemed to be trying to carve out a middle ground, making
attacks that would please old guard communists but also praising
what he called the ``more composed'' forces in the new alternative
groups.
   ``There is a realistic possibility to establish a lasting
political alliance with these forces,'' Grosz said, without
identifying them.
   A party sociologist interviewed in the trade union daily Nepszava
on Monday singled out the Social Democractic Party, the Hungarian
Democratic Forum, the Smallholders Party and another agrarian-based
group as possible partners for the Communist Party.
   The sociologist, Istvan Stumpf, said he thought the Social
Democrats stood ``a very good chance of regaining credit for the
idea of socialism.''
   His phrasing, Grosz's statements and the Central Committee
communique suggested the communists see a multiparty system as a
vehicle for making socialism popular again, rather than introducing
Western-style democracy.
   Stumpf said no one alternative group had worked out a fully
viable economic and political program and called for the
alternatives to be given full access to data needed to conceive such
policies.
   That would mean opening up government economic and other data to
groups outside the party, which dominates virtually the entire state
and government apparatus.
   Neither Grosz nor Stumpf set any date for introducing a fully
operational multiparty system or any possible coalition. Grosz said
the transition would take a long time and that parliamentary
elections next year would mark only the first stage.
   Representatives from five of the alternative groups met later
Monday and gave a guarded welcome to the Central Committee's
statement.
   Balint Major, of the Alliance of Free Democrats, said the Central
Committee statement ``definitely means some progress'' but contains
``some bombshells'' that suggest the ruling party is still reluctant
to share power.
</TEXT>
