<FIRST>r i BC-Hostages-Text     02-13 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hostages-Text,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Text of Letter from Anderson's Sister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Text of Peggy Say's letter to her brother,
American hostage Terry Anderson, marking her 48th birthday on
Wednesday:
   Dear Terry,
   My heart feels very close to you on this day. I came to celebrate
my 48th birthday by being close to you and praying for your strength
and freedom. I will go home much older, much sadder and much wise
than when I began this journey four years ago.
   I placed a bracelet with your name on the altar at Maaloula and
prayed there for a healing of our personal wounds, and for the
healing of the wounds between our country and the countries of the
Middle East. I also prayed for peace for the people of Lebanon and
freedom for those who live in bondage as you do.
   Your beautiful children are fine and send their love as so does
our family. Your many friends and thousands of people in America
work and pray every hour, every day for strength and freedom for you
and all the hostages.
   I have sent messages of gratitude to Sheik Fadlallah and
President (Hafez) Assad for their intense and complicated efforts to
free the hostages. Our country and others are working very hard to
bring this situation to a happy ending. I have great hope that
President Bush will work for a new and better relationship between
our people and our brothers in the Middle East.
   Stay strong little brother _ this too will pass.
   I love you,
   Peggy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
