<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-AirlineSecurity     02-13 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline Security,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain to Press for New Security Measures at Aviation Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain this week will press the International
Civil Aviation Organization for bomb-detection measures to be built
into the design of aircraft, according to Transport Secretary Paul
Channon.
   The meeting Wednesday and Thursday of the 33-nation organization
in Montreal was called by the United States and Britain after the
Dec. 21 air disaster over Lockerbie, Scotland, when a bomb blew
apart a Pan Am Boeing 747. All 259 people aboard and 11 people on
the ground were killed.
   It still has not been established whether the bomb, placed in
luggage, was put aboard at London's Heathrow Airport or in
Frankfurt, West Germany, where the New York-bound flight originated.
   Channon said he also planned to put forward proposals, which he
did not specify, on better screening of baggage, control of access
to airport and detection of explosives.
   He said he backed U.S. resistance to publicizing anonymous
warnings about sabotage attacks against a particular airline. It
emerged after the Lockerbie disaster that the U.S. government had
received a warning of an attack against Pan Am.
   ``If you were to announce every one (warning) you would be
announcing them all the time and people would soon get totally
inured to them,'' said Channon.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization includes Western,
Third World and East bloc countries.
   ``We are faced with an international problem and we must find an
international solution to it,'' Channon said.
</TEXT>
