<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     02-13 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition, Government Reported to Differ at Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the Solidarity trade
union and the government reported sharp differences Monday after a
meeting of a working group devoted to solving Poland's economic
problems.
   At issue was whether a government plan to attack the economic
crisis would be adopted by the working group as the basis for its
deliberations.
   Solidarity considers the plan drafted by the government of Prime
Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski a ``good declaration of
intentions,'' but short on specifics, Solidarity spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz said at a news conference.
   The opposition has not offered a reasonable alternative to the
plan, said Industry Minister Mieczyslaw Wilczek, speaking at a
separate news conference.
   The working group on the economy, which includes representatives
from the opposition, the government and the official trade union
alliance OPZZ, is part a broad series of negotiations known as the
``round table'' that began Feb. 6.
   Other working groups are meeting on issues of political reforms
and trade union freedoms, and the whole series of negotiations is
expected to last three to five more weeks.
   Solidarity activist Mieczyslaw Gil said Deputy Prime Minister
Irenuesz Sekula displayed a ``really worrying'' tone at the talks
that ``indicates that the government still has a monopoly in
implementing economic reforms.''
   A government spokesman, Zbyslaw Rykowski, characterized the talks
Monday as ``rather difficult'' and ``exchanges of monologues''
rather than a discussion.
   ``The economic debate is so vast that so far it is hard to put
some order into it,'' he said.
   Onyszkiewicz expressed wariness, but said that, ``Our hopes are
not quite blown yet.''
   ``It seem that the authorities would like to obtain our stamp (of
approval) under decisions that have already been made. We have been
and will be careful about it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
