<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SleepingAids     02-13 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sleeping Aids,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Regulations Issued by FDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration on Monday
issued final regulations for non-prescription sleep-aid products
that allow use of most of their active ingredients but bans other
ingredients not proved safe and effective.
   The major sleep-aid products already meet the new standard and
few changes will have to be made in product labeling, FDA officials
said.
   The regulations are not much different from the agency's
tentative recommendations on sleeping-aid ingredients issued in June
1978, said Mike Benson, a reviewing pharmacist with the FDA's
division of over-the-counter drug evaluations.
   The regulations, to be published in Tuesday's Federal Register,
will take effect in one year. They were developed as part of the
FDA's review of all non-prescription drugs, which began in 1972.
   The FDA standard allows use of diphenhydramine hydrochloride and
diphenhydramine citrate, contained in the sleep-aid products Compoz,
Nervine, Nytol, Sleep-eze-3, Sleepinal, Sominex and Sominex-2, the
FDA said.
   The agency also said approval of doxylamine succinate will remain
in effect. That ingredient is in Unisom, Doxysom and Ultra Sleep.
   Not permitted are pyrilamine maleate, potassium bromide, sodium
bromide and scopolamine hydrobromide. Products containing these
ingredients must be reformulated, the FDA said.
   The FDA, in its tentative finding 10 years ago, had recommended
banning these four ingredients unless they could be proved safe and
effective, and as a result many sleeping-aid manufacturers stopped
using them, Benson said.
   Claims on sleeping-aid product labels, substantially the same as
those in the tentative recommendations, may include: helps you fall
asleep if you have difficulty falling asleep; for relief of
occasional sleeplessness; and helps to reduce difficulty falling
asleep.
   Warning labels will have to be changed to add to the list of
medical conditions that if present indicate the product should not
be used. The new labels must warn against taking the product if you
have asthma glaucoma, emphysema, chronic pulmonary disease,
shortness of breath, difficulty in breathing or difficulty in
urination due to enlargement of the prostate gland, unless directed
by a doctor.
   The new labels also strengthen the caution involving alcohol,
advising people to avoid alcoholic beverages while taking the
product. It also advises against taking the product if also taking
sedatives or tranquilizers, without consulting a doctor first.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
