<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nigeria     02-13 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nigeria,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Dissolves Ruling Armed Forces Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ibrahim Babangida swore in a new
Armed Forces Ruling Council on Monday, telling its members to
disregard regional or tribal ties and consider their ``constituency
as the Nigerian nation, period.''
   The council, the West African nation's highest ruling body, has
been reduced from 29 to 18 members, with several Cabinet ministers
and the chief of state security dropped. Unlike the former council,
which had two civilian members, the new one has military members
only.
   Babangida's decision last week to disband the council had caught
the nation by surprise, and provoked rumors of discord within the
military and speculation about coup attempts.
   Col. Fred Chijua, chief spokesman for the Nigerian army, denied
in an interview with the African Guardian news magazine that there
had been any attempt against Babangida's government or that any
military personnel had been executed.
   Babangida, an army general, set up the original council after
seizing power in a barracks' coup in 1985. The council is to preside
over the country's return to civil rule in 1992.
   In recent months, there have been growing complaints about the
rising cost of living in Africa's most populous nation, and labor
unions have threatened nationwide strikes to protest
government-ordered cuts in fringe benefits and salaries.
   The military government has imposed an austerity plan to try to
get out of a deep recession partly caused by lower oil prices.
Nigeria's main export earnings come from petroleum exports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
