<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Bishops-Vatican     02-13 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bishops-Vatican,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Keynoters At Vatican-Bishops Meeting Mostly Conservatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The agenda for a special four-day meeting of Pope
John Paul II and U.S. archbishops and cardinals on conditions in the
American church was made public Monday.
   The agenda shows the meeting will involve more than 12 hours of
open discussion between the pope, members of his cabinet, the Curia,
and the U.S. bishops.
   According to the agenda, released by the Vatican and by the U.S.
Catholic Conference in Washington, presenters or speakers at
sessions on responsibilities of bishops and priests will be
Cardinals John O'Connor of New York, Bernard Law of Boston and James
Hickey of Washington.
   Cardinal Edmund Szoka of Detroit is to address a session on
people who do not belong to a chuch and the mass media.
   Presenters at sessions on matters such as the laity, family and
ecumenism include Archbishops John R. Quinn of San Francisco and
Paterick W. Flores of San Antonio and Bishop William R. Keeler of
Harrisburg, Pa.
