<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hearts&amp;Flowers     02-13 0932</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hearts &amp; Flowers,0968</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sweets ... And Some Not So Sweet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big gifts and guilt sometimes go hand in
hand, warns a psychologist taking aim at Cupids bearing surprisingly
large or expensive Valentine's Day gifts.
   When someone is either falling out of love or already has done
so, and is feeling guilty, ``sometimes they not only give a gift _
they go overboard,'' said Charles Lowe, a professor of psychology at
the University of Connecticut.
   A $2.50 card from someone who customarily sends a more modest
greeting can be a tip-off.
   ``Superficially, gifts are always nice. But gifts can be given
for the wrong reason _ flattery, ingratiation, wanting to get
something from you, or guilt,'' Lowe said.
   So how can one tell if a nice gift on Valentine's Day is a sign
cupid is on the mark or off target?
   ``If this person has not done this in the past, and comes up with
a big gift, that's something that needs to be thought about,'' he
said. ``It could be either a sign of falling in love again or of
feeling guilty.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jilted lovers or angry spouses can turn to an East
Dallas florist to deliver dead Valentine's Day floral arrangements
to their unloved ones complete with a visit from a black-robed Grim
Reaper.
   ``Some people have wanted us to send Venus' flytrap or poison ivy
with the dead flowers _ or just by itself,'' said Susan Roberts,
owner of Balloon-o-grams@Drop Dead Florists. ``But we
don't want to get into trouble for doing that.''
   Dead flowers in a ceramic skull with a plastic snake poking
through an eye cost about $38. For a personal delivery by the Grim
Reaper, its an extra $10.
   Mrs. Roberts incorporated the dead flower service into her store
several months ago.
   ``I was hoping this would be popular, but I didn't realize there
was this much demand for this type of thing.'' She said she plans to
open stores in Fort Worth and Arlington.
   She'll have competition in Arlington from Hate Inc., which offers
three ``hate-o-grams:'' dead flowers, candy boxes full of rocks and
a ribbon-trimmed box containing a dead fish.
   The company made $15,000 in the three weeks leading up to
Valentine's Day last year, said John Roure of Hate Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nature-loving cupids can buy a commemorative tree
in a Houston park for their valentines for only $100.
   The donor can choose the tree type and even specify the location
and the Houston Parks Board will send a card inscribed with a
personal message.
   Original board member Jerald Mize started the commemorative tree
program in 1977 when he planted 100 red maple trees on Buffalo Bayou
in memory of a friend. That tradition has brought more than 10,000
trees to Houston.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bride will be in white with a maid of
honor at her side, but tradition ends there for a radio newsman and
a nurse getting married on the air for Valentine's Day.
   His friends couldn't take off work, so Bill Bateman and his
bride, Cherie Warren, are cramming their wedding party into a radio
control booth along with disc jockeys broadcasting the KOMA morning
drive show.
   ``These are my friends, it's only natural for me to want to get
married with my friends,'' he said. ``KOMA is funny, it's like a big
family. They couldn't take off work to watch us get married, so
we're getting married here.''
   The wedding party will squeeze into the control room, and other
guests will be scattered around the station listening on monitors.
   ``We found a preacher with radio experience so he can understand
words like `time constraint,''' Bateman said.
   The ceremony has been pared down to about three and a half
minutes, he said. ``It's going to work out like a champ. It's going
to be great.''
   Bateman said his parents in Florida won't miss a word. ``The
music, the build up, the whole bit ... we'll just shoot them the
tapes.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLISS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cupids wanting their Valentine's Day messages
to come from Bliss have sent more than 600 envelopes to the
postmaster here for special hand postmarks.
   Good Housekeeping magazine was at least partially responsible for
the red tide when it listed Bliss among a half dozen U.S. post
offices that could provide ``a postmark as loving as the message
inside.''
   ``It surprised me. It made me feel good,'' said Postmaster
Patricia Barber, who subscribes to the magazine.
   She kept right on feeling good when the envelopes started pouring
into the tiny upstate hamlet around mid-January.
   Cupids send their stamped valentine in a separate envelope to the
postmaster and request that it be postmarked and forwarded to its
final destination.
   ``Ninety-one is my record for one day. They came from most every
state, and they went out to most every state,'' she said. ``One went
to Germany, one to Indonesia. Both of those had the right amount of
postage on them.
   ``Many had little notes wishing me a happy Valentine's and hoping
I was doing well. Two or three included an extra Valentine
especially for me.''
   Normally, Barber forwards her mail to Buffalo for machine
canceling, but for each piece of Valentine mail, she used her old
stamp, made sure it was well-inked and gently applied the mark.
   The U.S. Postal Service also put out a list of post offices for
Valentine's Day postmarks that included Loving, Texas; Hart, Mich.;
and Valentine in Arizona, Nebraska and Virginia. Bliss did not make
that list.
</TEXT>
