<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     02-13 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arens: Negotiations Should Be With Jordan, Not PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens told a skeptical
group of Jews on Monday that peace talks involving Palestinians
should be held with Jordan, not the PLO.
   An aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, meanwhile, outlined a
peace plan that calls for Palestinians in the occupied lands to halt
the 14-month uprising in exchange for elections and negotiations.
   But the aide, Yossi Ben-Aharon, also ruled out talks with the PLO.
   A Palestinian was killed and two others were wounded in the
occupied West Bank when an explosive device detonated after it was
picked up, the army said.
   It said it was checking reports by hospitals and family members
that two Palestinian children were hurt in a blast in a nearby
village.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, troops opened fire on stone-throwing
Palestinians in the Rafah refugee camp. Three Palestinians were
wounded, including two teen-agers struck in the head with
rubber-coated metal bullets.
   In a speech in Jerusalem to the World Sephardi Federation, Arens
argued that Jordan was a predominantly Palestinian state and that
peace negotiations should be held with King Hussein.
   ``If you want to address the Palestinian problem, you have to
talk to Jordan,'' he said.
   Arens said talking with the PLO would only jeopardize peace
efforts. ``We'll simply strenghten extremism, encourage violence,
and show that terrorism pays off,'' he said.
   But the Sephardi Federation, a liberal organization of Jews whose
families came from Arab countries, issued a statement urging Israel
to ``take risks for peace'' that could include negotiations with the
PLO.
   Shamir is said to be developing a proposal to present when he
visits the United States in March or April.
   Ben-Aharon said it would not include talks with the PLO. ``With
the PLO there is nothing to talk about, because we will not agree to
the existence of a second Arab state ... west of the Jordan river,''
he said.
   He called for an end to the uprising. ``Secondly, a formula for
direct negotiations has to exist,'' he said. ``At a certain point,
free elections will have to be held in order to determine the
representation that will decide the fate of our Arab neighbors'' in
the territories.
   He said Jordan should be a partner to the settlement.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began, at least 380 Palestinians
have been killed, most as a result of army gunfire. Fifteen Israelis
also have died.
   In a report released last week, the U.S. State Department
criticized Israel for the way it had responded to the revolt, saying
many deaths could have been avoided.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin made his first public comment on
the report Monday when he told the Israeli parliament the army ``has
behaved and continues to behave gritting its teeth against violence
and provocations like the Israel Defense Force.''
   ``We have nothing to hide because we are not embarrassed over
what we are doing,'' he said.
   An army spokeswoman said a Palestinian man was killed Monday and
two others wounded in a field near the West Bank town of Kabatiya
when ``they found a suspicious object, played with it and it
exploded.''
   The spokeswoman, who could not be identified under army
regulations, identified the dead man as Amin Mohammed Amin of
Kabatiya. She said there was no information on the inured.
   Doctors at nearby Jenin Hospital said they treated two Kabatiya
teen-agers for shrapnel wounds from the blast.
   Soldiers cordoned off the site and investigators were trying to
determine whether the explosive fell from an aircraft or was left
after an army training exercise, an Arab reporter said.
   In Tayasir, about 10 miles southeast of Kabatiya, two children
were reported hurt in an explosion.
   Doctors and family members interviewed at Al-Ittihad Hospital in
Nablus identified the children as Iktimal Abdullah, 4, and her
brother, Naim, 10. Family members said they heard an explosion and
found the children on the ground.
   Iktimal Abdullah later was transferred to Mukassad Hospital in
east Jerusalem, where she was reported in critical condition with
head wounds.
   Israel Radio said it was not known what exploded but quoted
family members as saying there were no Israeli soldiers or civilians
in the area at the time of the blast.
</TEXT>
