<FIRST>r a AM-People SUB a0541 02-13 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People, SUB, a0541,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Los Angeles.</HEAD>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs first item to UPDATE with Lansbury signing new pact with
CBS.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angela Lansbury, whose high-rated ``Murder, She
Wrote'' is one of the few bright spots on third-place CBS' schedule,
has agreed to stay with the network for another year, though not
necessarily in the same show.
   CBS announced Monday that negotiations for another season of the
top-10 hour drama are continuing, but that Miss Lansbury has agreed
to star in at least 13 episodes of a new half-hour show on CBS the
season after ``Murder, She Wrote'' ends its run.
   ``Murder, She Wrote,'' in which Miss Lansbury, 63, plays a shrewd
but grandmotherly mystery writer who gets involved in murder cases,
is in its fifth season, after which Miss Lansbury had planned to
quit. Under the new pact, Miss Lansbury's company, Corymore
Productions, operated by her sons David and Anthony Shaw, will
produce the half-hour show and two made-for-TV movies for CBS over
the next three years. Miss Lansbury will star in at least one of the
movies.
   The Wall Street Journal reported last week that Miss Lansbury and
the rest of the ``Murder, She Wrote'' crew had long grumbled about
penny-pinching by the network, which had undertaken a last-ditch
campaign to keep the show for at least another year.
   Miss Lansbury and crew celebrated the show's 100th episode in Los
Angeles on Sunday, the day before the new CBS deal was announced.
   ``I'm so proud of the show and I have so much a sense of
accomplishment of having remained in the top 10,'' Miss Lansbury
said at the bash.
   Miss Lansbury said she was eager to continue with CBS if
contractual hurdles could be cleared, adding, ``it's awfully hard to
walk away from success and leave an audience that's so dependent on
the show.''
   ``Murder, She Wrote'' draws an estimated 40 million viewers a
week and is a linchpin in CBS' successful Sunday night lineup. NBC
is similarly dependent on ``The Cosby Show'' as an anchor for its
top-10 Thursday night lineup and managed to eke another year out of
star Bill Cosby, who, like Miss Lansbury, had planned to quit his
show after this season.
   Miss Lansbury is a four-time Tony Award winner for her roles in
the Broadway plays ``Mame,'' ``Dear World,'' ``Gypsy'' and ``Sweeney
Todd.'' She has also appeared in such films as ``National Velvet,''
``The Long, Hot Summer'' and ``The Manchurian Candidate.''
</TEXT>
