<FIRST>r a AM-HotelFire     02-13 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hotel Fire,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Drop Arson Charges In Fire That Killed Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All charges against a British tourist accused of
setting a hotel fire that killed two people were dropped Monday
because the principal witness against her, her boyfriend, refused to
testify.
   Tara Jane Terry, 19, of Camberley, England, faced a federal arson
charge in the Sept. 17 blaze in Miami Beach at the Nassau Hotel,
which began in a room she shared with Mark Richardson, 20, of
Sandhurst, in Surrey, England.
   U.S. District Judge Kenneth L. Ryskamp ordered the indictment
thrown out on the request of prosecutors who complained that
Richardson refused to return from England to testify.
   ``It's not unusual,'' U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said.
``Witnesses frequently become recalcitrant later in the process, but
it's very disappointing when the witness is a key one and they're
overseas.''
   While the federal decision did not rule out state charges against
Ms. Terry, Dade County Assistant State Attorney Joseph Rosenbaum
said his office had no such plans.
   ``If they can't get Richardson back, how are we going to?'' he
said.
   Initial police reports claimed Miss Terry set the blaze, which
killed an 82-year-old man and a 76-year-old woman, after arguing
with Richardson.
   Richardson was detained briefly after the fire as a material
witness but was then freed to go back to England.
   Lehtinen said prosecutors can ask the British government to make
Richardson available for depositions, but added the process was long
and complicated.
   As soon as Ryskamp dismissed the indictment Monday, Miss Terry
sprang from her chair and pointed an accusing finger at her
prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney Terry Lindsey.
   ``Next time, make sure you have proof,'' she said angrily.
   The judge discharged her $100,000 bond and returned her passport
and other documents.
   ``All she wants to do is get on a plane to London and get back to
her home in Surrey,'' said her attorney, Richard Sharpstein.
   He attacked the case as unfair from the outset.
   ``This has been an irresponsible and embarrassing prosecution
from day one,'' Sharpstein said. ``However, a possible result is
that it shows that the American justice system works.''
   The government contention that Richardson's refusal to testify
prompted the dismissal was just a ``red herring,'' Sharpstein said.
   Miss Terry was charged under an infrequently used federal arson
statute making it illegal to set fires in establishments doing
interstate business.
</TEXT>
