<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LaborersUnion     02-13 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laborers Union,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Official Reputed To Have Mob Ties Resigns; Replaced By Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second-ranking official of the Laborers
International Union of North America, identified by a presidential
commission as having close ties to organized crime, retired Monday
and was replaced by his son.
   Arthur E. Coia, the union's secretary treasurer, announced his
retirement at the union's annual Executive Council session in Bal
Harbour, Fla. Arthur A. Coia, regional manager for the Laborers in
New England and eastern Canada, was immediately tapped to succeed
his father.
   Both men were mentioned in the 1986 report of the President's
Commission on Organized Crime, which said the union had ``clear ties
to organized crime.''
   The elder Coia, 75, once was indicted on racketeering charges for
allegedly accepting payoffs in return for steering union insurance
business to selected companies. But the case was dismissed because
the charges were filed after the statute of limitations had expired.
   The report, citing congressional investigations of organized
crime influence on organized labor, also accused Coia and his son of
involvement in schemes to bilk union health and welfare funds.
   The younger Coia, in a telephone interview, said both he and his
father were ``unfairly characterized'' in the report and had no
dealings with the mob.
   ``The mention of me and my father in that presidential commission
report is really not a detailed and fair representation,'' he said.
``The so-called link to organized crime does not exist.''
   The report also criticized internal union election policies,
including the provision that allowed the younger Coia, 45, to be
tapped to succeed his father.
   The Laborers union holds its convention every five years, when
delegates elect candidates to the Executive Council on an at-large
basis. If board vacancies occur between conventions, the remaining
board members choose a replacement, a policy the report said
``leaves few offices contested.''
   ``When the use of violence and intimidation are added, the
membership has little opportunity to express itself dramatically,''
the presidential report said.
   The hearings on which the report was based included testimony
that the elder Coia also sought to convince Robert Powell, a
longtime vice president of the union and one of its few black
leaders, not to run for union president.
   Powell testified that Coia told him the ``Italians'' had
organized the union and would always control it.
   The report accused the elder Coia and Laborers President Angelo
Fosco of abusive spending of union funds, including $200,000
authorized by Coia to pay for a private investigator to keep tabs on
a longstanding federal investigation of the union.
   Coia also ordered the union to pay $40,000 requested by his son
to cover legal fees stemming from a government investigation of the
union, the report said.
   There has been speculation that Focso might step down from the
union presidency this year, but the younger Coia discounted such
talk. ``I think the rumors are all false,'' he said.
   The Coias both are Rhode Island natives. The younger Coia, a
labor attorney by trade, has a law practice in Providence, R.I.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     02-13 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Score Bush Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private group of scholars and analysts said
Monday that President Bush's proposal to bail out the savings and
loan industry does not provide enough money or reforms.
   The plan, announced last week, would provide $90 billion to close
or sell 350 insolvent S&amp;Ls and meet pledges made by regulators last
year in cleaning up 223 institutions.
   The Shadow Financial Regulatory Committee, a group of 12
financial experts from colleges and consulting and law firms,
praised Bush for recognizing that the S&amp;L problem is much more
costly than previously acknowledged by the government.
   But, in a statement, it said, ``There is a strong possibility
that additional thrifts which are now marginally solvent will become
insolvent in the near future. Increases in interest rates may also
lead to financial difficulties for many more thrift institutions.''
   Meanwhile, in a separate development, the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. on Monday took control of Midwest Federal Savings &amp;
Loan Association, an insolvent S&amp;L in Minneapolis.
   Midwest was the 11th institution taken over under a program
announced by Bush last week. The FDIC plans to assume control of
more than 200 S&amp;Ls, insolvent under regulatory accounting rules,
over the next four to six weeks.
   Although government regulators will be more strictly supervising
the institutions, the FDIC is emphasizing that all insured deposits
will continue to be fully protected.
   Arizona State University business professor Edward J. Kane, a
member of the shadow regulatory committee, estimated that 800 to 850
institutions of the nation's 3,000 thrifts are ``economically
insolvent'' even though regulatory accounting rules show a far
smaller number.
   ``Any increase in interest rates is ... going to put a lot (more)
institutions under water,'' said Franklin Edwards, a business
professor at Columbia University.
   The group did not offer its own figure to counter the
administration's $90 billion estimate, but Edwards said the red ink
could total as much as $130 billion.
   Edwards said Bush would be wise politically to deal with the full
problem now, early in his term. He also criticized the proposal to
raise $50 billion over the next three years by selling
``off-budget'' bonds. The interest costs would be less expensive if
the money were raised by borrowing directly through the Treasury, he
said.
   Bush's plan also reorganizes the regulatory structure by giving
the Treasury Department and the commercial bank insurance fund, the
FDIC, more authority over savings and loans.
   But, Kenneth E. Scott of the Stanford University School of Law
said the president's plan seem more aimed at ``moving boxes'' than
accomplishing real reforms.
   The committee advocated a program of early intervention that
would impose federal control when an institution weakened and force
the institution to shut down before it actually became insolvent.
That way, depositors would be protected and expenditures by the
federal insurance funds would be rare.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
