<HEAD>Governor's Aunt Was Strangled, Authorities Say; Funeral Tuesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs the 7th graf, ``The Harris family,'' with one graf to update
with quote from governor.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARTERSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aunt of Gov. Joe Frank Harris, found
slain in her home over the weekend, was strangled, perhaps by a
robber, police said Monday.
   Allie Morrow Roper, 75, a sister of Harris' mother, Frances
Morrow Harris, was found dead Sunday morning after she failed to
pick up neighbors for church.
   Mrs. Roper apparently was killed Saturday night, said police Maj.
C.B. Siniard. Authorities found a shopping receipt from late
Saturday afternoon. She lived alone.
   There were ``signs of unlawful entry'' at her home, Siniard said.
``We're trying to determine with the family members if anything is
missing.''
   Mrs. Roper died of asphyxiation caused by strangulation,
according to the Bartow County medical examiner.
   She was found unclothed and bound, Siniard said.
   ``The brutal murder of my widowed aunt in Cartersville shocks not
only my family but the entire community, which knew Aunt Allie as a
dedicated and faithful church worker,'' Harris said in a statement.
   Mrs. Roper and her family operated a flower shop in Cartersville
for a number of years. A neighbor, Cecil Mauldin, said she trained
many of the florists in Cartersville, and ``was a friendly woman,
who would do anything for anybody.''
