<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-Council     02-13 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Council,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Resume `Shura' Council Despite Factionalistm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas briefly resumed a
council on Monday and tried to choose a Moslem government, but two
important leaders did not attend and rival factions continued
wrangling over shares of power.
   Guerrilla sources said the seven groups in the Pakistan-based
guerrilla alliance were divided on who should lead an interim
government in Afghanistan and on apportioning the top positions.
Differences also arose over including insurgent groups based in
Iran, they said.
   Afghanistan is predominantly Sunni Moslem, as are most guerrillas
based in Pakistan. Most of the insurgents in an eight-faction
coalition that operates from Iran are Shiite Moslem, the sect of
their host country.
   Some spokesmen said the council, known as a shura, would resume
Tuesday and would consider major issues for the first time. Others
said there was little or no hope of progress.
   ``The whole situation is such that nothing can come out of the
council,'' said a senior official, who like the others spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Factionalism developed immediately Friday at the inaugural
session of the shura, which has been seen as the last chance for
feuding guerrilla groups to compromise, and it was suspended.
   Insurgent leaders predict the Marxist government in Kabul will
collapse soon after the last Soviet soldiers withdraw on Wednesday.
The council's job is to choose a government that would take over and
arrange elections.
   Aides said Sibghatullah Mojaddidi and Syed Ahmed Gailani, who
lead two of the seven parties, did not attend the Monday meeting and
leaders of the five other other parties presided over the council,
which did not consider major issues.
   Mojaddidi did not attend because the other six parties rejected
his proposal for bringing the Iranian-based guerrillas in, sources
reported.
   A spokesman for Mojaddidi said: ``The shura is not going to work
out without the Iranian-based mujahedeen,'' using the word for the
guerrillas that means Islamic holy warriors.
   Gailani aides said he had a scheduling conflict Monday but would
attend the meeting Tuesday. But guerrilla sources said that he
stayed away because of an argument about who would lead the interim
government.
   Guerrilla groups summoned the council of insurgents, Moslem
scholars and officials of past Afghan governments. Mojaddidi, who
now holds the rotating chairmanship of the Pakistan-based alliance,
has insisted the others honor his plan to give the Shiite groups in
Iran 100 of the more than 500 council seats and seven interim
government Cabinet posts.
   Most Sunni guerrilla leaders say the Shiites, an estimated 15
percent of Afghanistan's population, are too few to receive so many
seats. About 80 percent of Afghans are Sunni.
   Shiite representatives have said they will accept only the
Mojaddidi plan, but have not carried out their threat to leave
Islamabad.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting in Afghanistan after a Communist
coup in April 1968 and Soviet soldiers entered the country in
December 1979, reaching an estimated total of 115,000 by May 15,
1988, when the Red Army began withdrawing under a U.N.-mediated
agreement.
   Pakistan, the United States, Iran and other countries have helped
arm and finance the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
