<SECOND>AM-People-Diana Ross,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diana Ross Ready to `Do Something Different'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diana Ross says she is determined to do something
different as she returns to the stage after taking time out to marry
and give birth to two sons.
   ``People expect glitter and glitz from me,'' Ross said in an
interview in the March issue of Vanity Fair magazine. ``But you have
to change, too. ... You have to keep cutting the strings all the
time.''
   For the moment, Ross, 44, is planning to record an album and go
on a concert tour.
   Her career was launched in the 1960s as the lead vocalist of the
Supremes, and she says she has a ``motherly instinct'' toward the
young black singers of the 1980s.
   ``I love Whitney (Houston),'' Ross said.
   But envy of Houston's success is what propelled her to resume her
career, according to a friend who is quoted anonymously by the
magazine as saying, ``Diana would be competitive with a tree.''
   ``I have to be better than the best. Super-everything,'' said
Ross, who has kept a low stage profile since she married Arne Naess,
a Norwegian tycoon, in 1985. Ross gave birth to a boy in August, her
fifth child, and her second son with Naess.
