<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     02-13 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Armed Civilians Clash at Army Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers on Monday battled a small
band of civilian intruders at an army base about 435 miles west of
Buenos Aires, the government news agency Telam reported.
   It appeared to be low-key replay of the La Tablada incident three
weeks ago.
   Telam said a patrol discovered four or five civilians and opened
fire at about 5:15 a.m. on the base of Weapons Battalion 141 near
Rio Cuarto, south of Cordoba.
   Shooting continued for about 90 minutes until the civilians fled,
the independent news agency Diarios y Noticias said. Soldiers did
not pursue the civilians fearing that it may have been a
diversionary tactic, it said.
   One soldier was wounded. The attackers, whose goal and motive
were not known, all escaped.
   On Jan. 23, about 50 armed civilians crashed through the main
gate at the 3rd Infantry Regiment at La Tablada on the outskirts of
Buenos Aires. By the time troops recaptured the base a day later, 28
intruders, nine soldiers and two policemen had been killed.
   The government of President Raul Alfonsin blamed leftist
subversives for La Tablada. Fourteen intruders were seized and were
imprisoned pending charges.
</TEXT>
