<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WorldCourt     02-13 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Court,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Court Opens Hearing In U.S.-Italian Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hearings opened Monday at the World
Court in a dispute between the United States and Italy over the 1968
seizure of a U.S.-owned company, a court spokesman said.
   It is the first U.S. case to be heard since the Reagan
administration rejected a 1986 World Court ruling ordering it to
stop arming the Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras.
   Boston-based Raytheon Co., an electronics company and defense
contractor, estimates it lost $6 million plus interest in the
takeover of its subsidiary company Elettronica Sicula S.p.A., said
Abraham Sofaer, the legal advisor to the U.S. State Department.
   Raytheon wanted to liquidate the Palermo, Sicily-based
manufacturer of cathode ray and vacuum tubes, but the Italian
government nationalized the company to save jobs on the island
plagued by unemployment.
   A five-judge panel is hearing the case, which is expected to
continue at least until Wednesday, the court spokesman said on
condition of anonymity. The Reagan administration filed the suit two
years ago for Raytheon, but only written arguments had been made
since then. Only governments can appear before the court.
   Formally known as the International Court of Justice, the
judicial branch of the United Nations has no enforcement powers and
depends on voluntary adherence to its rulings.
   Elettronica Sicula, also known as ELSI, was co-owned by Matchlett
Laboratories Inc., a U.S. company not involved in the case.
   The Italian government said expropriation of the company in 1968
was aimed at protecting the plant's 900 jobs after Raytheon and
Matchlett disclosed their intention to shut down the concern.
   The judicial panel consists of the court's president, Judge
Jose-Maria Ruda of Argentina, and Judges Shigeru Oda of Japan,
Roberto Ago of Italy, Stephen M. Schwebel of the United States and
Sir Robert Jennings of Britain.
   The case was filed in February 1987 after the Reagan
Administration rejected as invalid a World Court ruling in July 1986
ordering the United States to stop arming rebel forces attempting to
overthrow Nicaragua's leftist government.
   In apparent anticipation of that adverse ruling, the United
States had withdrawn in March 1984 its recognition of the unlimited
jurisdiction of the court, but said it would continue to accept the
court's authority in cases not connected with the Central American
issue.
   The ELSI case is the third one filed at the World Court by the
United States in a decade.
   In 1979, the United States asked the court to order the release
by Iran of 52 American diplomats held hostage in the U.S. embassy in
Tehran. The court, on an emergency basis, ruled weeks later that the
hostages should be released. They were ultimately freed in 1981.
   In the same year, the U.S. government and Canada jointly asked
the court to draw the boundary between the two nations in the Gulf
of Maine off North America's East Coast. That dispute was decided in
1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
