<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Kemp     02-13 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Kemp,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Takes Over HUD Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush caught a football tossed by Jack
Kemp, who called himself ``a kinder, gentler quarterback'' after
being formally sworn in Monday as the new Secretary of Housing and
Urban Development.
   Bush made the first visit by a president to the Housing and Urban
Development Department since Jimmy Carter a dozen years ago to watch
as his former rival for the Republican presidential nomination was
administered the oath of office by Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor.
   ``Jack's a man of ideas, and I've made clear I want him to apply
his creativity and energy to the area of housing and urban policy,
which are one of the most important and challenging issues in
America today,'' Bush said. ``These problems require a compassionate
strategy, and that's the reason I thought of Jack immediately and
asked him to take this job.''
   The references to football were frequent as Kemp, the former
professional football quarterback, invited a pair of friends to join
him for the ceremony _ Washington Redskins coach Joe Gibbs, and Gene
Upshaw, president of the National Football League Players
Association.
   Gibbs brought a football and tossed it to Kemp, who tossed it to
Bush as hundreds of HUD employees watched. There were no
incompletions, but the passes hardly covered one yard.
   Bush called Kemp, who left the House of Representatives after 18
years, an ``all-pro congressman'' and ``a great quarterback'' at
HUD. Kemp, thanking Bush for his remarks, said, ``I particularly
liked the part, Mr. President, about a kinder, gentler quarterback.''
   Bush said his administration will push for urban enterprise
zones, using tax incentives to encourage job-creating business in
inner cities, and look for innovative ways to improve public housing
and make home ownership available to its tenants.
   ``I believe that given a chance, economic freedom can bring a
revival to the inner city, and it can create jobs and housing and
dignity for every citizen,'' Bush said.
   Kemp pledged to ``help end the appalling tragedy of
homelessness,'' and to expand the number of eligible families
receiving ``housing assistance and housing opportunities.''
   ``Our mission is to inject oxygen and seed corn and new life and
new hope into those distressed inner cities,'' Kemp said.
   Although the ceremony was held to swear in the new secretary,
Kemp has been on the job for a week. He received the oath privately
from the department's general counsel following his unanimous
confirmation by the Senate.
</TEXT>
