<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Soviet     02-13 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviet,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Soviet Ship In Israel In 22 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Soviet ship to visit Israel in 22
years sailed into the southern port of Ashdod Monday to pick up 80
tons of relief supplies for Armenian earthquake victims, Israel
radio reported.
   The relief supplies, mainly clothing and flour, were blessed at
the port by an Armenian priest in long, black, flowing robes before
it was loaded on the 2,000 ton Vitya Novitsky.
   ``We are very proud that the Russians agreed to specially send a
ship from Turkey to pick up everything,'' peace activist Abie Nathan
told the radio.
   Nathan, who also directs the ``Voice of Peace'' radio station,
has made a personal campaign over the airwaves to solicit disaster
relief contributions.
   He also was instrumental in persuading the Soviets to send a
Soviet-flagged vessel to transport the supplies.
   It was the first time a vessel flying the hammer and sickle
stopped in an Israeli port since the Soviet Union broke diplomatic
relations with Israel after the 1967 Middle East war.
   For the past two years, the two countries have exchanged
low-level consular delegations and have increased cultural ties.
   Foreign Ministry officials have said they view the warming of
relations as motivated by a Soviet desire to play a part in any
future Middle East peace process.
   Israel sent two teams of relief workers to Armenia to aid rescue
efforts following the December earthquake which killed tens of
thousands.
</TEXT>
