<DOCNO> AP890213-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TraderVic's     02-13 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trader Vic's,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Reconsiders Fate Of Polynesian Potion Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump's announcement last month
that he would close the Trader Vic's bar in his lordly Plaza Hotel
boosted business so much that Trump says he'll let the saloon stay
awhile.
   Trump initially said the pseudo-Polynesian saloon was tacky
beyond toleration for the luxury hotel overlooking Central Park and
Fifth Avenue.
   But he told the New York Post that he can put up with the
tackiness a little longer because, with old customers trooping in
for a farewell drink, business at Trader Vic's has doubled.
   ``I'm in no hurry to close it. It's a very successful operation
now,'' Trump said. ``But since it's the greatest location in the
world, anything would be successful there.''
   The bar also got help from stories in newspapers ranging from the
Wall Street Journal to the Village Voice, and a New York Times
editorial pining over the passing of such Trader Vic's specials as
the Mai Tai or the Scorpion with floating gardenia, the Samoan Fog
Cutter or the Dr. Funk of Tahiti.
   The restaurant part of Trader Vic's, which operated from the
Plaza basement for 25 years, closed a year ago, but the bar stayed
open.
   Trump, who bought the Plaza last year for $390 million, said in
January that a classy Oriental restaurant and a health club would
replace Trader Vic's beginning in April or May.
   ``I now have no set timetable on this,'' he says now. ``I haven't
decided what to do with the space yet.''
   The Trader Vic's chain operates more than a score of restaurants
in the United States, Canada, West Germany and Japan.
</TEXT>
