<FIRST>r a AM-StolenMasterpieces     02-13 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stolen Masterpieces,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine Couple Held On Charges Of Stealing Masterworks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Argentine police commissioner and his wife
were held Monday on charges of conspiring to sell stolen paintings
worth as much as $100 million by such masters as El Greco and Goya,
FBI officials said.
   Juan Carlos Longo, 53, and his wife, Hilda, 40, who have homes in
Buenos Aires and Miami, were held without bond in pretrial detention
after being arrested last week, the FBI said.
   During the investigation, Longo told an informant, posing as a
dealer of stolen artworks, that 11 paintings stolen from Argentine
museums were split between two groups in Argentina, and one of the
groups was composed of police officials, according to an FBI
affidavit.
   Longo told the informant that people who stole the paintings
``paid for their freedom'' by giving ``half the paintings to police
officials,'' said the FBI affidavit from agent James D. Keith.
   Some of the information in the affidavit was corroborated by
taped conversations, the international law enforcement agency
Interpol, and the Argentine government, the FBI said.
   The Longos were arrested at the Westin Hotel on Feb. 6 after the
informant set up the purchase of ``Doves and Hens,'' a masterpiece
by Goya, allegedly stolen from the Castagnino Museum of Rosario,
Argentina, on March 24, 1987, the FBI said.
   The ``Doves and Hens'' piece was valued at $500,000, said FBI
spokesman Paul Miller. The worth of the 11 stolen paintings was
placed between $50 million and $100 million, Miller said.
   Longo was arrested after turning over the Goya painting to an
undercover agent posing as a wealthy art expert representing foreign
investors, the FBI said. His wife was arrested as she waited in a
car outside.
   The Longos' attorney, Fred Schwartz, did not contest the pretrial
detention. ``I may appeal detention to a district judge,'' Schwartz
said, ``but first I want to hear the tapes.''
   Miller said the FBI is working closely with Argentine federal
police.
   ``We are providing them with information and they are providing
us with information and we understand there will be arrests in
Buenos Aires,'' Miller said.
   The FBI affidavit told of two separate Argentine robberies
involving the theft of masterpieces.
   A 1983 robbery from the Estevez Municipal Museum in Rosario
bagged five paintings, including those by Bartolome Esteban Murillo,
Sanchez Coelmo, and El Greco.
   In March 1987, the Castagnino Museum lost six paintings in an
armed robbery, including works by Magnasco Alessandro, Tiziano
Vecellio and Goya.
   The affidavit said that a confidential informant in October was
approached by Longo, who offered to sell masterpieces stolen in
Argentina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
