<DOCNO> AP890213-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Drugs     02-13 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran To Hang 70 Drug Smugglers in One Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran says it will hang 70 drug traffickers
Tuesday, the highest number to be executed in one day in that
nation's fierce anti-narcotics crackdown aimed at stopping the flow
to at least 1 million addicts.
   Hard-line Prosecuter-General Musavi Khoeiniha said in a recent
radio interview: ``This is the end of the line. If we do not destroy
them (drug smugglers) they will destroy our youths.''
   Khoeiniha first gained fame in 1979 as the guiding hand behind
the militant extremists who stormed the U.S. Embassy, holding 52
hostages for 444 days.
   Iran instituted a new law on Jan. 21 that includes the death
penalty for anyone found with 30 grams (just over an ounce) of
heroin or five kilograms (11 pounds) of opium or hashish. Addicting
someone else carries a 20-year sentence.
   The law coincided with a crackdown that put helicopter gunships
into the air along the borders with Pakistan and Afghanistan to
track smugglers.
   On Jan. 16, a record 56 drug smugglers were executed. The
official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, says
105 smugglers have been executed since Dec. 31.
   The Iranian resistance group Mujahedeen Khalq accuses the Iranian
government of creating hysteria over the drug problem as a means of
extending a siege mentality and eliminating its enemies following
the 8-year Iran-Iraq war.
   An IRNA report on Tuesday's executions said 10 will be hanged in
Tehran and the rest in cities throughout Iran.
   Executions were suspended during a 10-day celebration that ended
Feb. 11 to mark the 10th anniversary of the revolution that toppled
the late Shah in 1979.
   Iranian police released statistics Monday saying 3,300 drug
traffickers have been arrested in Iran since 1987 and 11 metric tons
of opium, 1,540 pounds of heroin and 2.3 metric tons of hashish
seized.
   Drug addicts now have six months to kick the habit or face jail.
Addiction is not considered a medical problem in Iran.
   The prosecutor-general said: ``If an addict's decision to give up
his habit is serious he needs nothing else. They should not expect
the government to treat them as patients.''
   Iran has blamed everyone from underground opposition movements to
the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency for trying to turn Iranian
youth into addicts.
   Iranians leaving the country said many youths turned to drugs to
escape the intense pressure they faced to conform to Islamic
principals as Iran was reborn as a fundamentalist state.
   The draft in the ``holy war'' against Iraq was another factor,
they said.
   Iranian press reports concentrate on ways of eliminating drug
supplies rather than the cause of addiction.
   Khoeiniha said one way around the death penalty was to turn
others in.
   ``If they (smugglers) report themselves, repent, name old traders
and cooperate with discovering the rings certainly we will request
the great leader (Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini) to grant them parole.
Otherwise ... they will be punished according to the law.''
   In other developments in Iran on Monday:
   _Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani denied in an interview
allegations of a power struggle within Iran's top leadership, and
dismissed reports in world media of mass executions of political
opponents, Tehran radio reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said Rafsanjani responded to a
question from a French TV journalist asking about reports from
Amnesty International that more than 1,000 political foes were
executed since summer.
   _Iran announced it planned to free 260 disabled or ailing Iraqi
prisoners of war next week, Tehran radio said in another report.
   In Geneva, President Cornelio Sommaruga of the International
Committee of the Red Cross expressed concern about the slow
repatriation of prisoners and said Iran and Iraq were not fulfilling
their international obligations. U.N. officials estimate the number
of war prisoners in both countries at 100,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-INSEviction     02-13 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS Eviction,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Service Regains Access to Asylum Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday overrode
local authorities and ordered the reopening of a refugee processing
center that was padlocked last week as a health and fire hazard.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela set aside at least temporarily
an order Friday by a state district judge that had barred the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service from using the center in
Harlingen.
   ``There's between 200 and 300 people outside there right now
waiting to be processed,'' Omer G. Sewell, INS director in
Harlingen, 25 miles north of this border city, said shortly after
the court action.
   Later, he said immigration officials regained access to the
building and planned to begin seeing applicants again Tuesday
morning.
   More than 2,000 people a week, most from Central America, have
been applying for political asylum at the INS Harlingen office. Many
of the applicants have camped near the building while waiting for
their paperwork to be processed.
   City officials, who had sued in state district court to be
allowed to padlock the center, said they would comply with Vela's
order once they've seen it.
   ``As far as I am concerned, it (the center) is still closed. I
have not been served (with Vela's order),'' said Gavino Sotelo,
Harlingen city manager. ``The conditions at the center remain the
same as they were before. There is trash, there is human waste. If
this goes on, we might have to close it all over again.''
   Harlingen Mayor Bill Card said once the center is open, the city
will regularly inspect it and will notify Sewell of any violations
found.
   ``We just want to make sure that the facility is operated
properly. If it had been operated in a responsible way before, it
would have never been closed,'' Card said.
   Sewell said barring the INS from the building in Harlingen would
have created another crisis of homeless Central Americans in the Rio
Grande Valley.
   The last such crisis led Vela to issue an order Jan. 9 to force
the INS to allow the applicants to pursue their cases at their
intended U.S. destination after checking in with the INS in
Harlingen.
   Huge crowds also gathered at the building when it was used for
processing those who applied for amnesty under the Immigration
Reform and Control Act of 1986.
   The current backlog involves the immigration policy that calls
for refugee status for those found to be fleeing for political
reasons, but deportation for undocumented aliens entering for
economic reasons.
   In overturning a Friday order by state District Judge Robert
Garza, Vela said it ``prohibits the functions and operations of an
agency of the federal government.'' Vela also barred Harlingen
officials from restricting INS access to the 9,872-square-foot
former furniture store and from interfering with INS business there
``in any manner whatsoever.''
   He said, however, that his order should not be interpreted to
mean the INS does not have to comply with state or local laws or
ordinances related to public health and fire safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
