<DOCNO> AP890213-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-North-SouthKorea     02-13 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North-South Korea,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Alleges Armistice Violations, Demand End To Exercises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Monday accused South Korea
of a sea intrusion and two shootings across the border and blamed
U.S.-South Korean military exercises for suspended reconciliation
talks.
   Maj. Gen. Choi Ui Ung, senior North Korean delegate to the 446th
meeting of the Korean Military Armistice Commission in this truce
village, demanded the annual military exercises be stopped, calling
them provocations and an obstacle to talks between the communist
north and the pro-Western south.
   The general said the intrusions occurred between Feb. 3 and 12
and were ``grave provocations.'' No injuries were reported.
   The United Nations Command, which comprises the United States and
other Korean War allies, said one shooting incident across the
border was caused by ``an accidental firing'' and that the north was
already notified about it.
   The command promised to investigate the other alleged incidents.
   Choi blamed the United States and South Korea for the suspension
of Friday's scheduled parliamentary meeting in the same location.
   Pyognyang unilaterally boycotted the meeting, saying the joint
exercises called Team Spirit were offensive and preparations for a
nuclear war against the north.
   U.S. Navy Rear Adm. William T. Pendley, speaking for the United
Nations Command, said the north was using Team Spirit as an excuse,
but he did not elaborate.
   North Korea has called for removal of all 42,000 U.S. troops
stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Pendley also renewed his command's previous demand that North
Korea return all United Nations Command remains from the 1950-53
Korean War that ``you have publicly acknowledged that you are
holding.''
   Allied officials said the war remains included at least those of
two Americans. There was no North Korean response in the two
hour-meeting.
   The admiral renewed his command's perennial offer to invite North
Koreans to come to the south and observe Team Spirit. The North did
not respond as in the past. The exercises were reported to have
begun last week but there was no official confirmation.
   The north also demanded an end to Team Spirit on Wednesday, when
government officials from both Koreas met in Panmunjom to discuss
plans for the two Koreas' first meeting of prime ministers. No
progress was made because of the north's refusal to take up
procedural matters unless the south agreed to end Team Spirit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
