<FIRST>u a AM-FloridaSpaceport 1stLd-Writethru a0630 02-13 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Spaceport, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0630,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Endorses Plan For Commercial Spaceports</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS to Samuel sted Samual in 5th graf. Recasts 7th graf,
`A Spaceport...' to describe rockets.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida should move ahead with plans
to develop the nation's first commercial spaceports on Florida's
Space Coast and in the Panhandle, Gov. Bob Martinez said Monday.
   Martinez told a news conference he will recommend legislation
creating a Spaceport Authority to oversee the project and will
include $10 million in his budget proposal for the effort.
   ``When America enters the space commerce industry, it should be
from Florida,'' the governor said, adding the spaceport could make
use of many existing facilities at Cape Canaveral and the Kennedy
Space Center.
   ``Here in Florida we are uniquely positioned to serve as
America's launching pad,'' he said. ``We have the time, we have the
place, we have the talent, and we have the resources.''
   U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner appeared with
Martinez and said the federal government fully supports the Florida
effort, as well as similar efforts being pushed by Hawaii and
Virginia.
   ``Florida is leading in many aspects of the competition,''
Skinner said. ``The state that provides the money and effort to make
this work will get the most government support.''
   A Spaceport Florida study says that a facility for launching
small rockets that carry instruments to take various scientific
soundings should be built at Cape San Blas, near Port St. Joe in the
Panhandle's Gulf County. It also recommends two potential sites near
the Kennedy Space Center _ Cape Canaveral Air Force Station, using
three inactive launch pads once used for Atlas and Titan missiles,
and the abandoned town of Shiloh.
   Martinez said he is directing the Florida Department of Commerce
to take steps to develop the facility at Cape San Blas and to
determine which of the two sites near the Kennedy Space Center would
be best for launching large payloads into orbit.
   The study estimated the Cape San Blas site could be developed for
about $200,000 and could be open in nine to 12 weeks. The Air Force
once launched sounding rockets and many facilities are still
available.
   According to the study, development of an orbital launch
facilities on the east coast would require about three years.
   Ralph Christi, project leader for United Engineers and
Construction, the consultant that did the study for the state, said
a spaceport could be funded like an airport, through revenue bonds
or corporate debt.
</TEXT>
