<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 2053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Armstrong     02-13 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armstrong,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado Senator Announces He Will Not Seek Re-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Armstrong, a Colorado Republican who
has served in Congress since 1973, said Monday that he will not seek
re-election in 1990.
   Armstrong, 51, told reporters at a news conference in his Denver
office that he was tempted to run, but two terms is enough.
   ``I have never believed the great opportunity, or the greatness
of this country is centered in the U.S. Senate,'' he said.
   ``I thought that 12 years was about the right length of time.''
   Armstrong, who served from 1973-78 as a congressman and at
various times has been eyed as a candidate for president and vice
president by fellow conservatives, is Colorado's senior Republican
officeholder in Congress.
   ``I love to campaign. So heading out on the campaign trail to
meet people, shake hands and make speeches would be great fun. Based
on polling and the advice of friends who have offered to help, I
believe I would have a good chance to be re-elected,'' he said.
   But Armstrong added, ``I have considered myself and have wanted
others to think of me as a citizen legislator serving in Congress
for a time, but always with a firm intention of returning to private
life.''
   He said he would remain active in politics and did not close the
door on a run for the governorship.
   ``It's conceivable,'' he said. ``I won't rule it out. Who knows?''
   Armstrong said he will devote his time to unspecified business
concerns. He owns television stations in Twin Falls and Pocatello,
Idaho, and is building one in Jackson, Wyo.
   For years, Armstrong owned and worked at KOSI, a major radio
station in the Denver market. A born-again evangelical Christian, he
did several commercials for a Bible study organization before his
re-election in 1984.
   He maintains an interest in evangelical religion, he said, but he
does not plan to enter what he called ``the vocational ministry.''
   ``I don't see myself in that role.''
   Armstrong said he also would consider establishing his own
foundation or think tank.
   His announcement means there will be a wide-open race for his
seat in 1990. Republicans mentioned as possible contenders include
state Sen. Terry Considine, state Rep. Chris Paulson, and U.S. Reps.
Hank Brown and Joel Hefley. Armstrong would not say Monday whether
he planned to endorse anyone as a possible successor.
   On the Democratic side, former Gov. Richard Lamm, who had been
considered a likely candidate, announced recently he would not seek
the seat, but State Democratic Chairman Buie Seawell and U.S. Rep.
Ben Nighthorse Campbell are believed to have a strong interest in
running.
   Before being elected to the Senate in 1978, Armstrong represented
Colorado's 5th Congressional District, which includes Colorado
Springs. Before that, he spent a decade in the Colorado Legislature,
serving as Senate majority leader from 1969-72.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
