<FIRST>r a AM-WVaDeficit     02-13 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WVa Deficit,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caperton Proposes $765 Million in Borrowing, Abolishing Some Offices</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CN3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Gaston Caperton on Monday proposed
a ``bold and agressive'' program of cuts and said the state still
has to borrow as much as $765 million to pay its bills, improve
schools and develop economically.
   Caperton, making his first State of the State address, said he
wants to abolish the jobs of agriculture commissioner, secretary of
state and treasurer. The governor also asked for 5 percent pay
raises for public school teachers and state workers.
   The first-term Democrat presented lawmakers with a proposed
$1.781 billion budget for 1989-90, with budget cuts averaging 4.5
percent for all state agencies except education, health and human
services. The current state budget is $1.464 billion.
   ``The program I have presented ... is bold and aggressive,''
Caperton said. ``It will most assuredly bring out the critics, but
it will also bring out the best in West Virginia, and in us.''
   Caperton defeated three-term Gov. Arch Moore last year in a
campaign that assailed Moore's financial management. A special
legislative session earlier this month approved $392 million in tax
increases to help close a growing deficit and boost the state's
economy, which has been hurt by a slump in its dominant industries,
especially coal. Caperton asked for no additional revenue other than
the borrowing authority.
   The current projected state deficit is $260 million by June 30,
the end of this fiscal year, and $376 million by next year.
   The borrowing would include:
   _up to $500 million for school construction, including raising
$120 million in bonds reissued through the 1972 Better Schools
Amendment.
   _$135 million to be obtained from private lenders, possibly a
consortium of West Virginia banks.
   _$130 million, to be repaid through tolls, as part of a plan to
replace the West Virginia Turnpike with the West Virginia Parkway
Economic Development and Tourism Authority.
   Caperton proposed two constitutional amendments: one to eliminate
the jobs of agriculture commissioner, secretary of state and
treasurer; and one to allow cities and counties to decide on their
own form of government, including the possibility of forming joint
municipal-county governments or even merging two or more counties.
   Gubernatorial aide Phil Reale said the proposed amendments, which
must be approved by two-thirds of both the House of Delegates and
Senate, probably would be placed on the ballot for voter
ratification in a special election this fall.
   The 5 percent pay raise for teachers and state employees would
depend on whether the state can save $40 million to $45 million in
the first six months of the 1989-90 fiscal year.
</TEXT>
