<FIRST>r i AM-China-Bhutto     02-13 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Bhutto,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Meets Pakistan Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping held ``very
friendly and nostalgic'' talks Monday with Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto of Pakistan and recalled her father's friendship with past
Chinese leaders, Pakistan's ambassador said.
   ``I knew your father very well,'' Ambassador M. Akram Zaki quoted
Deng as telling Ms. Bhutto at a 40-minute meeting in Shanghai.
   The evening television news showed Deng holding his hands up
palms together to greet Ms. Bhutto in Moslem fashion, smiling
broadly as he did so.
   Zaki said the talks covered a general survey of Pakistani-Chinese
relationship, with some reminiscences by Deng about Ms. Bhutto's
father, the late Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto.
   The official Chinese news agency Xinhua quoted Deng as saying:
``Your father was a friend of the late Chairman Mao Tse-tung. Your
parents established a special relationship with the late Premier
Chou En-lai and his wife, Deng Yingchao. I personally have had
contacts with your family for a long time.''
   The elder Bhutto, president from 1971-73 and prime minister from
1973 until he was ousted in a 1976 coup and later executed, made
friendship with China a key element of his foreign policy.
   By choosing China for her first official foreign trip since being
elected last November, Benazir Bhutto sought to emphasize this
longstanding tie. The two sides signed agreements to extend a trade
protocol and encourage mutual investment, but expressions of
friendship dominated over substance.
   ``The torch of Pakistan-China friendship has been passed on to a
new generation who will surely ... pass (it) on to the next
generation,'' Xinhua quoted Ms. Bhutto as telling Deng.
   ``It was a very successful visit,'' Zaki said as Ms. Bhutto
prepared to leave Shanghai for home. ``The meetings with all the
top-ranking leaders produced complete identity of views.''
   Ms. Bhutto also met Monday with President Yang Shangkun and on
Sunday with Premier Li Peng and Communist Party General Secretary
Zhao Ziyang.
   Zaki reported the 84-year-old Deng meeting ``in very good
health.''
   He said the Bhutto-Yang talks included the current Soviet troop
withdrawal from Afghanistan after 10 years and said ``both hoped .
.. there would be a broad-based government peacefully established.''
He did not elaborate.
   Ms. Bhutto later confirmed to Western reporters that she met in
Beijing with Iran's ambassador to China, Alaeddin Broujerdi, and
discussed the disputes between Pakistan-based Afghan guerrillas and
those based in Iran. She gave no details.
   The guerrillas, aided by Pakistan, Iran and the United States,
have been fighting the Soviet-backed Afghan government since 1978.
The main dispute is over sharing of power after the Soviets leave.
   Afghanistan and fear of Soviet ambitions in Asia have been major
factors in Chinese-Pakistani ties. Mutual hostility with India has
been another. China recently held a fence-mending summit with India
and plans one with the Soviet Union in May, but relations with
Pakistan are expected to remain close.
</TEXT>
