<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru a0656 02-13 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protestant Group Claims Responsibility For Slaying Of Catholic Lawyer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Finucane's widow also criticizing
British official's comment and denying husband was IRA member. Pick up
9th pvs, `Northern Ireland...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Protestant vigilante group
claimed responsiblility Monday for killing a prominent Roman
Catholic lawyer. His widow and and Irish nationalists accused a
British official of making him a target.
   Patrick Finucane, who acted for clients involved in the outlawed
Irish Republican Army's campaign against British rule, was fatally
shot Sunday night by three men who stormed his home in north Belfast.
   His wife, Geraldine, was shot in the ankle but was in
satisfactory condition in a hospital. Their three children were not
hurt.
   On Monday, the outlawed Ulster Freedom Fighters telephoned a
coded message to the British Broadcasting Corp. in Belfast claiming
responsibility for the attack. The group said it ``shot Pat Finucane
the Provisional IRA officer, not Pat Finucane the solicitor.''
   ``While the Provisional IRA threaten and shoot Loyalist
(Protestant) construction workers ... the inevitable retaliation
will take place,'' the statement said.
   The IRA has targeted workers who do maintenance and construction
work for the police and British army in Northern Ireland.
   Mrs. Finucane denied her husband was an IRA member.
   ``Pat was a solicitor (attorney) who worked for human rights and
civil liberties. He defended both Catholic and Protestant alike,''
she said in a statement to the British domestic news agency Press
Association.
   She also criticized junior Home Office Minister Douglas Hogg for
telling a parliamentary committee discussing an anti-terrorist bill
that some Northern Ireland lawyers were ``unduly sympathetic'' to
guerrilla groups. Hogg's remarks were raised in the House of Commons
on Jan. 31.
   ``We firmly believe that it was instrumental in Pat's death,''
she said.
   Danny Morrison, vice president of the IRA's legal political arm,
Sinn Fein, said Hogg's comment provided the ``pretext for the
slaying of Mr. Finucane.''
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, the British Cabinet minister
responsible for the province, said Monday he believed Hogg's
comments had nothing to do with the slaying.
   ``Not at all,'' King said. ``I think that Mr. Finucane was well
known for the work he did for the clients he had.''
   In Dublin, Irish Prime Minister Charles Haughey called the
killing a ``particularly disturbing development'' and a ``major
attack on the system of justice in Northern Ireland.''
   He defended lawyers in Northern Ireland as acting
``conscientiously, impartially and courageously to anyone in the
community who has been accused of a crime.''
   Finucane, 38, was involved in the County Armagh inquest into the
1983 police killings of three unarmed IRA guerrillas. He also
succeeded in having charges dropped against a man in connection with
the killing of two soldiers at an IRA funeral last year.
   The predominantly Catholic Irish Republican Army is fighting to
push the British out of this Protestant-dominated province and unite
it with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
