<FIRST>u i AM-CentralAmerica 3rdLd-Writethru a0685 02-13 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0685,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central American Summit Quickly Bogs Down Over Democracy Measures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with squabble bogging down summit, quotes,
other. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COSTA DEL SOL, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A summit of the five Central
American presidents bogged down on opening day Monday in a dispute
involving Nicaragua and at least two other nations over how to
appraise progress toward democracy.
   An adviser to the Sandinistas said earlier Monday that Nicaragua
was making strong democratic commitments because it believes the
rebel movement is dead.
   ``With the Contras' military defeat and the passing of the Reagan
administration, the external military threat to the Nicaraguan
government that impeded democratization is gone,'' said Paul
Reichler, a U.S. lawyer employed by Nicaragua as an adviser and
representative.
   Later, however, foreign ministers Miguel D'Escoto of Nicaragua
and Ricardo Acevedo of El Salvador clashed publicly over whether
commissions to monitor progress toward democracy should include
Central Americans or foreign participants.
   ``We have the moral authority to select a commission of Central
Americans. We should carry out our own verification,'' Acevedo told
a news conference.
   ``It seems to us somewhat anti-democratic that it should be we
ourselves who appraise our own actions,'' D'Escoto told a separate
news conference.
   The two spoke as presidents Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua, Jose
Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador, Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras,
Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala and Oscar Arias of Costa Rica worked in
closed session late into the first day of a two-day summit.
   Costa Rica reportedly was siding with El Salvador in the dispute.
   ``They're going at each other quite harshly,'' said a member of
the Nicaraguan delegation, commenting on condition of anonymity.
   The meeting intends to breathe new life into the stalled
Esquipulas II plan designed to promote peace and demcoracy in the
region.
   Since the presidents signed the accord in August 1987,
Nicaragua's regional partners _ especially El Salvador, Costa Rica
and Honduras _ have criticized Nicaragua for what they alleged is an
authoritarian Sandinista regime.
   ``The political problem in the region is one of democracy _ of
totalitarianism versus liberty,'' Acevedo said.
   Officials with the Nicaraguan delegation said Ortega proposed a
bilateral agreement with Honduras that calls for the estimated
11,000-strong Contra force there to be disbanded. The Contras fled
to Honduras after U.S. military aid expired last year.
   Under the proposal, the Contras could take advantage of an
amnesty offered by the Sandinistas or go to third countries under
the supervision of international organizations. The Sandinistas
would release the estimated 3,500 Contras and former Nicaraguan
national guardsmen now in Sandinista prisons.
   The officials said Ortega presented the plan to Azcona at the
Feb. 2 inauguration of Venezuelan President Carlos Andres Perez.
   The five presidents first appeared encouraged by the mere fact of
being under the same roof after six months of delay. The summit was
rescheduled and postponed five times.
   ``I am sure that we, with optimism, will analyze efforts we've
made according to Esquipulas II and search for favorable solutions
that will promote peace and progress in Central America,'' Duarte
said as the meeting began.
   All the chief executives except Ortega, in a green army uniform,
wore casual attire fitting the climate of this seaside resort 40
miles southeast of San Salvador.
   They had intended to mark the anniversary of the signing with a
summit in August, but could not agree on an agenda.
   After some initial success, the Arias plan stalled last year.
   Officials said the summit's principal subject would be enforcing
compliance with the injunction against using one signatory's
territory as a base for attacking another, but the presidents
disagree on verification mechanisms.
   Arias is said to favor a commission of Central Americans, but
Nicaraguan officials said their government wants the United Nations,
the Organization of American States and human rights groups included
on such a panel.
   All the presidents expressed support for the framework
constructed last week by their foreign ministers in talks with U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   The ministers want ``an impartial mechanism'' created for on-site
verification of compliance. The tentative idea is to form an
observer group from Canada, Spain and West Germany.
   Arias, the 1987 Nobel Peace laureate, said the summit would
``re-establish our credibility with the Central American people and
the entire world.''
   A decade of civil conflict and economic depression have
transformed the region of 25 million people into a zone of
turbulence. An estimated 160,000 people have been killed in wars in
a decade and most Central Americans live in extreme poverty.
   Civil wars still plague El Salvador and Guatemala but the scale
has been reduced greatly in Guatemala.
   The Contras signed a preliminary cease-fire with the Sandinistas
last March but Ortega's government stands accused of failing to make
good its pledge to strengthen democratic institutions and practices.
   El Salvador's Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the
Marxist-led insurgent army, announced a two-day truce for the
meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
