<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:WaterTankArt Adv15   02-13 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Water Tank Art, Adv 15,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, Feb. 15 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX7 of Feb. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Water Tank Sculptures Capture Disappearing City Scene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When archaeologists dig up Lisa Harris' sculptures
centuries from now, they'll find clues to yet another era that has
gone down the drain.
   In the past month, the 35-year-old artist has created some 20
terra cotta water tanks, ranging from 2 inches to 2 feet. To Harris,
it's a way of commemorating the real-life rooftop towers, which to
her resemble monuments to the industrial age.
   ``I'm a child of the city and think there is a lot of beauty to
be found in the city's ugliness,'' Harris said.
   But the artist's models have been disappearing, with demolition
teams casting them them off the city's skyline faster than she can
cast them in clay.
   The rooftop tanks have been here since the late 1800s, when the
city was rebuilding from the Great Chicago Fire of 1871. They were
put on the high-rises of the time, buildings more than several
stories high.
   The filled tanks improved water pressure and served as resevoirs
from which to draw during emergencies. They were a craft in
themselves, at first made like wooden barrels with tongue-and-groove
seams so perfect that no extra seal was needed to hold the water.
   Harris found the models for her art in a changing industrial area
on Chicago's Near North Side. She drove there on another errand late
last year and decided to get out of her car and tour on foot.
   ``There was a whole vista of them,'' she said.
   She photographed some, sketched others. She studied the tanks,
trying to decide what techniques and materials she could use to
reproduce the ladders, capture the colors and portray the peeling
paint and weathered wood.
   Then, in her studio, she began constructing them, throwing clay
on a potter's wheel and adding hand-built parts for tops, stilts and
buildings. She fired them in a kiln and chose 10 for the show,
naming some for streets where she'd seen the real tanks.
   But by the time the exhibit opened Jan. 20, three of the real
tanks had been knocked down.
   ``Better water pumps have negated their use,'' said Lawrence
Acker, president of the Plumbing Contractors Association.
   Insurance companies still discount premiums for buildings with
tanks because the reservoirs provide extra protection, Acker said.
But a wave of housing rehabilitation work in recent years is
hastening the demise of the vessels. Old factories with tanks are
being converted into town houses with more modern plumbing. Old
schools are being gutted for lofts, and old housing is being made to
look newer.
   ``Progress,'' Harris said.
   Meanwhile, her exhibit will continue this month at the Lill
Street Gallery, a studio, gallery and ceramics school housed in a
building that was a horse barn when Lill Street was at the edge of
the city and at the end of the trolley line.
   Harris, a teacher at the school, says so far people seem to be
intrigued by the show.
   ``It looks stark,'' she said. ``It looks like a Chicago
cityscape. ...''
   The way it used to be.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Wed Feb. 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
