<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV14   02-13 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV 14,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues Feb 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Kinder, Gentler Cliche</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kindly, gently, and, it seems interminably, the
phrase that became a George Bush cliche is being used for him,
against him and all around him.
   The president spared it another repetition in what amounted to
his State of the Union address Thursday night _ he spoke of decency,
compassion, generosity, government that helps people, but he skipped
``kinder and gentler.''
   Bush was one of the few orators who did.
   ``A kinder, gentler America?'' House Speaker Jim Wright said in
the Democratic response to the president. ``That's the old time
Democratic religion. We embrace it enthusiastically.''
   There is the matter of agreeing on what it means. Wright said
words and gestures won't do _ it will cost money. By Democratic
reckoning, considerably more money than Bush proposes to spend.
   Wright finds the phrase a handy one. ``Obviously this is not a
kinder, gentler budget,'' the speaker said when President Reagan
sent Congress his farewell spending proposal.
   Bush adjusted spending priorities, notably by reducing the
proposed Pentagon budget, but Democrats still used the K word and
the G word to criticize his proposal.
   ``He's offering a minimum down payment on a kinder, gentler
America,'' said Sen. James Sasser of Tennessee, chairman of the
Budget Committee. ``But I can't see how he's proposing to meet the
necessary installment payments. They might have to repossess his
kinder, gentler America for failure to meet the payments.''
   But Richard Darman, Bush's budget director, said the new
administration's budget would, too, make the nation kinder and
gentler, although perhaps not as rapidly as everyone would like.
   Kinder and gentler than the Reagan administration?
   ``Well, I'm not saying that,'' Darman replied.
   He said the Bush budget seeks more money for education,
environmental cleanups, aid to the homeless, Medicaid for the needy
and like programs. ``If they are marks of a ... kinder, gentler
society, then it meets that test. ...''
   Democratic National Chairman Ronald H. Brown quickly joined the
oratorical game. Praising the achievements of Democratic governors,
Brown said ``for these leaders, kinder and gentler doesn't come from
the pen of some ghost writer. It comes from the heart.''
   Brown, installed last Friday, said the next time the
administration says ``we need leadership that's kinder and gentler,
I'm going to ask kinder and gentler than whom? The Republican
Party?''
   In 1992, chimed in Willie Brown, speaker of the California House,
``we will capture the White House and give this nation a kinder and
gentler leader.''
   That crop of Ks and Gs represents only the tip of the cliche. It
covers usage by a handful of political spokesmen since last
Thursday. A check of Associated Press files turned up 140 stories
using the phrase since the Nov. 8 election.
   It has become fodder for TV comics, promising kinder and gentler
one-liners. On Groundhog Day, forecasts were for another six weeks
of a kinder and gentler winter.
   Bush used his own line repeatedly during the presidential
campaign _ startling his strategists one night when he said he'd be
kinder and gentler, and would stop negative campaigning against Gov.
Michael Dukakis. By morning, he had decided otherwise.
   In conversation, trying to remember a man's name, Bush described
him as a kinder and gentler looking fellow.
   In the inaugural address, he declared a mission ``to make kinder
the face of the nation and gentler the face of the world.''
   All of this flowed from a passage in his acceptance speech last
Aug. 18 at the Republican National Convention, crafted by campaign
speechwriter Peggy Noonan, who should have signed up for royalties
on use of the line.
   ``The fact is prosperity has a purpose,'' Bush said. ``It is to
allow us to pursue the better angels, to give us time to think and
grow. Prosperity with a purpose means taking your idealism and
making it concrete by certain acts of goodness. It means helping a
child from an unhappy home learn how to read ... It means teaching
troubled children through your presence that there's such a thing as
reliable love. Some would say it's soft and insufficiently tough to
care about these things. But where is it written that we must act as
if we do not care, as if we are not moved?
   ``Well I am moved,'' he said. ``I want a kinder, gentler nation.''
   That's the line that stuck, outlasting the cryptic thousand
points of light turned on in the same speech.
   But after six months, it might be kinder and gentler to dream up
a new catch phrase.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington for more than 25
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
