<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-CypriotUniversity Adv22   02-13 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cypriot University, Adv 22,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs Feb. 22 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Greek Cypriots Openin a University; Turks Already Have One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of delay, the Greek Cypriot
community is founding a university in an effort to halt an exodus of
talented students and help reunify the war-divided Mediterranean
island.
   But when the Cyprus University opens next year, it will be
competing for international recognition with a 3-year-old Turkish
Cypriot university also seeking to become a prestigious higher
education center.
   Although Greek and Turkish Cypriot educators say they want
students from both communities, the island's long-running political
problems make that unlikely.
   ``Our university will teach in both Greek and Turkish, and
there'll be a department of Turkish studies,'' the Greek Cypriot
education minister, Andreas Philippou, said in an interview.
   ``We want it to contribute to reuniting Cyprus. We hope Turkish
Cypriots will attend, but it depends on the political situation.''
   Professor Okan Tarhan, head of the East Mediterranean University
at Famagusta in the Turkish Cypriot republic in northern Cyprus,
said: ``We have students from 17 countries but no Greek Cypriots.''
   Cyprus was unofficially partitioned in 1974 when the Turkish army
invaded after an Athens-inspired coup intended to unite the island
with Greece.
   The breakaway Turkish Cypriot statelet was proclaimed in 1983 in
the northern one-third of the island occupied by the Turkish forces.
   Reunification talks between Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders on
a United Nation-proposed bi-zonal federation resumed last fall after
a three-year break but have bogged down amid traditional differences.
   Some Greek Cypriot officials fear that the de facto partition of
the island will harden as time goes by, with new generations growing
up on both sides with no contact with each other.
   ``Cyprus is a tiny place, but there's a great hunger for higher
education,'' said Margit Schatzman, an American educational
consultant preparing a study on the Cyprus universities.
   ``Both the Greek and Turkish Cypriot institutions are structuring
their programs along mainstream Western university lines. It's clear
they're both looking for international status,'' she said in a
telephone interview from Milwaukee, Wis.
   Education Minister Philippou, a former mathematics professor at
Patras University in Greece, said the university plan was drawn up
in three months last summer by a group of politicians and Cypriot
academics, including professors at U.S. and British universities.
   ``The decision to have a university was taken almost 20 years ago
but never implemented,'' he said. ``Now it must happen if we're to
stop losing good people who go abroad to study.''
   The Greek Cypriot university is due to open in 1990 in temporary
premises with 400 students and 30 faculty and eventually grow to
4,000 students and 330 faculty members. It is budgeted to cost $42
million.
   The planners say that having a local university will save a large
chunk of an estimated $24 million spent every year on sending 10,000
Cypriots to Greek, British and American universities.
   Many start careers overseas because, with more than 50,000
graduates among the 480,000 Greek Cypriots, jobs at home are hard to
find at home.
   The government offers free business courses to recent graduates
to make them employable in Cyprus' booming service economy, but
``with our own university we can channel people where they're needed
by offering development-related courses,'' Philippou said.
   Young Greek Cypriots say they welcome a university because it
will make Nicosia livelier as well as saving family funds.
   ``The university will bring lots of activities, there'll be more
music and cultural activities. I'm looking forward to it,'' said
Eleanor Palaiologou, who wants to study management.
   The Greek Cypriot Parliament will decide whether some courses
should be taught in English. But with a business school planned,
that may be essential to attract first-rate staff and students,
several educators said.
   The East Mediterranean University, where courses are taught in
English, has a problem because it is in the Turkish Cypriot
republic, which is recognized only by Turkey.
   ``We're an international university, but we don't qualify for aid
from any international organization,'' said Tarhan, the university's
head.
   ``I think that's unfair since we're an educational institution
and not involved in politics.''
   Foreigners from Arab countries, Iran and Pakistan make up around
10 percent of its 2,300 students. The rest are Turks and Turkish
Cypriots, but they also may spend a year taking intensive English
classes before starting as freshmen.
   East Mediterranean, a former junior technical college upgraded to
a university in 1986, focuses on engineering and economics. Tarhan
said a business school will open and more humanities courses will be
offered in the next two years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Feb. 22</NOTE>
