<SECOND>BC-History, Adv21,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday, Feb. 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Feb. 21, the 52nd day of 1989. There are 313
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Feb. 21, 1965, civil rights activist Malcolm X was shot to
death as he was about to speak to a rally of several hundred
followers in New York.
   On this date:
   In 1846, Sarah G. Bagley became the first female telegrapher when
she took charge at the newly opened telegraph office in Lowell, Mass.
   In 1866, Lucy B. Hobbs became the first woman to graduate from a
dental school, the Ohio College of Dental Surgery in Cincinnati.
   In 1878, the first telephone directory was issued, by the
District Telephone Company of New Haven, Conn. It listed 50 names.
   In 1885, the Washington Monument was dedicated in the nation's
capital.
   In 1916, the longest and bloodiest battle of World War I _ the
Battle of Verdun _ began in France.
   In 1925, The New Yorker magazine made its debut.
   In 1947, Edwin H. Land first demonstrated his Polaroid Land
camera, which used self-developing film that produced a
black-and-white photograph in 60 seconds.
   In 1972, President Richard M. Nixon began his historic visit to
mainland China.
   In 1973, Israeli fighter planes shot down a Libyan Airlines jet
over the Sinai Desert, killing more than 100 people.
   In 1983, former Vice President Walter F. Mondale launched his
campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination at the Minnesota
state Capitol.
   In 1986, two weeks after becoming the first American convicted of
spying for China, retired CIA analyst Larry Wu-Tai Chin took his
life in a Prince William County, Va., jail.
   On this date:
   Ten years ago: Iranian authorities released Marine Sgt. Kenneth
Kraus, 22, who had been taken into custody after an attack on the
U.S. Embassy in Tehran the previous week. Officials had said Kraus
would be tried on charges of firing on Iranians.
   Five years ago: U.S. Navy helicopters ferried Marine combat
troops from their base at Beirut International Airport to warships
in the Mediterranean as the Marine withdrawal from the Lebanese
capital got under way.
   One year ago: Television evangelist Jimmy Swaggart tearfully
confessed to his congregation in Baton Rouge, La., and his TV
audience that he was guilty of an unspecified sin, and said he was
leaving the pulpit temporarily.
   Today's birthdays: Columnist Erma Bombeck is 62. Fashion designer
Hubert de Givenchy is 62. Tricia Nixon Cox is 43. Actor Christopher
Atkins is 28.
   Thought for today: ``In scandal, as in robbery, the receiver is
always as bad as the thief.'' _ Lord Chesterfield, English author
and statesman (1694-1773).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for use Tuesday, Feb. 21</NOTE>
