<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:TapDancing Adv16-1stAdd   02-13 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Tap Dancing, Adv 16-1st Add,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEW YORK _ ``Black and Blue''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   When the brothers appeared in Hollywood movies in the '40s,
choreographer Nick Castle thought up ``mad tricks'' for the pair to
do, Harold said. Nick Castle Jr. wrote and directed ``Tap.''
   Most of the tappers had to take other jobs during the lean years,
said Henry Le Tang, 73, who choreographed ``Tap'' and most of
``Black and Blue.'' Honi Coles weathered those years working at the
Apollo Theater. Harold Nicholas spent the '50s working in Europe. Le
Tang, who always loved to teach, opened a tap school when he was 20.
   ``Tap was my love,'' Le Tang said. When its popularity waned, he
choreographed nightclub acts and, for seven years, TV's ``The Gary
Moore Show.''
   Fifteen-year-old Savion Glover, a tap prodigy as were the
Nicholas Brothers, Donald O'Connor and Mickey Rooney, absorbs every
style of tap, Le Tang said.
   ``The older dancers call him `the little sponge,''' hs said. ``As
he keeps getting more spectacular, his own style will start to come
out. It is beginning to happen and will continue to happen.''
   All the older tappers seem to have nicknames. ``I haven't heard
my real name in I don't know when,'' Sims said. Jimmy Slyde, who's
in both ``Tap'' and ``Black and Blue,'' specialized in sliding.
Bunny Briggs, 66, with his saucer eyes and Bambi-like lashes, dances
in both ``Tap'' and ``Black and Blue.'' He got his nickname from his
grandmother because when she'd come home from work, Bunny would
quickly scoot to get her slippers.
   ``I danced as soon as I was born,'' he said. ``When I saw Bill
Robinson dance, I knew I wanted to be a dancer. He sanctioned it.''
Briggs tapped with big bands as a visual addition and an added
rhythm instrument.
   The earliest forms of tap dancing can be found centuries ago in
parts of Africa and Ireland. It was further distilled in the United
States by African slaves and the immigrants who brought their clog
dancing with them to the new world.
   Tap started its current escalation on Broadway in 1971, when
``No, No, Nanette'' was revived. ``Eubie!'' came to Broadway and
Eubie Blake, whose music it comprised wanted Gregory and Maurice
Hines in it, recalling them from the act they had with their father
called Hines, Hines and Dad. The brothers went on to do ``Duke
Ellington's Sophisticated Ladies.''
   Alfonso Riberio originated the title role in ``The Tap Dance
Kid'' and the names of tappers such as Hinton Battle and Gregg Burge
got known around Broadway for that show and ``Sophisticated
Ladies.'' Lee Roy Reams brought Astaire-style tapping to ``42nd
Street.'' Honi Coles won a Tony as best supporting actor in a
musical in ``My One and Only.'' Patti LuPone taps today in the
revival of ``Anything Goes.''
   Upcoming are Broadway musicals in which Tommy Tune works with the
Manhattan Rhythm Kings and one in which Gregory Hines plays,
choreographs and dances as pianist-composer Jelly Roll Morton,
allowing tap to signify music.
   Le Tang is confident that tap will resume its proper position in
the arts.
   In the meantime, the International Tap Association is underway in
Boulder, Colo., giving the dance form an even greater credibility. A
project of the Colorado Dance Festival, the association has started
receiving inquiries from producers looking for tappers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Feb. 16</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
