<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ChicagoElection Adv26-2Takes   02-13 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Chicago Election, Adv 26-2 Takes,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: To be mailed to subscribers next week.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Chicagoans go to the polls this week in a special
mayoral election to decide who will serve the last two years of the
second term of the late Harold Washington, the city's first black
mayor. The leading candidates are two blacks hoping to win over
Washington's supporters and the son of the longtime political boss
Richard J. Daley.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ghosts of two former mayors are hovering over
the campaign trail as voters in the nation's third-largest city
decide who will lead them into the 1990s.
   Long gone is the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, a boss of the old
school, who used concentrated political muscle to run Chicago for 21
years before his death in 1976.
   But the front-runner in the special Democratic mayoral primary is
one of his sons, Richard M. Daley, the 46-year-old Cook County
state's attorney whose blood ties to City Hall legend sometimes seem
to transcend his own record.
   Gone as well is Harold Washington, the city's first black mayor,
whose death on Nov. 25, 1987, set the stage for this year's special
election.
   But his legacy of leadership is a key issue for black voters
being wooed by Mayor Eugene Sawyer, 54, Daley's chief primary rival,
and Alderman Timothy Evans, 45, who is running a third-party
campaign on the ``Harold Washington'' ticket.
   At stake in the special mayoral contest are the last two years of
Washington's second term.
   In the Democratic primary, Sawyer and Daley also face Lawrence
Bloom, a white alderman who supported Washington, and two lagging
candidates. Three Republicans _ none well known in this Democratic
stronghold _ were on the GOP ballot.
   After the Feb. 28 primary elections, Evans will take on the
winners in the April 4 general election.
   This campaign season, in a city known for its deep racial
divisions, black voters who united behind Washington are being
ardently courted by Sawyer and Evans.
   Neither can supplant the affable, streetwise Washington, who has
become a symbol of change and unity for many Chicagoans.
   ``Harold Washington...embodied all of the hopes and aspirations
of a generation of people who genuinely believed that Chicago was
ready for reform,'' said Cook County Recorder of Deeds Carol Moseley
Braun, who last fall became the first black to win a major county
office.
   Five weeks before the primary, Sawyer _ elected by the City
Council to succeed Washington _ finally won the endorsement of civil
rights leader and presidential contender Jesse Jackson.
   ``He has done more than any of his primary opponents to sustain
the Harold Washington coalition,'' Jackson said.
   But the delay in that long-awaited endorsement underscores the
discord in the black community since Washington's death.
   And Jackson declined to say where he would stand if Sawyer faced
Evans in the general election.
   Evans, who served as Washington's floor leader in the City
Council, is campaigning as the late mayor's heir apparent. His
withdrawal from the Democratic primary prevented a split in the
black vote that would have virtually guaranteed Daley the nomination.
   Jackson's endorsement was a matter of great concern to both black
candidates, but some observers say it won't help Sawyer.
   A massive black turnout is Sawyer's only chance in the primary,
said Paul Kleppner, author of ``Chicago Divided: The Making of a
Black Mayor'' and director of the Social Science Research Institute
at Northern Illinois University in De Kalb.
   ``My suspicion is that he (Sawyer) is going to get the
overwhelming bulk of the black vote, with moderate turnout _ and
that won't be enough,'' he said.
   Sawyer still has ``the image that he was put in there by the
white aldermen,'' Kleppner said, referring to the role of longtime
Washington foes in engineering Sawyer's election over Evans as
acting mayor in December 1987.
   ``Time heals a lot of wounds,'' counters Joseph Gardner,
Washington's former political office director, who endorsed Sawyer
and predicts a strong black turnout for him.
   The racial breakdown of Chicago's voting-age population on July 1
was about 46.8 percent white, 38.3 percent black and 14.9 percent
Hispanic, said Marie Bousfield, Chicago's city demographer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ChicagoElection Adv26-1stAdd   02-13 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Chicago Election, Adv 26-1st Add,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: city demographer.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In 1983, black voters turned out in force to support Washington
in the primary, giving him 36 percent of the vote and a stunning
victory over then-Mayor Jane yrne and Daley, who divided the white
vote. Washington went on to a narrow victory in a racially charged
general-election fight against little-known Republican Bernard Epton.
   Kleppner said he believes the racism that marked the 1983 mayoral
contest remains, but ``it's under the rug.''
   Racism was tempered when the city actually had a black mayor, he
said, and many white voters feel Daley is a shoo-in.
   Daley's status as front-runner has not been hurt by virtually
citywide recognition of the family name.
   ``Bring back the Daley dynasty!'' supporters cheer at some
campaign stops.
   Sawyer and Evans _ and Washington _ came up through the ranks of
the ``machine,'' the patronage-rich political organization Daley's
father built.
   Daley says little about his father, whose last years in office
were marred by the riots at the 1968 Democratic National Convention
and other controversies.
   He cites his own record as county prosecutor and a state senator.
   ``The politics and name-calling are tearing Chicago apart when we
need to work together,'' Daley told a civic club meeting.
   ``I'm not interested in being `the white candidate,' or in
serving as mayor for half the people.''
   Kleppner says Daley will win the primary if he avoids the kind of
slip that could provide a focal point for black opposition. He adds
that such a slip is unlikely since Daley ``has been very well
scripted.''
   Daley kept to that script in a television debate earlier this
month with Sawyer and Bloom. Repeatedly baited by Bloom _ who at one
point said his supporters thought Daley was the ``great white hope''
_ Daley refused to spar.
   City jobs and minority hiring are hot topics and Sawyer, boasting
that a quarter of city contracts are going to minorities, contends
Daley's election would mean moving backward.
   Aides say Daley has a good affirmative action record in his
office, more than doubling the number of black lawyers there in
eight years.
   Activist Lu Palmer said he's not convinced.
   ``No white mayor has ever been sensitive to the needs of our
people,'' he said.
   Daley may benefit from black-Jewish tension lingering after the
furor last spring over tape-recorded lectures by Sawyer aide Steve
Cokely that contained anti-Semitic remarks. Sawyer waited five days
to fire Cokely. A few hours before the announcement, Evans denounced
Cokely's remarks as ``inappropriate.''
   There are many Jews among the white ``lakefront liberals'' who
helped elect Washington.
   ``I don't think that either black mayoral candidate played an
exemplary role in the Cokely affair,'' said Barry Morrison of the
local Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
   There have been other tussles.
   Days after becoming mayor, Sawyer faced the disclosure that as an
alderman years before, he accepted what he called a finder's fee of
$30,000 for helping a lawyer obtain a bank loan. In another case, he
admitted filing income tax returns late, though no money was owed
the government.
   Daley, meanwhile, was questioned about a report that petitions
circulated for a failed 1986 referendum to make the mayor's race
non-partisan may have included fraudulent signatures linked to
workers in his office. He cooled the issue by calling for
appointment of a special prosecutor.
   Sawyer says the winner of the Democratic primary is sure to be
mayor, but Evans demonstrated considerable strength when he
submitted more than 100,000 signatures in filing for his third-party
bid _ four times the required number.
   Kleppner suggests it doesn't much matter who wins.
   With the 1991 regularly scheduled mayoral race coming up soon
after this spring's special election, the winner will begin
campaigning immediately, he said.
   ``What this city needs it's not going to get from any of the
candidates,'' Kleppner said, ``and that's long-range planning.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
