<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   02-13 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Stars We Are'' (Capitol) _ Marc Almond
   
   When was the last time you heard lyrics like these?
   ``I'll be a dragonfly, a butterfly, A secret or a little lie to
test you, A song a verse a lullaby, A symphony...''
   ``In my hands the grains of sand, A thousand million moments of
emotion _ Oh these my dreams are yours.''
   ``I'm a teardrop in a storm, A storm at the end of the world.''
   Set words like these to a rock beat and add strings, trumpets and
other lush instrumentation, backing vocals with plenty of
atmospheric reverb, and an occasional spoken-word passage. What do
you have? Donovan? The Moody Blues? King Crimson?
   No, this is not a lost 1967 recording of early Art Rock. But Marc
Almond and his group, La Magia, exhibit a youthful romanticism that
has been missing from rock since the Flower Power days.
   That's refreshing as a break from the current formulas, a
revitalization of an almost extinct style. And it's reassuring to
know that even in the late '80s a songwriter can refer to himself as
someone ``who is afraid of getting jaded.''
   But youthful romanticism and idealism can lead to youthful
excess, and this record is often both trite and overwrought in its
efforts to achieve poetry. In a song called ``The Very Last Pearl,''
Almond aptly sings, ``Call me romantic, Call me deluded.'' He
concludes another song by drawing out the phrase, ``And I ... a fool
... for love!'' Really, now.
   Amid such excess, however, there are some good songs on this
album. ``Only the Moment'' and ``Tears Run Rings'' in particular
stand out as well-realized pop songs that manage to escape being
overdone. All it takes is a little restraint.
   _ By Dan Murphy, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Wall of Pride'' (Columbia) _ Omar and the Howlers
   
   Omar and the Howlers play the kind of loud, rowdy rock 'n' roll
that sounds best late at night in a noisy, crowded bar.
   That doesn't mean you have to invite a bunch of strangers over to
your apartment and throw beer bottles against the wall to enjoy
``Wall of Pride,'' the Texas band's second album. But make no
mistake, it's party music all the way.
   Transferring such bar-band energy to a record is no easy task but
producer Terry Manning, who has worked with blues-rockers Z.Z. Top
and George Thorogood, has a way with this sort of thing.
   The focus is not on the songs, which are good if not overly
distinctive, as much as the sound itself, especially the sandpaper
growl of lead singer Omar, who also plays a raw, scraping guitar.
   He's helped by a strong rhythm section and keyboard player Eric
Scortia, who apparently isn't afraid to occasionally use his elbows
instead of his fingers to pound the piano.
   The album's two cover songs are interesting: a remake of the
Animals' ``We Gotta Get Out of This Place,'' which abandons any
pretense to the subtlety of the original; and a version of Jimmy
Reed's ``Down in Mississippi,'' recorded in an odd, muffled sound
that recalls the great bluesman's loping style.
   The originals, most of which are written or co-written by an
otherwise unidentified K. Dykes, range from the all-out boogie of
``Rattlesnake Shake'' to the rhythm and blues-flavored ``King's
Ransom.''
   That's not a very far range, but these guys don't claim to be
Renaissance men. They're Howlers.
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
