<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--TheUniversity Adv24-26   02-13 1138</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--The University, Adv 24-26,1169</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Feb 24-26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Two Titans Consider ``The University''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Oakeshott is 87 years old, lives in a
stone cottage in Dorset, England, and is, in the minds of many, one
of the century's great philosophers.
   A. Bartlett Giamatti, a teacher of Italian, English and
comparative literature, was president of Yale University and is
about to become the commissioner of baseball in April.
   The two men, seemingly so distant in place and circumstance, are
actually close intellectual neighbors. By happy coincidence, each
has just published collections of essays describing their views on
education and the idea of the university.
   Both have fashioned elegantly written defenses of liberal
education and the ideal of the university as a place of civil
conversation; a place where, as Oakeshott puts it, a student may
``come to seek his intellectual fortune'' undistracted by the press
of time or outside worries.
   ``The Voice of Liberal Learning: Michael Oakeshott on Education''
(Yale University Press, $20) was edited by Timothy Fuller, head of
the political science department at Colorado College and a friend
and unabashed admirer of the British philosopher who is professor
emeritus at the London School of Economics.
   Giamatti's ``A Free and Ordered Space: The Real World of the
University'' (W.W. Norton, $19.95) consists of 23 essays, many of
them originally delivered as speeches at commencements or
convocations.
   The Oakeshott collection, in particular, represents a welcome
rescue operation, an opportunity for Americans to discover a major
British philosopher and teacher of enormous wit, charm and modesty.
His essays add a civilizing voice to the current school reform
debate.
   For universities and their supporters, the two collections
couldn't be more timely. Taken together, they represent a forceful
rebuttal to ``The Closing of the American Mind,'' the curmudgeonly
best seller by University of Chicago political scientist Allan Bloom
which charged American higher education with selling out its
intellectual responsibilities to 1960s hooliganism.
   The introductions in both collections leave no doubt that
Oakeshott and Giamatti are aiming straight at such
Bloom-and-doomsayers. Giamatti, for one, blames his academic
colleagues for their silence under siege, and urges them to make
their mission better understood to an increasingly impatient public.
   ``A parent who hungers to know, for instance, why a child's
college experience costs so much or, worse, has seemed so
unsatisfactory or lacking in connectedness with anything in the past
will have heard very little from higher education about its issues
or its problems,'' Giamatti writes.
   ``Small wonder that Allan Bloom's book is a best seller.''
   Oakeshott's essays are more difficult, both intellectually and
for their use of British idiom. The collection includes some of
Oakeshott's least-known works, some of which appeared as much as 40
years ago only in out-of-print journals.
   Over the years, Oakeshott has acquired a small but devoted army
of academtic adherents. He is perhaps best known for his definitive
introduction to Thomas Hobbes' ``Leviathan.'' But his other works,
notably ``Experience and Its Modes,'' and ``Rationalism in
Politics,'' have become bibles for those who have watched with
horror the rise of social science and technocracy on U.S. campuses
at the expense of history and the humanities.
   Oakeshott describes the university as an idea, more than a place
_ a community where scholars, teachers and pupils engage each other
in ceaseless skepticism. Universities are, and must remain,
blessedly ``useless'' beyond the enjoyment of learning they offer
participants.
   His essays, including several in the present collection, also
constitute a powerful defense of political conservatism and have
thus been quoted regularly by columnists such as William F. Buckley.
   Yet Oakeshott himself has always been far more good-natured in
his views than those who have most often invoked his name. Still,
practical-minded Americans often find a number of his beliefs
difficult to swallow.
   For example, he describes the undergraduate as ``not a child, not
a beginner. He has already had his schooling elsewhere, and has
learned enough, morally and intellectually, to take a chance with
himself upon the open sea...'' That description might seem a bit
elitist to some, leaving little room in the modern university for
remediation.
   Further, Oakeshott completely and defiantly rejects utilitarian
justifications for higher education:
   ``The current talk about the `mission' and the `function' of a
university goes rather over my head,'' he writes. ``It assumes that
there is something called `a university,' a contrivance of some
sort, something you could make another of tomorrow if you had enough
money, of which it is sensible to ask, `What is it for?'''
   Or again: ``A university ... has a place in the society to which
it belongs, but that place is not the function of contributing to
some other kind of activity in the society but of being itself and
not another thing.''
   The historian of Oakeshottian bent, for example, practices
history for its own sake, not for its supposed ``lessons'' or other
real or imagined uses. Viewed in purely practical terms, Oakeshott's
scholar doesn't give a hoot about whether his activity is of use,
except insofar as it is interesting to him. He wants to understand
for understanding's sake.
   Giamatti, as a former university president, is far more willing
to explore scholarship's connections with other segments of society.
But his central view of the university as a ``free and open space''
is remarkably compatible with the Oakeshott ideal.
   ``Its essence,'' Giamatti writes, ``is that give-and-take, that
civil conversation in its innumerable forms. When that conversation,
the to-and-fro of ideas, is stymied or foreclosed or frozen, when
the questing for truth is told that it must cease because there is
only one Truth and it is Complete, then the institution in its
essence is chilled and its life threatened.''
   In an essay titled ``The Earthly Use of a Liberal Education,''
Giamatti confronts an all-too-American challenge to higher learning:
   Liberal education ``is all very well, but how does someone make a
living with this joy of learning and pleasure in the pursuit of
learning? What is the earthly use of all this kind of education
later on, in the practical, real world?
   ``These are not trivial questions, though the presuppositions
behind them puzzle me somewhat. I am puzzled, for instance, by the
unexamined assumption that the `real world' is always thought to lie
outside or beyond the realm of education. I am puzzled by those who
think that ideas do not have reality or that knowledge is irrelevant
to the workings of daily life.''
   It's comforting to know that such thoughts still occupy the man
who might adjudicate baseball's balk rule come next Spring.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE _ Lee Mitgang has covered education for the AP</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   since 1981.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Feb. 24-26</NOTE>
