<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Denims     02-13 0080</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Denims,0082</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Denims</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY708</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   It's no longer enough that jeans just fit _ and last.
   Manufacturers now promote jeans that have been acid-washed,
white-washed, stone-washed, rinsed, bleached, or over-dyed.
   Last spring's favored look was acid-washed. This spring, says Roy
Schiefner, manager of product development for jeans manufacturer
Levi Strauss, ``light-colored, lived-in denim'' will be popular.
   He says the style may also turn to narrower, slimmed-down styles,
which translates as tighter-fitting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
