<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Bodywear     02-13 0116</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Bodywear,0117</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Bodywear</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY709</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Like other active-sports gear, the body-hugging costumes worn by
dancers, swimmers and bikers have been appropriated as fashionable
streetwear for teens and near-teens.
   The old reasons for skintight outfits in sports and dance are
free movement and to cut down wind or water resistance. A new reason
might be that, coupled with brilliant colors, the new clothes flaunt
a trim figure.
   Designer Bonnie August couples a short, loose graffiti T-shirt
with second-skin bike pants, both done up with flashy neon colors.
She also uses leotards, tank suits, crop tops, and stirrup tights in
combinations of cotton blends, spandex, and shiny ribbed synthetics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
