<DOCNO> AP890213-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Rock     02-13 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Rock,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Rock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock stars and fans need their designer lines just like any other
upwardly mobile strivers.
   Somewhat ambiguously billed as ``designers of rock 'n' roll
street fashion,'' a firm called Lip Service now brings rock star
fashion to off-the-rack customers.
   A favorite motif of designer-founder Drew Bernstein is the skull
and dagger, which is featured on Lip Service T-shirts, jackets,
leggings, and, yes, panties _ the kind worn on the outside for
decoration.
   A bold ``War?'' poster-type print also shows up on jackets, and
the collection also goes heavy on leather-look vinyls, lace-ups and
zippers in odd locations on chaps, hot pants, bustiers, pegged jeans
and any other items the rocker feels naked without. These are topped
off with bangles, studs, insignias and other jewelry that might more
accurately be described as hardware.
   Bernstein, 25, is a former musician who says his clothes appeal
to rock band players and their fans. Sales in 1988 were around $1
million and marketed in Germany, Canada, Japan and the United
States. Outlets are boutiques, and prices range from $20 for a crop
top to about $100 for a vinyl jacket.
   Bernstein says he started his company in 1985 in his parents'
garage in Hollywood, having put his career as a rock musician behind
him at the age of 22. He now employs 30 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
