<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Maternity     02-13 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Maternity,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Maternity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In the past, pregnant women spent much of their time at home and
maternity fashions carried little significance.
   Today, with more and more women in the workplace, designers go
out of their way to produce chic and contemporary maternity clothes,
says Judy Loeb, director of design for Trio, manufacturers of
maternity clothing.
   She offers this advice for mothers-to-be:
   _ Buy your regular size; maternity clothes are made to
accommodate your changing body. Oversized regular clothing will hike
up in front. But pants occasionally should be one or two sizes
larger, to accommodate larger hips and thighs.
   _ Balance your wardrobe between career clothes and weekend wear.
   _ Reduce leg discomfort with support pantyhose.
   _ Wear a full or half slip to make clothes fall better and
provide a smoother silhouette.
   _ Wear natural fibers, like cotton, wool and some rayons.
   _ Space your purchases; leave some of your budget for impulse
buying, changing seasons and special events.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
