<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-13 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0786</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest banks raised their prime
lending rates to 11 percent from 10.5 percent, the highest level
since 1984, and economists predicted more increases will follow.
   Friday's rise was the first in 1989 for the rate, which banks use
as a benchmark for setting interest on consumer and corporate loans,
such as adjustable-rate mortgages.
   The last increase, from 10 percent to 10.5 percent, occurred Nov.
28. In 1984, the prime rate reached 10.75 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices, as measured by the Producer
Price Index, rose 1 percent in January, their fastest pace in nearly
three years, led by rising food and energy prices.
   It was the biggest monthly increase since an identical surge in
October 1985 and was equivalent to a 12.7 percent annual rate of
inflation, the Labor Department said Friday.
   Analysts warned the new figures could signal spiraling inflation
in 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats won't begin
negotiations with President Bush over his $1.16 trillion budget
until the administration specifies the programs it would cut to
reduce the deficit.
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., and his
House counterpart, Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said Friday they
would meet with administration budget director Richard Darman on
Monday to try to learn more details about the fiscal 1990 spending
plan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savers withdrew a record $8.1 billion from the
nation's thrift institutions in December, but $3.4 billion of the
total was accounted for by one healthy institution reducing deposits
as part of a deliberate strategy.
   Separately, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said Friday it
had taken control of six more savings institutions, bringing to 10
the number of S&amp;Ls brought under the agency's control since
President Bush on Monday gave it that responsibility under his plan
for the S&amp;L crisis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Administration ethics attorneys are
scrutinizing investments held by Secretary of State James A. Baker
III to determine whether any should be sold to avoid a possible
conflict of interest.
   Baker, who was White House chief of staff and then treasury
secretary in the Reagan administration, has substantial interests in
real estate, oil and bank stocks, his latest disclosure form shows.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ivan Boesky, the imprisoned speculator at the
center of Wall Street's insider trading scandal, will not apply for
parole from his three-year term at a California prison when he
becomes eligible next month.
   Sources said Friday that Boesky's lawyers are waiting to see
whether information provided to the government by Boesky results in
the indictment of high-yield bond financier Michael Milken before
seeking early release.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s
high-yield bond trader Michael R. Milken has asked a federal judge
to reject the firm's mammoth settlement for securities fraud because
it violates his rights.
   Drexel recently plea bargained with the U.S. attorney, agreeing
to pay $300 million in fines and civil penalties for securities law
abuses. Part of Drexel's deal also involved firing Milken and
withholding his multimillion dollar pay.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unilever Group, the European conglomerate, has
agreed to buy the Faberge and Elizabeth Arden lines of toiletries,
cosmetics and fragrances for $1.55 billion in cash from New York
investor Meshulam Riklis.
   The deal, announced Friday, marks the latest major European
acquisition of a U.S. company and continues the worldwide
consolidation in the cosmetics business.
   Unilever bought Chesebrough-Pond's Inc. for $3.1 billion two
years ago and owns such brand names as Vaseline, Pond's and
Elizabeth Taylor's Passion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil industry is cheering President Bush's
proposed tax incentives for energy producers, but officials and
analysts were split on whether the measures would help curb the
nation's growing dependence on foreign oil.
   The American Petroleum Institute, representing the nation's major
oil companies, Friday welcomed the Bush tax incentives but said more
steps would be needed, including opening up more federal lands and
offshore areas to oil exploration.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar soared and the stock market dropped in a sell-off
prompted by new inflation worries and rising interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 36.97 to 2,286.07,
extending its loss for the week to 45.18 points.
   Bond prices also plummeted but recovered from the day's lows.
Gold and silver also took a dive.
   On other markets, coffee, energy and soybean futures prices fell
sharply; grain futures were higher and livestock and meat futures
were mixed.
</TEXT>
