<FIRST>r f PM-Obit-Sanborn     02-13 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Sanborn,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conrail Chairman Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard D. Sanborn, chairman, president and
chief executive officer of Consolidated Rail Corp., has died at the
age of 52.
   Sanborn died Sunday afternoon of an apparent heart attack, said
Sol Renick, a spokesman for the Philadelphia-based rail company.
   The board of directors will meet Wednesday to discuss a
successor, the company said.
   Sanborn, who had 27 years of experience in the railroad business,
took over as chairman on Jan. 1 with the retirement of L. Stanley
Crane, who in eight years guided the company from massive losses to
profitability.
   Conrail was formed by Congress in 1976 to reorganize six bankrupt
Northeast railroads, including the Penn Central. After 11 years of
government ownership, Conrail was sold March 26, 1987, for $1.6
billion in the largest public stock offering in U.S. history.
   Conrail's board elected Sanborn president and chief operating
officer when Crane announced his retirement a year ago.
   Before joining Conrail, Sanborn was president and CEO for CSX
Distribution Services Inc., a unit of the railroad holding company
CSX Corp.
   After graduating from Harvard Law School in 1960, Sanborn began
his railroad career with the Atlantic Coast Line Railroad in 1961 as
an attorney. He joined Seaboard Coast Line Railroad in 1972 and
worked his way to president and chief executive officer of Seaboard
System Inc. in 1982.
   He joined CSX as president and chief executive in 1986.
   Sanborn, a native of Sanbornville, N.H., graduated from the
University of New Hampshire in 1957.
   He is survived by his wife, Hilda Joan, two children and his
father.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
