<DOCNO> AP890213-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Japan-Trade     02-13 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Widens In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus rose in January over a year
ago as low oil prices continued to keep down import costs, the
Finance Ministry reported Monday.
   The surplus grew to $3.25 billion last month from $3.07 billion
in January 1988, but was well below the monthly record of $9.65
billion set in December.
   January exports rose 11.5 percent from a year earlier to $19.32
billion and imports climbed 12.7 percent to $16.07 billion. The
figures are compiled as the goods pass through customs.
   Japan's surplus with the United States, however, fell slightly
over a year ago, to $2.974 billion from $2.976 billion. Exports to
the U.S. market increased 11.1 percent to $6.50 billion, while
imports from the United States surged 22.4 percent to $3.52 billion.
   Finance Ministry officials said Japan's overall surplus rose
because of steady demand for Japanese goods in other countries
enjoying continued economic expansion and because of lower prices
for the crude oil Japan imports.
   They said imports of manufactured goods remain strong, a trend
they expect to continue for some time.
   In trade with the United States, Japan boosted car exports by 9.7
percent to $1.50 billion in January. U.S. steel sales in Japan
soared six-fold to $41.19 million and car sales nearly doubled to
$41.62 million.
   Japan's exports to the European Economic Community rose 6.4
percent to $3.66 billion in January, while imports from the EEC
leaped 24.4 percent to $2.02 billion. That left Japan with a surplus
of $1.64 billion, down from $1.82 billion in January 1988.
   Because of large oil imports, Japan ran a $1.04 billion deficit
in trade with the Middle East, down from $1.30 billion in January
1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
