<FIRST>r f BC-MiddleEast-Economy     02-13 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Middle East-Economy,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Arab Countries Reach Accord on Economic Grouping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt, Jordan, North Yemen and Iraq have
agreed to form an economic alliance patterned after the European
Economic Community, diplomats said Monday.
   They said representatives of those countries will meet in Jordan
on Tuesday to put the final touches on the agreement, and the heads
of state are expected to sign the accord Thursday.
   Officials in the four countries have said the Arab Economic
Cooperation Council would enhance economic ties and lead to more
cooperation in number of fields, including industry, transportation,
agriculture, electricity and scientific research.
   ``With a population of 80 million and vital strategic and
political influence, the new group will be a major block which all
other Arab countries ... should reckon with,'' said one Asian
diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
