<FIRST>u f BC-Consolidated-Emery 1stLd-Writethru   02-13 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Consolidated-Emery, 1st Ld-Writethru,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consolidated To Acquire Emery</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES throughout with new information; Lary, one r, in 4th
graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Freightways, Inc., said
Monday it will acquire Emery Air Freight Corp. in a cash deal valued
at $230 million.
   Emery, one of the nation's largest air freight carriers, has
accepted Consolidated's offer of $7.75 a share in cash for all
outstanding common stock and $21.10 per share in cash for all
outstanding preferred stock, the companies said.
   The agreement has been approved by the boards of directors of
both companies, according to the announcement.
   Lary Scott, president of Consolidated Freightways, said the
combined company will operate under the name ``Emery Worldwide, a CF
Company.''
   Emery has undergone a restructuring in recent years as
competition from other overnight delivery services stiffened. The
competitive climate is likely to heat up even more if the pending
buyout of Tiger International by Federal Express Corp. is completed.
   In the third quarter ended Sept. 30, the latest period for which
the company has reported earnings, Emery lost $9.95 million, or 41
cents a share, on revenue of $313.8 million.
   In 1987, Emery bought Purolator Courier Corp. but its service
levels remained disappointing as it integrated Purolator's field
operations into its own.
   Last year, Tennessee businessman and former Federal Express
executive Arthur Bass said that he was considering taking over the
company, but no deal ever emerged.
   Emery Chairman William F. Souders told the annual meeting in May
that the company was ``positioning (itself) for the long haul.'' He
said then that Emery's goal was to become a ``strong, profitable,
customer-driven company.''
   Souders said the merger with Consolidated would ``offer customers
the best service available.''
   Consolidated Freightways does business in trucking and air
freight delivery. Its 1988 revenue totaled $2.7 billion.
   The Wilton, Conn.-based Emery, which employs about 17,000 people,
provides worldwide air courier and cargo service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
