<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-13 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain and Soybeans Open Mostly Lower on Follow-Through Selling from
Last Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened lower this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders said most of the pressure at the bell was the result of
follow-through selling after Friday's sharply lower close in the
bean pits, as well as showers over the weekend in the key South
American growing regions of Argentina and Brazil.
   New-crop beans, however, managed to avoid most of the downturn,
in part because the government said late last week it would limit
how much soybean planting will be allowed on set-aside land.
   On the opening, wheat was 2 cents to 3 cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.26 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2 cents lower, with March at $2.64{ a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to
2\ cents lower, with March at $2.04{ a bushel; and soybeans were \
cent to 5{ cents lower, with March at $7.29{.
   Livestock futures were mostly higher, but pork futures mostly
lower on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .45 higher, with February at
74.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent to .55 cent higher,
with March at 82.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to
.17 cent higher, with February at 41.77 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .27 cent to .60 cent lower, with February at 37.40
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
