<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls-MidwestFederal     02-13 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Midwest Federal,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Takes Over Troubled Thrift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators today took over the
operations of Midwest Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association and
announced the resignation of the thrift's chairman, who is among the
targets of an FBI fraud probe.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank of Des Moines said it had declared
Midwest Federal insolvent and appointed the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. conservator under a program announced by President
Bush last week.
   In the same statement, the home loan bank said Midwest Federal
Chairman Harold Greenwood Jr. and the thrift's managing officer,
Charlotte Massica, resigned.
   U.S. Attorney Jerome Arnold of Minneapolis last week said
Greenwood and Massica were among the targets of an FBI investigation
into possible fraud at Midwest Federal.
   Thurman C. Connell, president of the Des Moines bank, said in a
statement that Greenwood resigned because ``he needed to focus on
personal issues.''
   ``Greenwood, in cooperation with federal regulators, determined
his resignation was in the best interests of Midwest Federal,'' the
statement said.
</TEXT>
