<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   02-13 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower As Interest Rate Fears Resurface</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to update with closing prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed sharply lower but above their
worst levels Monday amid renewed concern that British interest rates
could remain high for an extended period.
   Dealers said trading was cautious following comments by
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson over the weekend that
Britain's January inflation rate would show a ``particularly marked
rise.''
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 23.4
points, or 1.1 percent, at 2,032.7. The index was down a minimum
18.8 points in early business, but then moved as much as 35.2 points
lower in early afternoon.
   Volume was light, as 474.5 million shares changed hands, down
substantially from Friday's 671.4 million shares and sharply lower
than the brisk pace of dealing seen in recent weeks.
   Britain's inflation figures are due on Friday.
   Lawson seemed to be preparing markets for bad news with a warning
that the annual inflation rate would top 7 percent in January. That
would compare with an annual rise in December of 6.8 percent.
</TEXT>
