<HEAD>Soybeans Off Sharply, Grains Lower on Weather, Follow-Through Selling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices slipped lower
across the board Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders said the beans came under pressure at the opening bell
because of follow-through selling after Friday's sharply lower close
and considerable rain over the weekend in the key South American
growing regions of Argentina and Brazil.
   New-crop beans, however, slipped only half as much, in part
because the government said late last week it would limit how much
soybean planting will be allowed on set-aside land.
   Without any significant export business announcements, prices in
the wheat and corn pits slid lower in sympathy.
   On the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3\ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.26 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2\ cents lower, with March at $2.64\ a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to
3 cents lower, with March at $2.03} a bushel; and soybeans were 4
cent to 10} cents lower, with March at $7.25.
