<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PaloVerde-Record     02-13 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Palo Verde-Record,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unit 3 World's Top Nuclear Power Plant Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTERSBURG, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palo Verde Unit 3 generated more
electricty last year than any nuclear plant in the world, operators
said Monday.
   The Arizona Nuclear Power Project said statistics from Nucleonics
Week, a publication of the nuclear industry, show that the newest of
three units at the generating station 50 miles west of Phoenix
produced 10.87 million megawatt hours last year _ enough for two
cities the size of Tucson.
   The output of the plant's other two reactors lagged, however.
According to Nuclear Regulatory Commission figures, Unit 1 has
operated at 51 percent of capacity since its startup in late 1985,
and Unit 2 has run at 67.3 percent.
   Unit 3, which was started in late 1987 and entered commercial
operation early in 1988, has operated at nearly 90 percent of
capacity and last summer set a U.S. record of 214 days of continuous
operation after startup.
   It also set a U.S. record for a month, with 955,400 megawatts in
March.
   Each of the triplet reactors is rated at 1,270 megawatts. ANPP
officials said they serve 4 million customers of the seven utilities
in Arizona, California, Texas and New Mexico which united to build
the $9.3 billion complex.
   The publication listed the Grohnde and Philippsburg-2 nuclear
plants in West Germany as Nos. 2 and 3 in the world, with 1988
production of 10.79 million and 10.21 million megawatts,
respectively.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
