<SECOND>BC-Hotel Sale ,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Property Firm Selling Luxury Los Angeles Hotel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hotel Bel-Air, a 92-room luxury hotel popular
for years with movie stars and other celebrities, is up for sale.
   The hotel, one mile west of Beverly Hills' famous Rodeo Drive,
has drawn considerable investor interest, said officials of
Dallas-based Rosewood Property Co.
   ``Because of its world-class reputation, we have for some time
had incredible investor interest in the property at world record
prices,'' said Denny Alberts, Rosewood Property chairman and chief
executive officer, in a statement.
   ``We believe that it is an appropriate business decision for us
to realize an outstanding profit at this time by selling the Hotel
Bel-Air while maintaining a management contract.''
   The hotel's rooms, including 33 suites, are arranged in one- and
two-story, mission-style buildings and bungalows on an 11.5-acre,
lushly landscaped estate. Laurie Farmer, Rosewood Hotel Group
advertising and marketing manager, said estimates are the hotel is
worth $1 million per room.
   Hotel spokeswoman Donna Smith in Newport, Calif. said no names of
interested buyers had yet surfaced because the sale was a
``closed-bid process.''
   Guests at the hotel have included Marilyn Monroe, Sophia Loren,
Audrey Hepburn and Gregory Peck, said Ms. Smith.
   On Jan. 29, ``Miami Vice'' star Don Johnson nabbed an intruder in
his room at the Bel-Air as the man rifled through the purse of
Johnson's fiancee, actress Melanie Griffith. Johnson stopped the man
from taking expensive jewelry and held the intruder for police.
