<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-UniversityEndowments     02-13 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-University Endowments,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Endowment Performance Hurt by Stock Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College and university endowments earned some
money on their investments for fiscal 1988 but the performance was
hurt by the stock market crash, a study reported Monday.
   The National Association of College and University Business
Officers said that the average rate of return for the period July 1,
1987 to June 30, 1988 was 1.3 percent. That was down from 13.9
percent in fiscal 1987.
   ``Considering the year on the stock market, we were pleased that
they had a positive rate of return,'' said association spokeswoman
Lucy Howton. She said the endowments held their own for a number of
reasons.
   ``The best stocks did rebound after the crash,'' she said. ``And
not all institutions are totally invested into stocks. Bonds and CDs
did well.''
   The endowment study of 315 schools, conducted annually since
1974, showed total market value for participating funds at $49.5
billion in fiscal 1988, up from $47.9 billion the previous year.
   The 10 participating institutions with the highest endowment fund
assets were the same 10 as the year before, in the same order.
Harvard topped the list with an endowment of nearly $4.2 billion, as
of mid-1988. The University of Texas system was second with $2.8
billion, followed by Princeton at $2.3 billion and Yale at $2.1
billion.
   The other top 10 institutions were Stanford, $1.6 billion;
Columbia, $1.4 billion; Texas A&amp;M, $1.2 billion; Washington
University, $1.1 billion; MIT, $1.1 billion; and the University of
California, $1.1 billion.
</TEXT>
