<DOCNO> AP890213-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-JapaneseCondoms     02-13 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japanese Condoms,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Japanese Condom Maker Eyes U.S. Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Contents may offend some readers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRATFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American consumers accustomed to finding
``Made in Japan'' stamped on cameras and radios increasingly can
find those words on packages of a more intimate product: condoms.
   Okamoto Industries Inc., Japan's leading condom maker with a 63
percent market share, last year launched a U.S. subsidiary and plans
to have its product on store shelves in the Northeast in a couple of
months.
   Other Japanese companies also have entered the U.S. market in
recent years.
   While some industry analysts say high consumer brand loyalty
makes it difficult for the Japanese to grab market share, Hisayuki
Naito, general manager of Okamoto U.S.A. Inc., predicts Okamoto will
capture 10 percent of the American condom market in two years and up
to 25 percent within seven.
   ``The Japanese philosphy is that once we have committed
ourselves, we will do it,'' said Naito, who sees a vast untapped
market in America because of health concerns about AIDS and the
birth control pill.
   U.S. retail condom sales increased 62 percent to $292 million
between 1985 and 1987, according to Salomon Brothers Inc.
   But only 16 percent of Americans use condoms as the primary form
of birth control compared with 76 percent in Japan, where the birth
control pill is illegal, analysts say.
   ``In this country, the condom is a very hidden product,'' Naito
said during a recent interview. A display rack with packages of
Okamoto's American competitors decorates one wall of a conference
room at the company headquarters.
   ``This is more healthy, no question about it,'' Naiko said,
unfurling a pink Crown condom, one of four Okamoto brands to be
marketed in the United States.
   The company plans a $2 million ad campaign stressing the quality
of its condoms, including print ads in Vogue, Playboy and The
Advocate, a magazine aimed at gays.
   One ad features a photo of a condom stretched by two fingers _ a
frankness that Okamoto hopes will help Americans overcome their
shyness about the product, Naito said.
   The other Okamoto lines are Harmony, Regal and Beyond, which is
packaged in a plastic compact case and is aimed at women, who
account for 25 to 40 percent of all U.S. condom purchasers.
   Okamoto is an $800 million-a-year company that also sells tires,
distributes Reebok, Keds and Rockport shoes in Japan and makes the
plastic interiors for Honda, General Motors and Ford cars.
   Condoms, which Okamoto also sells in Europe and Canada, account
for about 10 percent of the company's business.
   Okamoto has six employees in Stratford and marketing deals with
eight independent wholesalers. It will continue shipping condoms
from Japan but may eventually build a U.S. plant, Naito said.
   Other Japanese companies long have been trying to crack the U.S.
market.
   Fugi Latex Co., the No. 2 Japanese condom maker, and Nisshoiwa
Corp. of America, a Japanese trading company, own 60 percent of
Safetex Corp. of Lyndhurst, N.J. under a joint venture begun in
1987. Fuji has made condoms in the United States since buying the
Newark plant of Circle Rubber Co. about 15 years ago, which it since
has closed.
   Sagami Rubber Industries Inc.'s Kimono condom has been imported
by Mayer Laboratories Inc., of Oakland, Calif., since April 1987.
   Industry analysts warn that the Japanese may have difficulty in
the U.S. condom market because Americans remain somewhat embarrassed
by the subject. They therefore are likely to stay with brands they
recognize and can grab quickly from store shelves.
   New York-based Carter-Wallace Inc., maker of the Trojans brand of
condoms, now controls about 53 percent of the market. Schmid
Laboratories Inc., based in Little Falls, N.J., controls about 27
percent of the market with such brands as Ramses, Sheik and Excita.
   Salomon Brothers predicts condom sales will continue growing at
15 percent annually in the foreseeable future. But some observers
predict growth will slow with the calming of fears about
heterosexual transmission of AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
