<SECOND>AM-Trader Vic,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Ponders Fate of Polynesian Potion Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One month after declaring Trader Vic's tacky
beyond toleration, Donald Trump says the pseudo-Polynesian saloon in
his lordly Plaza Hotel can stay open a little longer because of
booming business.
   Trump told the New York Post that business at Trader Vic's has
doubled with old customers trooping in for a farewell drink.
   ``I'm in no hurry to close it. It's a very successful operation
now,'' Trump said.
   Then, having given with one hand, the billionaire developer took
away with the other by adding: ``But since it's the greatest
location in the world, anything would be successful there.''
   Stories in newspapers ranging from the Wall Street Journal to the
Village Voice helped. So did a New York Times editorial pining the
passing of such Trader Vic palate pleasers as the Mai Tai or the
Scorpion with gardenia afloat, the Samoan Fog Cutter or the Dr. Funk
of Tahiti.
   The restaurant part of Trader Vic's, which operated from the
Plaza basement for 25 years, closed a year ago, but the bar stayed
open.
   Trump bought the Plaza last year for $390 million. He said in
January that a classy Oriental restaurant and a health club would
begin materializing in April or May in the space from which he was
bouncing Trader Vic's.
   ``I now have no set timetable on this,'' he says now. ``I haven't
decided what to do with the space yet.''
   The Trader Vic's chain operates more than 20 restaurants in the
United States, Canada, West Germany and Japan.
