<DOCNO> AP890213-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Tax     02-13 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Tax,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Members Disagree On Uniform Tax On Interest Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European Community countries disagreed
Monday on a proposed witholding tax of 15 percent on interest income
from bonds and bank savings and sent the plan to a high-level study
group.
   At a meeting of the EEC economics and finance ministers, Britain
and Luxembourg completely opposed the Commission's proposal while
West Germany sought a reduction in toward the level of its own tax
of 10 percent.
   Of the other member states, France, Italy, Spain, Denmark,
Portugal, Ireland and Belgium broadly supported the proposal.
   The proposal was made last week by the European Commission in an
effort to harmonize the widely different taxes on interest income in
the 12 member States _ from zero in Luxembourg to 35 percent in
Ireland.
   Because EEC laws on taxation need to be approved unanimously,
diplomats said that it was difficult to see how the proposals could
be adopted unless radical changes were made.
   Luxembourg's Finance Minister Jacques Poos said Luxembourg would
block the commission's plan. Luxembourg, which has banking secrecy
laws and is considered the EEC's tax haven, fears its economy will
suffer if a tax is imposed.
   The high-level study group is expected to complete its report in
four to six weeks. The ministers will discuss its conclusions at
their regular monthly meeting in April. The group is composed of the
chief tax authorities of the twelve EEC member states.
</TEXT>
