<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-GMSubsidiaries Bjt   02-13 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-GM Subsidiaries, Bjt,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>GMAC 4th Qtr. Earnings Up 9.5 Percent, GM Hughes Up 16.5 Percent,
EDS Down 0.8 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Acceptance Corp. on Monday
announced a 9.5 percent increase in its fourth-quarter profits,
while GM Hughes Electronics reported a 16.5 percent profit rise and
Electronic Data Systems Corp. had a 0.8 percent earnings drop during
the period.
   The three subsidiaries of the nation's biggest carmaker reported
their earnings in advance of the parent company, which was expected
to announce overall results Tuesday.
   GMAC, the company's financing and mortgage operation, posted a
profit of $257.4 million in the final three months of 1988. That
compared with net income of $235 million in the same period of 1987.
   Revenue during the quarter fell to $3.36 billion from $3.44
billion a year earlier.
   Fourth quarter 1987 earnings were considered unusually low
because of a surge in refinancing mortgages that GMAC assumed with
the purchase of two mortgage companies in 1985, the company said.
   GMAC's 1988 profit fell 18.3 percent to $1.19 billion from $1.45
billion. Annual revenue rose to $13.5 billion from $13.4 billion in
1987.
   EDS said it earned $103.4 million, or 85 cents a share, in the
fourth quarter of last year, compared with $104.2 million, or 85
cents a share, during the same period in 1987. Revenue rose to $1.3
billion from $1.19 billion a year earlier.
   For the year, EDS had a profit of $384.1 million, or $3.15 a
share, up from $323.1 million, or $2.65 a share, during 1987. The
company said it expanded its business base in 1988 in the
commercial, international, governmental, financial and insurance
markets as well as signing a five-year agreement with GM.
   Annual revenue rose to $4.84 billion from $4.43 billion in 1987.
   GM Hughes Electronics said its fourth-quarter 1988 earnings rose
to $169.5 million, or 43 cents a share, from $145.5 million, or 36
cents a share, during the same quarter in 1987. Revenue during
fourth quarter 1988 was $3.1 billion, up from $2.7 billion a year
earlier.
   For the entire year, GM Hughes earned $653.3 million, or $2.01 a
share, up 25.3 percent from $521.1 million, or $1.67 per share, in
1987 profits. Annual revenues rose to $11.2 billion last year from
$10.5 billion in 1987.
   The earnings include the impact of a first quarter accounting
change, which boosted net income by $18.7 million.
   EDS earnings are the base for GM Class E stock and GM Hughes
profits are linked to GM's Class H stock.
   Last week, GM announced a 20 percent increase in its dividend and
a 2-for-1 split of its common stocks. Dividends rose 41 percent for
GM's Class E stock and 64 percent for GM Class H stock.
   Ford Motor Co.'s earnings are expected to be announced Thursday.
   On Feb. 2, Chrysler Corp. posted a fourth quarter profit of
$433.6 million, or $1.85 per share, and annual earnings of $1.05
billion, or $4.66 a share, down 18.6 percent from 1987.
   The Big Three automakers are expected to earn a total of about
$11 billion in 1988, breaking the companies' combined 1984 earnings
record of $9.79 billion.
</TEXT>
