<FIRST>r f AM-EnquirerBids     02-13 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Enquirer Bids,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Preliminary Bids Due Tuesday for National Enquirer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inquiring minds will have to wait until spring to
find out the winning bidder for the company that owns the gossipy
tabloid The National Enquirer.
   An official for one of the investment banking firms handling the
sale said Monday that preliminary bids for GP Group Inc. were due
Tuesday, although announcement of a winner wasn't expected until
spring.
   Prospective bidders were expected to include Robert Maxwell, the
British publishing figure who has moved aggressively into the U.S.
market in recent months, paying $2.6 billion last fall for the
publishing giant Macmillan Inc.
   Others mentioned as potential bidders are Mike Rosenbloom, a
Canadian investor who owns rivals Globe, National Examiner and Sun;
Hachette SA, the French publishing concern that also has made
serveral U.S. acquisitions in recent years; and employees of GP
Group.
   The auction is being handled by the Blackstone Group, a private
New York investment bank, and Veronis, Suhler &amp; Associates Inc., an
investment banker specializing in communications properties.
   Austin Beutner, an executive at the Blackstone Group, said there
has been ``lots of interest'' in privately-held GP Group since it
was put up for sale late last year after its owner, Generoso Pope,
died.
   ``There are many serious parties and we expect the transaction to
be announced sometime in the spring,'' he said.
   Beutner declined to identify any of those who have expressed
interest in bidding and declined to comment on what price the
company may bring.
   GP Group owns The National Enquirer and its sister publication
Weekly World News. According to the Audit Bureau of Circulation, the
Enquirer had an average weekly circulation of 4.3 million in the six
months ended June 30, 1988, while Weekly World News was just over 1
million.
</TEXT>
