<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-13 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose sharply in moderate
trading Monday, surprising analysts who said there was little news
to stir the market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled 48
cents higher at $17.59 a barrel. Last week, the contract fluctuated
before closing the week at $17.11. Other contract months also rose.
   Among refined products on the exchange, the March contract for
unleaded gasoline rose 0.58 cent to 48.15 cents a gallon, while
domestic heating oil scheduled for delivery next month closed up
0.81 cent at 48.17 cents a gallon. Other contract months also gained.
   Mary L. Haskins, assistant vice president of institutional energy
futures for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., said the rally came as a
surprise.
   ``It baffled most traders, to be honest with you,'' she said.
``In fact, the market fundamentals were mildly bearish.''
   The International Energy Agency, for example, lowered its
estimate of demand growth for 1989, Ms. Haskins said. Earlier
projections of strong demand growth had helped push the market up in
recent weeks.
   Other talk in the market focused on news that Iran, one of 13
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, plans
to increase its production capacity to 4 million barrels a day this
year, from about 3.5 million. However, Oil Minister Gholamreza
Aqazadeh said Iran would adhere to its quota even with higher
capacity.
   Greg Dreis, energy broker with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures,
attributed Monday's gains to technical factors after a week of
fluctuating prices.
   ``There were more people coming in and that made the market more
susceptible to a rally,'' he said.
</TEXT>
