<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices posted some scattered losses in a
quiet session Monday, extending last week's decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen 36.97
points on Friday, slipped another 3.57 to 2,282.50.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
602 up, 861 down and 509 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 143.52 million
shares, down from 173.56 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 172.72 million shares.
   Interest rates edged upward in the credit markets amid
expectations of action soon by the Federal Reserve to tighten credit.
   Analysts said stock traders also were in an edgy mood following
the market's decline Friday, which was the largest since Wall
Street's winter-long rally began.
   Prices tumbled Friday after the Labor Department reported that
producer prices of finished goods jumped 1 percent in January,
exceeding analysts' projections.
   Then stocks had to absorb another jolt when banks across the
country raised their prime lending rates from 10.5 percent to 11
percent.
   On Monday, however, early selling of blue chips apparently pushed
them down to levels where they attracted a few traders who had been
waiting for a pullback as a buying opportunity.
   Emery Air Freight climbed 1{ to 7| as the most active NYSE issue.
The company agreed to be acquired by Consolidated Freightways for
$7.75 a share.
   Consolidated's shares fell 1~ to 32~.
   Long Island Lighting gained 1{ to 14\. Over the weekend a federal
judge dismissed a verdict of fraud returned against the company by a
jury in December.
   Losers among the blue chips included Eastman Kodak, down ~ at
47{; General Electric, down [ at 46[, and American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, down \ at 31].
   By contrast, General Motors, which a week ago announced a
dividend increase and plans for a 2-for-1 stock split, rose 1] to
91}.
   Johnson &amp; Johnson gained { to 89. The company reported higher
fourth-quarter earnings, increased its dividend and voted a 2-for-1
stock split.
   Champion Products, traded on the American Stock Exchange, jumped
12[ to 75} on word of an agreement for Sara Lee Corp. to acquire the
company for $77 a share.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $0.48 billion, or 0.02
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.14 to 164.15.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose .13 to 337.39, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up .52 at 292.54.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 1.10 to 401.27. At the Amex, the market value index closed
at 321.76, down 1.01.
