<FIRST>u f AM-Champion-SaraLee     02-13 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Champion-Sara Lee,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Champion Products Finds Friendly Buyer for $321 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Champion Products Inc., a maker of
athletic and leisure clothing, successfully fought off a hostile
takeover and agreed Monday to be sold to Sara Lee Corp. of Chicago
for $320.9 million.
   The announcement that the food and apparel giant would buy
Champion for $77 a share followed Champion's request for bids to
fend off a takeover by a New York investment group.
   ``Our shareholders are receiving full value and this transaction
is the best possible outcome for our employees, customers and the
communities in which we operate,'' Champion President Roger Holland
said.
   Champion, well-known in college bookstores around the country for
sweatshirts and T-shirts, had been a takeover target of the
investment group Walsh, Greenwood &amp; Co.
   Acting through Phonicam Inc., a company created to attempt the
takeover, the investment group had offered $51 a share, $55 a share
and last month upped its offer to $61 a share.
   ``I think the $61 figure was getting into an area that
shareholders may have started thinking they were getting fair value,
and that's why management went looking for buyers,'' said Patricia
Ryan, an analyst for Rayomnd James &amp; Associates, a St. Petersburg,
Fla.-based borkerage firm.
   Sara Lee officials said they would begin a tender offer this week
for the 4.16 million outstanding shares of fully diluted Champion
stock and various convertible stock options.
   Champion stock climbed $12.125 to close at $75.75 in American
Stock Exchange trading Monday.
   After the deal was announced, a spokesman for Phonicam said the
company couldn't justify spending that much money for Champion.
   Ryan said she thought the sale to Sara Lee might help Champion
continue its fast-paced growth because the company might receive
more capital investment from its new parent.
   Champion has enjoyed 14 straight quarters of increased sales and
profits, and last year boosted earnings 114 percent to $14.89
million, or $4.34 a share, on sales of $219 million.
   Although the company is best known for uniforms and athletic
clothes, much of Champion's recent growth has come by adding leisure
wear and branching out into department and specialty stores.
   Sara Lee, one of the nation's 50 largest companies, sells
packaged food and various consumer products and operates a food
service business. The company reported $10.4 billion in sales in its
last fiscal year.
   ``One of our missions is to grow all of our businesses, and
strategic acquisition is one way of doing that,'' Sara Lee spokesman
Ron Culp said. ``This was just one of those good opportunities that
come along.''
   Culp said the company had not been interested in buying Champion
until it was asked to make a bid for the suburban Rochester-based
firm.
   Champion will join Sara Lee's other apparel companies, including
Hanes underwear, L'eggs hosiery, Isotoner gloves and Bali bras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
