<DOCNO> AP890213-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GM-Janesville     02-13 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM-Janesville,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Moving Some Truck Production To Wisconisn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB SCHMALFELDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said Monday it will shift
production of three light-duty trucks to a Wisconsin plant from
Michigan in 1991.
   GM spokesman Tom Klipstine also said the automaker would put
production of at least one new truck line in its Flint, Mich.,
plant, which has about 3,800 workers to compensate for the switch to
a plant in Janesville.
   GM said production of its Chevrolet Suburban and Blazer trucks
and the GMC Jimmy utility vehicles would be moved from Flint to
Janesville in 1991 for the 1992 model year.
   Gov. Tommy G. Thompson announced the move in Milwaukee.
   The Janesville plant, which employs about 5,700 people, currently
produces the Buick Skylark and the Chevrolet Cavalier compact
models. GM said those lines would be phased out to make room for the
new truck lines.
   Klipstine said decisions on employment, production speeds and the
length of retooling time for both plants is unknown. It is likely
that both plants will be shut down to refit machines to make the new
products.
   He said he did not know what Flint's new truck would be or when
it would be announced.
   ``Those are the kinds of things we won't know until we learn what
kind of product line is coming into Flint,'' he said. ``We're
talking about something that's going to happen in 1991.''
   The Flint plant now produces 32 vehicles an hour and made about
136,000 vehicles in 1988. In April, it will begin production of crew
cab and cab chassis light-duty truck models now being made in
Janesville.
</TEXT>
