<FIRST>u f AM-ToyboxintheSky 1stLd-Writethru f0112 02-13 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toybox in the Sky, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0112,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barbie and G.I. Joe: Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after the 6th, ``But quality,'' to UPDATE with
toy maker's comments on another toy failure, add Monday time element.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbie and G.I. Joe had birthday parties this
week. Mr. Game Show couldn't make it.
   ``He died,'' said Walter Kirchberger, a toy company analyst.
   Weep not, though, for Mr. Show. Of the estimated 5,000 games and
toys being introduced at the toy industry's annual coming-out party
in Manhattan this week, the vast majority will join him in that big
toybox in the sky.
   ``You'll see a lot of products at the Toy Fair this week that you
won't see next year,'' said Harold Vogel, another industry analyst.
``Most toys do not make it into a second season.''
   One reason: ``There's lots of junk.''
   But quality isn't the only criterion; some entries are undone
only by outrageous circumstance. ``The Evel Knievel doll did very
well when it came out. Then it just fell apart,'' said Vogel, of
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. He guessed that Knievel's 1977 guilty plea in a
baseball-bat assault didn't help the toy.
   Plain poor judgment kills other entries. Consider the ill-starred
Golden Girl and the Guardian of the Gemstones. ``One of the biggest
stiffs in the history of the business,'' its manufacturer, David
Galoob, said Monday.
   ``The concept was action figures for little girls,'' said Galoob,
chief of Lewis Galoob Toys Inc. ``There were 12 beautiful female
warriors with shields and swords. The trade bought in very, very
heavily.
   ``And what we discovered was that little girls didn't want to
play with warrior figurines.''
   Other casualties of the toy wars are harder to explain. Barbie
turns 30 years old this week, dancing on the grave of a pretender
named Gem. While G.I. Joe marches on at 25, the Inhumanoids _ a
toady group from the center of the Earth _ withered in the light of
day.
   Why?
   Nobody knows.
   ``That is the $64 million question in the toy industry. And in
most other industries,'' said Kirchberger, of Paine Webber Group
Inc. ``Nobody sets out to make a bad movie. It just happens. It's
the same thing with toys.''
   Manufacturers are willing to enter the fray in hopes of capturing
a chunk of the $12.8 billion annual toy business. They trim losses
by making models of most new toys, holding back on full-scale
production until orders come in.
   Still, there have been some epic bombs. View-Master Ideal Group
Inc. is still scratching its head over Michael Jackson's Zoo, a
menagerie of stuffed animals inspired by the rock star's
predilection for offbeat pets.
   ``He even went on tour with his chimp. So we tried,'' said
View-Master's Jeremy Jacobs. ``We had the chimp appearing in stores
in Southern California. We had quite a few good promotions, but we
just couldn't move the product.''
   Then there was Mr. Game Show, a big hit at last year's Toy Fair,
a goner now. Kirchberger gave the eulogy:
   ``It was modeled after a TV game show; there was a figure of a
host, he spoke, he'd ask you questions, you'd push buttons to
indicate your answer, he'd tell you if you were right or wrong and
how much you won.
   ``Very clever. Wrong price point, wrong I-don't-know-what. Mr.
Game Show didn't make it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890213-0261 </DOCNO>
