<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-13 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Lower; Gold Declines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against most major
currencies Monday in thin trading as players awaited the next round
of U.S. economic reports.
   Gold prices also declined. Republic National Bank of New York
said gold bullion was bid at $385.20 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST,
down from $387 late Friday.
   The dollar advanced in the Far East and continued rising later in
European trading, buoyed by expectations of higher U.S. interest
rates. The dollar later retreated in New York.
   Dealers said last Friday's report of a greater-than-expected 1
percent rise in U.S. wholesale prices in January had rekindled
speculation that the Federal Reserve would hike its discount rate
soon in an effort to help curb inflation by slowing the economy. But
the absence of a rate boost took away the market's excuse to drive
the dollar still higher, traders said.
   The discount rate is the interest the Fed charges on loans to
financial institutions.
   ``We didn't see a lot of business moving through today,'' said
Robert Hatcher, vice president of corporate currency trading at the
New York office of Barclays Bank PLC of Britain. ``It's a case of a
market that's waiting for additional economic data before it moves.''
   Market participants are awaiting the publication of Tuesday's
report on retail sales for January, Wednesday's report on business
inventories and factory use for December, Thursday's report on
January housing starts and Friday's report on the December
merchandise trade deficit.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.65 Japanese yen to a closing 128.30 yen. Later in
London, the dollar was quoted at 128.60 yen and by the end of
trading in New York the dollar was quoted at 128.07 yen, down from
128.68 yen late Friday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7495 from $1.7547 on
Friday. Later in New York, sterling advanced to $1.7525 from $1.7467
late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8677 West German marks, down from 1.8695; 1.5877
Swiss francs, down from 1.5885; 6.3575 French francs, down from
6.3588; 1,359.00 Italian lire, down from 1,363.50; and 1.1860
Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8705 West German marks, up from 1.8595; 1.5895
Swiss francs, up from 1.5778; 6.3650 French francs, up from 6.3200;
2.1120 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0960; 1,362.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,353.75; and 1.1868 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1857.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $384.25 a troy ounce from
$391 bid late Friday. In Zurich, the late bid for gold was $383.75,
down from $389.50 bid late Friday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $6.80 an ounce to close at a bid
of $387.05.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
declined to $386.20 a troy ounce from $388.80 late Friday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid of $5.79 a troy ounce, down
from Friday's late bid of $5.85. On New York's Comex, silver for
current delivery rose to $5.826 a troy ounce from $5.812 late Friday.
</TEXT>
