<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 1917EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe-Merc     02-13 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe-Merc,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Merc Blasts Media Coverage Of Futures Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange charged Monday
that journalists covering a federal trading-fraud investigation had
``trampled upon and smeared the integrity'' of the world's two
largest futures exchanges.
   The Merc's Board of Governors said in a statement that the
disclosure of the probe on Jan. 19 had sparked a ``media frenzy''
that had inflicted possibly irreversible damage on the futures
industry.
   ``The unbridled race by some in the media to print and broadcast
the most sensational and outlandish scrap of information has
resulted in a denigration of all traders, regardless of guilt or
innocence,'' the exchange said.
   ``Most importantly, it has viciously trampled upon and smeared
the integrity of two Chicago institutions...their officials and
their members in a manner that is unconscionable,'' the exchange
said.
   The statement was signed by Merc Chairman John Geldermann and
Merc Executive Committee Chairman Leo Melamed.
   The Merc said neither it nor the rival Chicago Board of Trade
were targets of the investigation.
   The probe is believed to be focused on allegations that as many
as 100 traders and brokers at the two exchanges systematically
cheated customers out of millions of dollars in profits on contracts
for future deliveries of commodities ranging from soybeans to
Treasury bonds.
   Federal authorities in Chicago have refused to comment on the
investigation. No indictments have yet been issued.
   The Merc said it would hold meetings this week to update members
on its comprehensive review of the exchange's trading rules and
practices. The review, launched in reaction to news of the
investigation, is not slated for completion until at least late
March.
</TEXT>
