<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-SemiconductorShipments     02-13 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Semiconductor Shipments,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Indicates Semiconductor Demand Increasing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Market figures for January indicate
semiconductor demand is increasing for the first time in four months
and that the contracting market may be slightly reversing itself,
analysts said Monday.
   An increase in U.S. semiconductor orders caused a rise in the
closely watched ``book-to-bill'' ratio for January, which reached
1.0, according to figures released by the Semiconductor Industry
Association. The figure was .93 in December.
   A book-to-bill ratio of 1.0 means that for every $100 worth of
products billed, manufacturers received $100 worth of new orders, or
bookings.
   The total shipments, or billings, of $1.004 million in January
were 10.9 percent higher than the same figure a year ago and 17.1
percent lower than in December.
   The January 1989 orders, or bookings, of $1.124 million were 5.8
percent higher than the average bookings posted last year and 5.4
percent higher than December's figure.
   ``It means the industry is coming back toward a growth
environment after four months with less than a one-to-one (ratio),
indicating a shrinking of the market and people buying less from
September to now,'' said Mel Phelps, of the Hambrecht &amp; Quist
investment company.
   ``This indicates for the first time they are beginning to order
as much as is being produced,'' he said.
</TEXT>
