<FIRST>r f AM-RJR-Horrigan     02-13 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RJR-Horrigan,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Horrigan Resigns As Board Chairman Of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ E.A. Horrigan Jr., chairman of the
board of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. since 1980 and an unsuccessful
player in the bid to buy out RJR Nabisco Inc., said Monday he will
resign from the company effective March 1.
   Horrigan said he will continue to assist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
&amp; Co., the new owners of RJR Nabisco, the tobacco company's parent
company, during the transition period until his successor is named.
   ``KKR has made it very clear that they recognize the strength of
our tobacco operations and their position as the core of RJR
Nabisco's business, and that their intention is to be a partner in
moving R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. ahead,'' he said.
   In October 1988, Horrigan and RJR Nabisco President F. Ross
Johnson announced that executives of the food and tobacco giant were
considering taking the company private in a leveraged buyout worth
almost $17 billion.
   Kohlberg won the bidding war on Nov. 30 with a bid valued at $109
a share, or $25.1 billion. Johnson resigned as president and chief
executive officer last week when Kohlberg took control.
   Horrigan joined R.J. Reynolds in July 1978 as chairman and chief
executive officer of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco International Inc. He was
elected to the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. board of directors in April
1979. He became chairman, president and chief executive officer of
the company in February 1980.
   Horrigan was elected to the board of directors of R.J. Reynolds
Industries, now RJR Nabisco, in December 1980, and was named
executive vice president of the parent company in September 1981. He
was elected president and chief operating officer of R.J. Reynolds
Industries in 1984 and became vice chairman of its board in 1985.
</TEXT>
