<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Affiliated     02-13 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Affiliated,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Affiliated Publications Reports $29 Million Quarterly Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Affiliated Publications Inc. said Monday it lost
$29.5 million in the fourth quarter of 1988 and $80.8 million for
the year, largely due to its share of a telecommunications firm's
losses.
   Affiliated, parent company of The Boston Globe, said it owns more
than 61 million shares of McCaw Cellular Communications of Kirkland,
Wash. Affiliated's share of McCaw's fourth-quarter loss totaled
$43.7, eliminating the $14.2 million in profit the company earned
from its other operations.
   For the fourth quarter, losses were $29.5 on revenue of $137
million, compared with a loss of $3.6 million on revenue of $135.6
million for the same period last year.
   Losses for all of 1988 totaled $80.9 million on revenue of $534.2
million, compared with earnings of $201.2 million, or $2.87 a share,
on revenue of $490.1 million in 1987.
   On Jan. 19, Affiliated and McCaw announced a restructuring under
which Affiliated will distribute its Globe Newspaper Co. and
Billboard Publications Inc. subsidiaries to its shareholders in a
tax-free spinoff.
   Immediately after the spinoff, Affiliated will merge with McCaw.
The restructuring is pending approval of shareholders and federal
regulators.
   Affiliated also is the parent company of Globe Pequot Press, a
book publisher.
   McCaw is one of the largest cellular telephone systems operators
in the United States and one of the nation's top paging operators.
</TEXT>
