<FIRST>r f BC-Bradfield-FederalReserve     02-13 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bradfield-Federal Reserve,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Counsel For Federal Reserve Leaving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general counsel of the Federal Reserve
System's board of governors will leave the agency to join the law
firm of Jones, Day, Reavis &amp; Pogue on March 1, the Cleveland firm
announced Monday.
   Michael Bradfield, who worked under former Federal Reserve
Chairman Paul Volcker and current Chairman Alan Greenspan, will be a
partner in the Cleveland-based firm's financial institutions section
in Washington, said Richard W. Pogue, Jones, Day managing partner.
   ``During his last eight years at the Federal Reserve, Mike
Bradfield participated in some of the most significant developments
in the history of the financial institutions industry in the U.S.
and gained experience and insights that we believe will be
invaluable to our clients,'' Pogue said in a news release.
   Bradfield received a law degree and a master's degree in
international affairs in 1960 from Columbia University. He joined
the Treasury Department after two years in private practice and
remained there until 1975.
   For the next six years, Bradfield worked for a Washington law
firm. He joined the Federal Reserve in 1981.
