<FIRST>r f AM-Carl's-Insider     02-13 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carl's-Insider,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Relatives of Hamburger Chain Founder Settle Insider Trading Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal insider-trading case against six
relatives of the founder of the Carl's Jr. hamburger chain was
settled Monday when the defendants agreed to pay fines and
restitution totaling $187,560.
   Chief among those settling Monday was Donald F. Karcher, brother
of chain founder Carl N. Karcher and president of Carl Karcher
Enterprises Inc., which runs 460 Carl's Jr. restaurants in the West.
   Neither he nor any of the other defendants admitted guilt in
settling the Securities and Exchange Commission case in U.S.
District Court. All were ordered to refrain from future securities
violations, according to an SEC announcement on the settlement.
   An assistant to Donald Karcher said Karcher had no immediate
comment on the settlement.
   The government's civil complaint alleged that Carl N. and Donald
Karcher and their wives tipped relatives and in-laws to an expected
dip in the company's stock price in 1984, and that the relatives
sold stock to avoid losses totaling $310,000.
   It is against securities law to take advantage of information
unavailable to the general investing public when trading stock.
   Carl N. Karcher, chairman of the Anaheim-based company and its
spokesman in homey commercials touting traditional American values,
remains a defendant in the case. So do his wife, six other relatives
and an employee.
</TEXT>
