<DOCNO> AP890213-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 2323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Malaysia-Coal     02-13 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Malaysia-Coal,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Coal Fields Worth $2.56 Billion Found In Malaysia, Says Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German team has found two
coal deposits containing about 93 million tons of coal worth an
estimated $2.56 billion, it was reported Tuesday.
   The two deposits were found in the Tebulan and Merit South areas
of Sarawak state, The New Straits Times reported, quoting S.P. Chen,
Sarawak's Geological Survey Department director. The coal is of the
sub-bituminous type suitable for industrial use as fuel.
   The new areas are adjacent to the existing Merit Pila coal field,
180 miles northeast of Kuching, which was discovered last April and
has about 63.7 million tons of coal worth more than $1.72 billion,
Chen said.
   Chen said the discovery was part of a $1.1 million-dollar survey
being conducted by seven West German geologists since 1983. The
seven are in Sarawak as part of a German technical aid program that
ends in 1990.
   Chen said there were about 78 million tons of coal in the Tebulan
area and 15 million tons in Merit South.
   Commercial mining at the Merit Pila coal field began last June by
the United States-based Global Mineral Exploration Corp. and a
Malaysian-South Korean joint venture, Lucky Hill Ltd, Chen said.
   Global was expected to produce 350,000 tons annually and Lucky
Hill 120,000 tons. So far, Global has produced 29,500 tons and Lucky
Hill 20,500 tons. The coal is being exported to Taiwan and Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
